{in this game, Black was slow with g7-g6 ...but white failed to realize that he must act fast ...and ended worse with slow moves like Re1 and Nbd2-Nf1 !!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 {This is a good consolidating move. Black is protecting the e5-pawn and is ready to finish the development} 6. c3 (6. O-O {Is simply a mistake because Black can exchange the light-squared bishop after:} b5 7. Bb3 Na5 8. d4 {The try to open the position comes too late, now Black can simply reply with:} exd4 $1 {with an advantage}) 6... b5 $6 7. Bb3 $6 (7. Bc2) 7... Na5 8. Bc2 c5 9. O-O g6 $6 {In general, Black's dark-squared bishop is very well placed on g7, but the problem is that this move is a bit slow and creates a temporary disharmony in Black position. White should act dynamically by trying to open the position immediately. There are three possible pawn breaks that need to be investigated} 10. Re1 $6 {White started losing time and now Black has time to consolidate} (10. b4 $5 cxb4 11. cxb4 Nc6 12. d4 {with an initiative}) (10. a4 b4 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. d4) (10. d4) 10... Bg7 11. Nbd2 (11. d4 {is well met by} exd4 $3 {opening the dark-squared bishop} 12. cxd4 (12. e5 {is logical, but doesn't give anything to White after:} dxe5 13. Rxe5+ Be6 14. cxd4 c4 $15) 12... O-O) (11. a4 b4) 11... O-O 12. Nf1 h6 $1 {very good move. Black needs to stop Bg5's move. White is fighting for the d5-square, and the exchange of the dark-squared bishop for the f6-knight is favorable for White} ({If} 12... Re8 $1 13. Bg5 (13. Ng3) 13... Bb7 14. Ne3 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qd2 Bg7 17. b4 cxb4 18. cxb4 Nc6 19. Bb3 {White has small but long-lasting advantage}) 13. Ng3 (13. Ne3 Bb7) 13... Re8 14. h3 Bb7 {Black already wants to open the position with d5. The rule in such positions is that the side which manages to execute the central break,d5 for Black or d4 for White, in good circumstances, has the initiative} 15. Nh2 $6 (15. Be3 Rc8 $132 (15... c4 $1 {is another good option} 16. d4 (16. b4 $2 cxd3 17. Bxd3 Nc4 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Nd2 d5 $17) 16... exd4 17. Bxd4 Nc6 18. Be3 d5 $11 19. Bf4 dxe4)) (15. d4 $2 {is not very good due to the famous "double capture" which opens Black's bishops and Black is ready to play d6-d5 at any momment} cxd4 16. cxd4 exd4 $17) 15... d5 $1 $17 16. Qf3 (16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Bd2 Nf4 $17) 16... c4 $5 (16... Rc8 $3 {White is in some kind of zugzwang !!!} 17. Be3 (17. Bd2 dxe4) (17. a4 b4 $17) 17... d4 {Winning more space with a tempo} 18. Bd2 c4 $17) 17. dxc4 Nxc4 $17 {The knight is joining the fight, and it is obvious that Black has the upper hand.} 18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. hxg4 dxe4 20. Nxe4 Nd6 21. Be3 f5 22. gxf5 gxf5 23. Bb3+ Kh7 24. Ng5+ hxg5 25. Qh3+ Kg6 26. Rad1 Qf6 27. Bc2 Rh8 28. Qg3 Rad8 29. Bb6 Rde8 30. Qg4 Be4 31. Bxe4 Nxe4 32. Qf3 Qxb6 33. Rxe4 fxe4 34. Qxe4+ Kh6 35. Rd3 Bf6 36. Rh3+ Kg7 37. Rg3 Rd8 0-1

