{A GREAT GAME BY BLACK - demonstrating the typical double capture....from a different opening!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Re1 g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. Bc2 O-O 9. d3 $6 (9. d4 {is logical and necessary} e5 10. d5 {This structure is good for Black now, because his bishop is not on b7 and this d4-d5 is not coming with a tempo.}) 9... b5 (9... e5 {is also logical}) 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Nf1 {White has played the opening very passively, and now Black has a small but clear advantage!} e5 $3 12. Ng3 Re8 {We get a "Breyer" type of position, but with a few extra tempis for Black. In such cases with the knight on d7 (not on a5), there is no need to spend time for h6 because we are not afraid of Bg5} 13. h3 Rc8 (13... d5 {was good enough}) 14. d4 $2 {typical mistake} (14. Be3 d5) (14. Bg5 Qc7 (14... h6 $1 15. Bd2 d5) 15. Qd2 $1) 14... cxd4 {Black already fully completed the development and is ready to meet the d4-break with the double capture which will open the lines and diagonals for his rooks and bishops} 15. cxd4 exd4 16. Nxd4 d5 $1 $17 {This move is always open when it is not allowing e4-e5. Opening the position completely favors Black because some of White's pieces are still not developed} 17. exd5 Rxe1+ {This exchange favors Black when White can't answer it with Rxe1} 18. Qxe1 Nxd5 19. Nge2 Qb6 0-1

