{} 1... e5 {Let's discuss this position which is very important for understanding the structure. White has three options: 1. To do nothing with a move like h3 2. To play dxe5 3. To push d5} 2. d5 {This is not dangerous because it is not coming with tempo and Black is still not committed to Bb7} (2. dxe5 {This exchange makes sense, but you should remember that Black is always taking with the knight here, especially with the bishop on g7. If our knight was on c6, the same rule applies} Nxe5) (2. h3 $2 {This move is a mistake because it allows us a double capture} exd4 3. cxd4 cxd4 {This structure is always favorable for us, especially with the bishop on g7}) 2... b5 {The correct setup here is to play on the queenside. One can argue that f7-f5 is a possible break, and we can prepare for it. Yes, that is true; f7-f5 is part of our plan, but not now. We leave this option for the endgame. This is a very important position to discuss. I will show you how to react to the quick a2-a4 break and to the slow play with Nd2-f1 keeping the pawn on a2 for a while} 3. a4 {can be met in two ways - Nb6 or Rb8} (3. Nbd2 c4 $5 {now this move is not so good because White can strike with b3. The rule is that c5-c4 is very strong when the a-pawn is not on a2.} 4. b3 $1 ({If} 4. Nf1 Qc7 $1 {Black is preventing b2-b3 break} (4... Nc5 $2 5. b3 $1 cxb3 6. axb3 Bd7 7. b4 Na4 (7... Nb7 $4 $16 {Our knight is horrible here, this retreat can be acceptable only if the position is very close} 8. Bd3 Qc7 (8... a5 9. Bd2 $1 (9. bxa5 $2 {This is a horrible move}) 9... a4 10. Qe2 Qb6 11. Be3 Qa6 12. c4 $16 bxc4 $2 13. Bxc4 $18) 9. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Rf1e3,Rc3c4]}) 8. Bxa4 bxa4 9. c4 $1 Qc7 10. Qd3 Rfc8 11. Ne3 Rab8 12. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Rc4c5] White is ready to push c4-c5 in an appropriate momment}) 5. Bd2 (5. a4 {Is possible, but not helping White at all} Rb8 {remember not to play the move Bb7} 6. Ng3 Nc5 7. h3 Bd7 8. axb5 (8. a5 {is dropping a pawn after:} Nb7 {[%cal Rb7a5]}) 8... axb5 (8... Bxb5 $5 {Is also possible}) 9. Be3 {[%cal Rb8a8]}) 5... Nc5 6. b3 cxb3 7. axb3 Bd7 8. b4 Na4 9. Bxa4 bxa4 $15 {and Black is actually better because White is not in time to play c4} 10. Qc2 a5 $1 {other moves are possible too, but this is a very typical way to stop c3-c4} (10... h6 $2 11. c4 $16)) 4... cxb3 5. axb3 Qc7 {Now there is no reliable way to protect the c3-pawn.} 6. Bb2 {the bishop abandoned the c1-h6 diagonal, giving Black another resource like:} Bh6) 3... Rb8 (3... Bb7 $2 {is a mistake, the bishop belongs to the c8-h3 diagonal}) (3... Nb6 {is playable, but not the best}) 4. Nbd2 c4 $1 {This move is always good if Black's pawn is not on a2} 5. axb5 axb5 6. Nf1 Nc5 7. Ng3 Bd7 {Black's position is very good, and he is ready to take over the initiative on the queenside} 8. Ra3 {Doubling on the a-file doesn't bring an advantage to White} Qc7 9. Be3 Rfc8 10. Qe2 Qd8 {[%cal Rb8a8]} *

