{This is a model game for Black for the double capture structure} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 (5. O-O d6 6. c3 g6) 5... d6 6. c3 g6 {makes sense, because White wasted some time} (6... Bd7) (6... Bg4 $6) (6... Be6 $2) 7. d4 exd4 $3 {this move is amazingly strong and shocked me a lot when I study the game for the first time.} (7... Bd7 $1 {This is also good. We have a good version of the differed Steinitz-Smyslov variation, but exd4 is more active and better!} 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 b5 10. Bc2 O-O) 8. cxd4 (8. Nxd4 {With the pawn on c3 this move doesn't make sense. White can't develop his other knight on c3 and this setup doesn't make sense.} Bd7 $132 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $1 (9... Bxc6 $1)) 8... b5 9. Bb3 Bg7 10. h3 $6 {white must act fast!!} ({White should do something very fast} 10. O-O $1 O-O $132) 10... O-O (10... Nxe4 $2 11. Bd5) 11. O-O Na5 $5 12. Bc2 c5 $5 13. Nc3 $6 {This move is a mistake because it allows Black to apply the double capture. In chess ,literature you can also find this structure as "e4" vs. "d6" in Ruy Lopez. As we already know, the dynamic potential of Black's position almost always compensates for the slight structural disadvantage.} (13. d5 Nc4 $1 {with a very good verson of Modern Benoni !!} (13... Re8 $5 {Black shouldn't delay Nc4, because now the a5-knight is our of play.} 14. Nbd2 $1) 14. Re1 (14. Nc3 b4 $17) (14. a4 $1 Nb6 $11) 14... Nd7 $17) (13. dxc5 {This leads to another very pleasant structure for Black. This pawn majority on the queenside, supported by the g7 bishop promising him an advantage in the following endgame} dxc5 14. Nc3 Bb7 $15) 13... cxd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Bb7 $1 15. a3 $6 Re8 $1 $17 16. Re1 Rc8 $1 {All Black pieces are ready for the fight.} 17. Nf3 (17. Nce2 d5 (17... Bxe4 $19) (17... Nxe4 $19) 18. exd5 Qxd5 (18... Nxd5 $5) 19. Nf3 Qxd1 20. Bxd1 Nd7 $19) (17. Rb1 d5 18. e5 Ne4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Rxe4 Rxe5 22. Rxe5 Bxe5 23. Be3 Nc4 24. b3 Nxe3 25. fxe3 Qf6 $17) (17. Bf4 Nc4 $19) 17... Nc4 $1 (17... d5 $1 18. e5 Nd7 19. Bf4 Nc4 $17 20. Nxd5 Ndxe5) 18. Nd2 Nb6 $1 19. Nf1 d5 $1 20. e5 Ne4 $1 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Qxd8 Rcxd8 23. Bg5 Rc8 24. Ng3 (24. Nxe4 Bxe4 25. Rxe4 Rxe5 26. Rxe5 Bxe5 27. Rb1 Nc4 28. b3 Nxa3 $19) 24... Rxe5 25. Ncxe4 Bxe4 26. Bf4 Re6 27. Rxe4 Rxe4 28. Nxe4 Bxb2 29. Re1 Bxa3 $3 30. Nf6+ Kh8 31. Ra1 (31. Be5 Nc4 32. Ba1 (32. Bd4 Bb2) 32... Bb2 $19) 31... Nc4 {A MODEL GAME BY BLACK !!} 0-1

