{a wonderful example of the c5-c4 advance .....which is even stronger now that the white pawn is on a3 (or on a4)} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a3 $2 {White is losing time and weakens the b3-square. This move only makes sense in the d3-Nc3 line} d6 9. c3 Bg4 $5 {I don't like this move when the d-pawn is not on d4.} (9... Na5 $1 {Looks logical too} 10. Ba2 c5) 10. d3 Na5 11. Bc2 $6 (11. Ba2 {At least White can try to keep the bishop on the long diagonal, but probably Yifan doesn't want to exchange the bishops after Be6}) 11... c5 12. h3 Bd7 $1 (12... Bh5 $2 {When White's pawn is on d3, this move is a mistake. White can continue now with Nd2-f1-g3 maneuver, forcing Black to exchange on f3 or to keep the bishop passive on g6.}) 13. d4 (13. b4 {Is not challenging, because Black can simply retreat} Nc6 $11) 13... Qc7 $1 14. d5 $6 (14. Nbd2 cxd4 (14... Rac8 {is another possible way to continue} 15. d5 {with plans similar as in the game.} c4 $1 {Black has decent chances with the maneuver Na5-b7-c5 followed by a5-b4 break}) 15. cxd4 Rac8 (15... exd4 {Black is not ready to enter this structure now. Both bishops are misplaced (not on "g7" and "b7" and rooks are not on "e8" and "c8". He needs to win at least one tempo} 16. Nxd4) 16. Bd3 Rfe8 (16... Bd8 $5) (16... exd4 $1 {When White loses time for Bd3 then this move is good} 17. Nxd4 Rfe8 18. N2f3 Qb7 $11) 17. d5 Nb7 $2 {Try never to play this move when the position is open. Now the position is strategically lost after:} (17... Bd8 $5 18. Nf1 Qa7 19. Ng3 (19. b3 Rc3) 19... Bb6 20. Re2 (20. Qe2 Nb3) 20... h6 21. Bd2 Nc4 22. Be1 Rc7 23. b3 Na5 24. Rb1 $16 Nb7 25. b4 $16) 18. b4 $16 Qc3 19. Nb3) 14... c4 $1 $15 {now that the White pawn is on a3, the c5-c4 advance gains in strength because White has weakened a complex of squares on the queenside!} 15. Nbd2 Nb7 16. Nf1 Nc5 17. g4 {Remember: after g2-g4 there are two typical reactions ...h5! and g6!} h5 $3 $17 (17... g6 $1 {Sometimes the h5-break simply doesn't work or the positions are too complicated, so I am presenting you the second possible plan, which also works very well after "g2-g4"} 18. Bh6 Rfb8 {Leaving the e8-square available for the knight is important.} (18... Rfe8 19. Ng3 a5 $2 20. g5 $18) 19. Ng3 a5 20. Kh1 (20. Kh2 Bxg4) 20... Bf8 21. Qd2 Bxh6 (21... Qd8) 22. Qxh6 Qd8 $36 23. Nf5 $2 {This move is almost always met by Bxf5} Bxf5) 18. N3h2 (18. gxh5 g6 $3 $17 {amazing concept. Black sacrifices material but opens files and diagonals for his pieces. White's pieces are stuck on the queenside when Black can easily transfer his forces into the attack.} (18... Bxh3 $17 {this simple move also gives Black an advantage}) 19. hxg6 fxg6 20. Bh6 Bxh3 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. N1h2 (22. Ng3 Bg4 $17 23. a4 Nh5 $19) 22... Ng4 23. Qd2 Qd8 $19) 18... hxg4 19. hxg4 Qc8 20. f3 Nh7 $15 {Now the dark squares on the kingside are quite weak and Black is planning to penetrate through them.} 21. Ng3 Bg5 (21... g6 {I will show you another illustrative line to see that we can even sacrifice an exchange} 22. Bh6 Bg5 23. Bxf8 Qxf8 24. Nhf1 Bf4 $44) 22. Nf5 Qd8 23. Kg2 g6 24. Ng3 Kg7 25. Rh1 Rh8 26. Nhf1 Qf6 27. Be3 Bxe3 28. Nxe3 Ng5 29. Qe2 Rag8 30. Raf1 Qf4 31. Rxh8 Rxh8 32. Rh1 Rxh1 33. Nxh1 Nd3 $1 34. Bxd3 (34. b4 Nxf3 35. Bxd3 Nh4+ 36. Kg1 cxd3 $19) 34... cxd3 35. Qf2 d2 36. Ng3 Nxf3 $3 (36... Qxe3 37. Qxe3 d1=Q 38. Qxg5) 37. Qxf3 Bxg4 $3 38. Qf2 d1=Q 39. Nxd1 Bxd1 40. Qe1 Bf3+ 41. Kg1 f5 42. exf5 gxf5 43. Qf2 Kg6 44. b3 e4 45. c4 bxc4 46. bxc4 Qg5 47. c5 f4 48. cxd6 fxg3 {An amazing game by Kosteniuk!!} 0-1

