{[%evp 0,126,38,38,43,14,25,-2,9,3,6,9,16,-18,0,-3,13,-28,-9,-24,33,12,-13,-33,-8,14,21,17,17,28,31,34,38,33,18,8,26,28,6,10,19,5,14,11,21,7,23,16,17,16,4,-1,25,-4,-7,-9,-4,-27,8,-10,6,0,4,11,0,-12,-5,-1,0,-29,8,-10,-14,-45,-44,-44,-32,-22,-50,-50,-29,-50,5,0,0,0,0,-16,0,-38,-35,-38,-34,-41,-38,-49,-70,-77,-37,-59,-57,-91,-56,-56,-30,-60,-85,-80,-100,-128,-171,-195,-172,-174,-184,-207,-197,-201,-201,-195,-211,-253,-206,-166,-359,-340,-347,-410,-351] again the typical c5-c4 advance by black (played at a good moment!)} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O (8... Bg4 $2 {I already mentioned that this move is a mistake with the pawn still on d2. White continues with h3, d3, followed by Nd2-f1-g3} 9. h3 (9. d3 O-O 10. h3 $16) 9... Bh5 10. d3 $16) 9. h3 (9. d4 Bg4 $1) 9... Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. a4 c5 16. d5 {Both sides have advantages and disadvantages. White managed to play d4-d5 and closed the b7-bishop. On the other hand, with the pawn already on a4, Black can play c5-c4, freeing the c5-square for the knight and gaining access to the b3-square.} c4 $1 {Black's plan is very clear now: to relocate the Bb7 and put it on d7!} (16... Qc7 $2 {This is a typical mistake because White can play} 17. b3 $3 {with the idea to meet c4 with b4} c4 (17... b4 18. c4 $16 {and start organizing a kingside attack, by means of f2-f4 or g2-g4}) 18. b4 $16) 17. Bg5 Nc5 18. axb5 (18. Kh1 Be7 $1 {Now this is the better square than "g7"} 19. Kg1 Nfd7 {Black wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops} 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Kh1 Nb6 {the typical idea is to provoke axb5 or a5} 22. a5 Nbd7 {Black waste some time, but now there is no tension on the queenside} 23. Kg1 Bc8 24. Qd2 Nf6 25. Qg5 Kg7 26. Rf1 h6 27. Qd2 Qc7 28. Ra3 Nb7 29. Rfa1 Bd7 $15) 18... axb5 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Qd2 Be7 $1 {Black is unpinning the knight and later can be transferred to the a7-g1 diagonal} 21. Ra1 Bb7 22. Bh6 Nfd7 23. h4 (23. Nh2 Nb6 24. Ng4 Bc8 25. Be3 Bxg4 {with the pawns already on b5 and c4, it is good for Black to exchange his light-squared bishop for the opponent knight.} 26. hxg4 Qc7 27. f3 Ra8 28. Rxa8+ Nxa8 29. Ne2 Bd8 30. Qc1 Qa7 31. Kf1 Bb6 $15) 23... Nb6 24. Bg5 Nba4 25. Rb1 Bc8 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Qh6 Qf8 28. Qg5 (28. Qxf8+ $4 Kxf8 $17 {Black has a clear advantage in this endgame...and at some moment he will also play f5!!}) 28... f6 29. Qe3 h5 30. Nd2 Bd7 31. Bxa4 Nxa4 32. b3 cxb3 33. Rxb3 Rc8 34. Ne2 Qd8 35. f3 Kg7 36. Rb4 Qa5 37. Rb3 Nc5 38. Rb1 Qa2 39. Rf1 Qc2 40. Rc1 Qd3 41. Qxd3 Nxd3 42. Ra1 Kf7 43. Nb3 Rc4 44. Rd1 Nb2 45. Rb1 Na4 46. Rc1 Nc5 47. Nxc5 dxc5 48. Kf2 Ra4 49. Rc2 f5 50. Ke3 Kf6 51. Rb2 Ra1 52. g3 fxe4 53. Kxe4 Ra3 54. Kd3 Ke7 55. f4 exf4 56. Nxf4 b4 57. Ne2 Bb5+ 58. Ke4 Bxe2 59. Rxe2 Rxc3 60. Ke5 Rd3 61. Rc2 Re3+ 62. Kf4 Rc3 63. Ra2 b3 0-1

