{[%evp 0,110,38,38,38,17,17,29,26,0,3,12,28,-1,3,21,10,-19,-15,-9,25,-8,8,-31,13,-23,-7,-18,-11,-24,-11,-25,-64,-52,-12,-20,-21,-13,-6,-24,-12,-35,-24,-30,24,-50,25,30,44,31,38,36,36,43,32,29,36,15,25,-11,0,0,53,-23,-25,-18,0,-44,-45,-75,-23,-231,-228,-228,-186,-250,-250,-319,-498,-498,-267,-269,-218,-313,-263,-277,-175,-251,-174,-174,-174,-174,-366,-501,-111,-111,-111,-122,-99,-84,-35,-72,66,-36,6,-285,-151,-593,-608,-611,-618,-615,-625] The dxe5 strategy by White is usually bad and this game is a good example of how Black should handle the position.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 c5 12. dxe5 $6 {this is simply a bad move !} dxe5 {When Black already took space on the queenside by b5, then dxe5 is also good. The usual reply is Nxe5.} 13. Nf1 c4 14. Bc2 Qc7 $1 $15 {there is no d4 pawn ..so the c5 square can be used by the black pieces!} (14... Bb7 $6 {the bishop is usually going to e6 in this structure.}) 15. Ng3 Nc5 16. Qe2 Re8 (16... Rd8) (16... Be6 $1 17. Ng5 Rfd8 (17... Bd7 {is playable, but the text move is very instructive}) 18. Nxe6 fxe6 $40) 17. b4 cxb3 18. axb3 Be6 19. Rb1 (19. b4 Nb3 $15) 19... h6 $1 20. Nd2 Bf8 21. Ndf1 Ncd7 22. Bb2 Rac8 23. Ne3 g6 $1 24. Red1 Nb6 25. Ra1 Ra8 $15 26. Qf3 Bg7 27. Rd2 h5 28. Rad1 Rad8 29. Nd5 Bxd5 30. exd5 Nc8 $3 31. Ne4 Nxe4 32. Bxe4 Nd6 $1 (32... f5 $6 33. d6 (33. Bb1) (33. Bxf5) 33... Nxd6 34. Bd5+ Kh7 35. Ba3 e4 36. Qg3 Bxc3 37. Bxd6 Rxd6 38. Bg8+ Rxg8 39. Rxd6) 33. Bb1 e4 34. Qe2 e3 35. Rd3 (35. fxe3 Bh6 36. Rd3 Qb6) 35... exf2+ 36. Qxf2 Ne4 37. Qe3 b4 38. Kh1 bxc3 39. d6 Qd7 40. Ba3 h4 41. Qf3 Ng3+ 42. Kg1 Qa7+ 43. Qf2 Qd7 44. Re3 Rxe3 45. Qxe3 Re8 46. Qc5 Rc8 47. Qf2 Rd8 48. Bd3 Bf8 49. Bc4 Ne4 50. Qd4 Nxd6 51. Qxc3 Qa7+ 52. Qd4 Nb5 53. Qxa7 Rxd1+ 54. Kf2 Nxa7 55. Bxf8 Kxf8 0-1

