{ALLOWING White's Nf5 !!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Be7 (6... Bc5) 7. O-O d6 8. c3 O-O 9. Re1 Nb8 $6 {Black is a tempo down compared to a normal Breyer with d3 because White didn't spend time for the move h3} ({Black should continue in a "Chigorin" style} 9... Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Nf1 (12. b4 Nc6 $11) 12... h6 (12... Bf8 $6 {Is a typical mistake. Black should start with h6} 13. Bg5 $1 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Ne3 $14) 13. Ng3 (13. Ne3 Bf8 14. b4 cxb4 15. cxb4 Nc6 $15) 13... Bf8 $11) 10. Nbd2 (10. h3 {There is no need to play h3, because as we know with the pawn still on "d3", the pin Bg4 is not dangerous} Bb7 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 12. Nf1 Nc5 (12... c5 $6 13. Ng3) 13. Bc2 Re8 14. Ng3 Bf8 $132 {we transposes to Breyer line with d3} 15. b4 (15. d4 $2 exd4 16. cxd4 Ncxe4 $15) 15... Ncd7 16. a4 c5 $11) 10... Nbd7 (10... Bg4 $2 {the random ..yet so typical mistake!!} 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nf1 Nbd7 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Nh4 Re8 15. Nhf5 $14) 11. Nf1 $1 Nc5 (11... c5 $6 {Is not very good with the knight on d7} 12. Ng3 Bb7 (12... g6 $2 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Ng5 d5 15. exd5 $18) (12... Nb6 {Is a decent try, but White is better after:} 13. d4 c4 (13... cxd4 $6 14. cxd4 Nfd7 (14... Qc7 15. Bg5 $16) 15. Nf5 $16) 14. Bc2 $14) (12... a5 {is well met by} 13. a4) 13. Nf5) 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. Ng3 Re8 14. d4 $14 (14. h3 $6 {again there is no need to include this move} Bf8 15. b4 Ncd7) 14... Ncd7 15. a4 $5 c5 (15... g6 {makes some sense}) 16. d5 $1 c4 ({If Black plays} 16... g6 17. b3 $3 $14 {is very strong} Bf8 (17... c4 18. b4 $1 (18. bxc4 $5 bxc4 19. a5 Nc5 20. Be3 Qc7 21. Rb1 Bc8 22. h3 Bd7 23. Nd2) 18... Nb6 19. h3 $16 (19. a5 {Or even closing the queenside in White's favour} Nbd7 20. h3 $16)) (17... Rc8 18. a5 $5) 18. h3 Bg7 19. Bg5 Qc7 (19... h6 20. Bd2 Qc7 21. a5 $5 $14 {We have seen this idea many times. White is closing the queenside but fixes the a6-pawn and wins some space for the eventual endgame. In the meantime, White has a very big space advantage and can easily transfer his pieces to the kingside and organize an attack there. There are two typical ways to start the kingside attack. One is g2-g4, followed by Nf5 or g5. Another is the f2-f4 break, opening the f-file.} (21. Nh2 $16)) 20. Qd2 Rab8 21. a5 Rf8 22. Nh2 $16 {[%cal Re1f1,Rf2f4]}) 17. Nf5 $1 {SUPER SOS !! As a general rule, Black must not allow Nf5 in a blocked position with c5-d5. He must always play g6 to avoid Nf5 or keep his bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal to take this knight!!} (17. h3 $6 g6 $1 $132) 17... Bf8 18. h3 g6 $2 (18... Nc5 $1 19. g4 $16 (19. Nh2 Bc8 20. Qf3 Bxf5 21. Qxf5 g6 $13)) 19. Nh6+ Bxh6 (19... Kg7 20. Ng5 Re7 21. Nhxf7 Qb8 22. Nh6 Kxh6 23. Ne6+ g5 24. h4 $18 Kg6 25. hxg5 Nh5 26. Qf3 $18) 20. Bxh6 Nh5 21. Qd2 Nc5 22. Nh2 Rb8 23. Ng4 Bc8 24. axb5 Rxb5 (24... axb5 25. Ra7) 25. Ra2 a5 26. Ne3 Nf4 27. Nxc4 $18 g5 28. h4 f6 29. g3 Nh3+ 30. Kg2 Kf7 31. Rh1 Kg6 32. b4 Kxh6 33. bxc5 Rxc5 34. Ne3 Nf4+ 35. Kf1 Ng6 36. Nf5+ Bxf5 37. hxg5+ Kg7 38. gxf6+ Kxf6 39. exf5 Nf8 40. Ba4 Kxf5 41. Qh6 Ng6 42. Bxe8 Qxe8 43. Rh5+ Kf6 44. Qg5+ Kg7 45. Qh6+ Kf6 46. Rb2 Rc7 47. g4 Qa4 48. Rf5+ Ke7 49. Qxh7+ Kd8 50. Qg8+ Kd7 51. Qe6+ Kd8 52. Rb8+ 1-0

