{This lecture is an introduction to the so-called Steinitz Deferred/Smyslov Variation arising after} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 {As you will see, this variation can be played almost entirely by relying on typical plans and ideas. Apart from a few forced lines that you need to remember, everything else is not based on concrete theory. That's why you can play this variation all your life and your opponents will not be able to prepare against you. In more than 70% of your games, White will opt for setups based on c2-c3 followed by d2-d4. These main lines are dealt with in the second lecture dedicated to this variation. In this lecture, I examine the possible deviations such as 5.Bxc6, 5.Nc3, 5.d4, and 5.c4. Note that White can play c2-c4 before or after castling. Both scenarios are examined in this lecture. The conclusion is that Black is doing more than fine in all these lines if he knows what he is doing.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Line with 5.Bxc6+!?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C73"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[EventDate "2023.06.21"]

{[%evp 0,38,14,14,14,14,12,22,31,3,23,14,32,-19,26,26,41,39,41,26,25,19,29,17,26,43,27,33,54,54,55,45,49,36,20,20,15,24,50,37,43]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {In my opinion, this is the right move order. The only drawback is that Black allows the Exchange Variation which is by the way not dangerous at all.} ({Another possible move order is} 3... g6 {I am not going to recommend it mainly because of} 4. d4 {which leads to some very drawish positions.} ({In case of} 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 d6 7. d4 Bd7 {we transpose to the main line of the Steinitz/Smyslov Variation.})) 4. Ba4 d6 $5 {This is the initial position of our survey. In 70% of your games, White will choose the main line based on 0-0, c2-c3, and d2-d4. However, White has 2 options to avoid it - 5. d4 and 5.Bxc6+. Another possible deviation is 5.0-0 followed by c2-c4 on the next move. In all cases, Black is totally fine and he has nice counterplay!} 5. Bxc6+ $5 {Together with 5.d4, this is another (unsuccessful) way for White to avoid the main lines of the Smyslov (Differed Steinitz) Spanish.} ({After} 5. c3 Bd7 6. d4 g6 7. O-O Bg7 {we reach the Differed Steinitz or Smyslov Variation which is covered in a separate lecture.}) ({The structure arising after} 5. Nc3 Be7 $5 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 Bb7 9. O-O Bf6 10. Nde2 Ne7 11. Be3 c5 $132 {provides Black with an excellent counterplay.}) 5... bxc6 6. d4 f6 $3 {I like very much this good positional move overprotecting e5! Black has a very good game now!} ({If you are in the mood for a dynamic game, I would suggest} 6... exd4 $1 {which is also quite playable.} 7. Nxd4 ({Nothing gives} 7. Qxd4 Nf6 {when the White queen is misplaced on d4.}) 7... c5 8. Ne2 Bb7 9. Nbc3 g6 $3 {Remember this move. Whenever possible, try to develop the dark-squared bishop to the long diagonal.} 10. O-O Bg7 $36 {Black has decent counterplay in this structure. The bishop pair provides good compensation for the slightly damaged pawn structure. At the same time, Black's doubled pawns are not such a big liability. Besides enjoying good central control, Black has also the possibility of playing on the b-file.}) 7. Nc3 $5 {This is the initial tabiya of this direction. Now the plan is ...Ne7-Ng6 followed by ... Be6! and ...Qb8! if he castles long! (of course we also play Be7 and 0-0. Generally, when White plays h2-h4 we play ...h7-h5! ...and when White plays de5 usually we take with the g6-knight or with the f-pawn!} ({Another interesting position arises after} 7. c4 {1-0 (34) Adams, M (2685)-Conquest, S  (2585) Hastings 1996 continued} Ne7 8. Nc3 c5 $3 {Remember this idea to fight against the construction c2-c4 & Nc3. It's important to prevent White from breaking our structure with c4-c5. As we will see in a while, Black wants a static centre.} 9. dxc5 {The right way to release the tension.} ({A positional mistake would be} 9. d5 $6 {when Black enjoys a fantastic version of KID. Now, he just needs to carry out the advance ...f6-f5 under favourable circumstances. The most natural continuation is} Ng6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gf6f5] preparing ...Be7 and ...f6-f5.} (9... Qd7 $5) (9... g6 $5) 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 f5 $15 {Black is already better. He has a bishop pair, good central control and the possibility to play on the kingside. At the same time, White usual queenside play is not possible here. White should play} 12. exf5 {Allowing ...f5-f4 would have been even worse. A possible line would be} Bxf5 13. Nd2 O-O 14. f3 Bd7 15. Nde4 Nh4 $15 {Black is better. He can proceed with ...Qe8-g6 followed by doubling the rooks on the f-file.}) 9... dxc5 {Our doubled pawns are not a problem here because they are placed on a closed file. While the d4-square is a weak point, d5 is not! Black is already better.} 10. Qxd8+ {In the endgame, Black's advantage will be even bigger.} ({A typical reaction to} 10. Nd5 {is} Nc6 $1 {We will need the knight in order to fight for the d4-square. At the same time, Black can just ignore the d5-knight for the time being. The play is going around this pieces. At some point, we can always kick it back by means of ... c7-c6. Let's take a look at one illustrative line.} 11. Nh4 (11. Be3 Bd6 $17) 11... Be6 12. O-O Nd4 13. f4 {White has no other constructive ideas.} Bd6 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Nxf4 O-O 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 $15 {Black is better in view of his more active knight and the weak d4-square. Actually, the e4-pawn is weaker than our doubled pawns.}) 10... Kxd8 11. Nd5 ({Putting pressure on c5 by means of} 11. Be3 Nc6 12. Na4 {is well met by} Nd4 {with a huge advantage for Black.}) 11... Nc6 12. Bd2 a5 $17 {A very useful move in this structure. Besides gaining space, Black rules out any b2-b4 breaks. Later on, we can put pressure on b2, after fixing the queenside structure with ...a5-a4.} 13. Bc3 Bd6 14. O-O-O Nd4 $17 {Black's advantage is out of question.}) 7... Ne7 $1 {In this position, White has two major plans - 0-0 or 0-0-0. In the arising positions, the knowledge of the typical ideas is far more important than memorizing concrete lines.} ({Another option is} 7... g6 $5 {which is also quite good and totally unexplored!} 8. Be3 ({Premature is} 8. h4 {since Black has} Bg4 ({Another typical reaction to h2-h4 is} 8... h6 {the idea beeing to meet h4-h5 with ...g6-g5.} 9. Be3 Bg7 10. h5 g5 $132 {Black has very good counterplay in this position.})) 8... Bg7 9. Qd2 h6 $3 {[%cal Gg8e7] Once again, this move is very important.} ({The immediate} 9... Ne7 $2 {will be met with} 10. Bh6 $16 {with a huge advantage for White. We need to preserve the dark-squared bishop which can potentially become very strong.}) 10. O-O Ne7 11. h3 {Before Rad1, White prevents ...Bg4.} (11. Rad1 Bg4 $15) 11... g5 12. Rad1 O-O $36 {I would take Black in this position. The flexible pawn structure makes the bishop pair an important factor in this position. Black can always consider ...Ng6 followed by ...f6-f5.}) 8. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1] The most challenging continuation. Besides supporting the centre, White prepares Qe2 followed by 0-0-0.} ({Worse is} 8. O-O $6 {which is very well met by} Ng6 9. Qe2 Qd7 $3 {[%cal Gd7f7] Remember this typical move. From our Italian camp, we know that the queen is well placed on d7 (in front of the bishop) in two cases: 1) White does not have a light-squared bishop 2) White's light-squared bishop is blocked on the queenside} (9... a5 $132) 10. Rd1 Qf7 $3 $15 {As a matter of fact, f7 is the perfect square for the queen in this pawn structure. Besides controlling the important diagonal a2-g8, the queen also supports the advance. ..f6-f5. Also, after dxe5 fxe5, the queen will actively participate in the play along the semi-open f-file.} 11. Be3 ({Obviously, the position arising after} 11. dxe5 fxe5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gc8g4] is in Black's favour. Black will proceed with ...Be7 followed by ...0-0 and ...Bg4.The play on the f-file can be very dangerous. Also, at any moment, the g6-knight can jump to h4 or f4.}) ({The thematic reaction to} 11. d5 {is} c5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gf6f5] closing the position. Later on, Black will easily organise the advance ... f6-f5.}) 11... Be7 12. b3 h6 {Another typical move. Before playing ...f6-f5, we take the g5-square under control.} 13. Na4 O-O 14. c4 f5 $17 {Due to his good central control and bishop pair, Black will be doing more than fine in the arising open position.}) ({As we already know, the structure arising after} 8. dxe5 fxe5 $15 {is better for Black in view of the semi-open f-file. The bishop pair is an important factor as well. The game might continue} 9. O-O Ng6 10. Bg5 Be7 ({As we know, another possibility is} 10... Qd7 $15 {After} 11. Qd2 h6 12. Be3 Be7 13. Rad1 O-O $15 {Black is better.}) 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 $17 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc8g4,Gg6f4] Black has a huge advantage due to his good central control and active play on the kingside.}) 8... Ng6 9. Qe2 {The most consistent.} ({The advance} 9. h4 $6 {is always well met by} h5 10. Qe2 {White is planning to castle long. We are now following the game Shirov - Huebner, 1996.} ({Note that then the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 are included,} 10. dxe5 {is best answered by} Nxe5 $1 {The problem is that ...fxe5 would weaken the g5-square. Now, White should reckon with the threat of ...Bg4. Let's take a look at a sample line.} 11. Nxe5 fxe5 12. Qd2 Be7 13. Bg5 ({After} 13. O-O-O Bxh4 {White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Be6 14. O-O-O O-O $1 $132 {Black enjoys decent counterplay.}) 10... Bg4 11. O-O-O Be7 12. Qc4 Qd7 {We can now see that the inclusion of the moves h2-h4 and ...h7-h5 is to Black's advantage since he managed to fortify his bishop on g4.} 13. Rdg1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gf2f3] White is planning to chase the bishop away by playing Nd2 followed by f2-f3. This is, however, a time-consuming procedure.} a5 {The most natural move in the position.} ({Another very interesting option would have been} 13... Be6 $5 14. d5 cxd5 15. exd5 ({The position arising after} 15. Nxd5 c6 16. Nc7+ Kf7 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Qxc6 Qxa2 $132 {is more pleasant for Black due to his safer king.}) 15... Bf7 {Black's bishop pair and strong centre make his position more promising.}) 14. Nd2 exd4 {Black opens up the position in the right moment. White's pieces are rather passive now.} (14... Be6 $5 15. d5 cxd5 16. exd5 Bf7 17. Qd3 f5 18. f3 Bf6 19. Nc4 $14) ({The game went} 14... Rb8 15. d5 cxd5 16. exd5 Qc8 17. f3 Bd7 18. Qd3 {1-0 (42) Shirov,A-Huebner,R/ Dortmund 1996/CBMs/}) 15. Bxd4 a4 {[%cal Gg4e6,Gc6c5] Black has a huge advantage. He is ready to proceed with ...Be6 followed by ...c6-c5.}) 9... Be6 $1 10. O-O-O ({Once again, we need to check what happens after} 10. h4 {We already know the right reaction -} h5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {Once again, I would like to remind you that this is the best reaction when the moves h2-h4 and ... h7-h5 have been included.} 12. Nxe5 fxe5 $1 13. O-O-O Be7 14. g3 Bf6 $3 {This important move is prophylaxis against f2-f4.} 15. f3 ({The immediate} 15. Qd2 {will be well met by} Bg4 16. Rdf1 Bf3 $15 {with an advantage for Black.}) 15... a5 16. Qd2 Qb8 17. Kb1 a4 18. Ka1 Qb4 $17 {Black's queenside activity, combined with the bishop pair, provides a huge advantage.}) 10... Qb8 $1 {Remember this typical idea which works very well when White castles long. Black is always ready to proceed with ...a6-a5 followed by ...Qb4 and ...Rb8.} 11. Kb1 ({After} 11. d5 cxd5 12. exd5 Bd7 $132 {Black is doing more than fine. He can focus on the queenside without bothering about central tensions.} ({or} 12... Bf7 $132)) ({As usual, nothing gives} 11. h4 h5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nd4 ({The time,} 13. Nxe5 {can be met also by} dxe5 $36 {[%cal Gf8a3] which is possible in positions with 0-0-0. Black's dark-squared bishop is now participating in the attack.}) 13... Bc4 $36 {Black's queenside initiative is quite annoying.}) 11... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] Sooner or later, this typical move has to be played. The pawn should go to a4.} ({Another option is} 11... Qb7 12. Bc1 Be7 13. g3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} (13... Rb8 14. b3 Bf7 15. h4 $16 {Spasskij - Lutikov, URS 1979.}) 14. h4 h5 15. Ne1 a4 $15 {with an advantage for Black.}) 12. h4 h5 13. dxe5 dxe5 $15 {Once again, this is the right recapture since the white king is on the queenside.} 14. Ne1 Bb4 $36 {Black managed to develop a dangerous initiative. White has to be very precise.} *

