{[%evp 0,38,27,14,14,14,12,28,31,-5,23,7,32,-10,28,41,41,34,26,24,22,22,22,22,45,26,26,27,45,53,61,49,38,20,20,15,5,-2,43,36,36]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 $5 5. d4 $5 {With this move, White is trying to avoid the main lines and to get a dynamic position. My main suggestion here is} Bd7 $1 {which I find more practical than 5...b5.} (5... b5 $1 {This is another interesting choice that sometimes leads to a forced draw. However, White does have some other options and although Black is totally fine, the play is very different than the Smyslov Spanish. So, make your choice!} 6. Bb3 Nxd4 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. c3 {This is the best move. According to the computer, the evaluation of this line is 0.00.} ({After} 8. Qh5 $2 {Black's most precise reaction is} Qe7 $17 {when Black is fighting for a huge advantage. He is ready to proceed with natural moves such as ...Nf6 and ...c7-c5. A possible line would be} 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qh4 c5 11. c3 c4 12. Bd1 d3 $17 {with a huge advantage.}) ({A typical reaction to} 8. a4 {is} Bb7 {Strangely enough, in this position, even some strong players went for} 9. Qxd4 $2 {which is typically met by} c5 10. Qe3 c4 11. Ba2 Nf6 12. Nc3 Be7 13. axb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 {This position was reached in the high-profile game Ghaem Maghami - Short, N, 2013. Now, Black could have played} O-O $19 ({or} 14... Nxe4 15. O-O O-O $19) 15. Nc3 d5 $19 {with a decisive advantage in both cases.}) ({The pseudo-attacking} 8. Bd5 $6 {is just a waste of time. A logical continuation of the game would be} Rb8 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Bc6+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $36 {Black's better development provides him with a strong initiative. He can continue with ...Be7 followed by ...0-0, and ...d6-d5. The following lines are quite illustrative -} 12. O-O Be7 $36 13. b3 ({After} 13. c4 O-O 14. Nc3 Qe6 {White's position seems a bit too overextended. The following game of Demchenko is a typical illustration of what might happen in such positions -} 15. Nd5 c5 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qd3 Qxe4 18. Qxd6 Qxc4 19. Qxa6 Nd5 20. b3 Qd4 21. Bg5 Qg4 22. Bd2 Rb6 23. Qa7 h5 24. Rad1 Rg6 25. g3 h4 26. Rfe1 h3 {0-1 Karatorossian,D-Demchenko,A/Yerevan 2016/ Mega Updates}) 13... d5 $3 {The most precise continuation. Black immediately opens the position up.} 14. exd5 Qxd5 $15 15. Bb2 Qxd4 16. Bxd4 Rd8 17. Be5 O-O $1 {White cannot complete the development without allowing the rook invasion on d2.} 18. Nc3 Rd2 $17) ({The move} 8. Qxd4 $4 {is known to be the most typical mistake in the entire variation. After} c5 9. Qd5 Be6 10. Qc6+ Bd7 11. Qd5 c4 $19 {Black is just winning a piece.}) ({After} 8. O-O Nf6 9. a4 Rb8 $15 {White does not have a comfortable way of regaining the pawn since Qxd4 is always met by ...c7-c5-c4.}) 8... dxc3 {The best continuation according to the computer.} ({An alternative is} 8... d3 $5 {This is playable if you want to avoid the draw, although White is slightly better (Besides if you want to avoid the draw, you can play 5.d4-Bd7!} 9. Qxd3 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. c4 (11. Bf4 O-O 12. Nd2 Bb7 $132) 11... O-O 12. Nc3 c6 ({Black can also play} 12... b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bf6 $132 {with good counterchances in this Benoni-like position. White should reckon with the advance ...a6-a5-a4.}) 13. Bf4 Ng4 {In this complex position, the play is going on for three results.}) 9. Qd5 {This is how White can force the draw.} ({Black is better after} 9. Nxc3 $6 Nf6 $1 $15 {If Black can consolidate with ...Be7 followed by ...0-0, White does not have enough compensation for the pawn. Therefore, energetic play is required. Fortunately for Black,} 10. e5 {is not dangerous.} ({After} 10. O-O Be7 $17 11. Nd5 (11. Bd5 Rb8 $17) 11... Be6 $17 {White does not have any compensation for the pawn.} (11... O-O $17)) 10... dxe5 11. Bxf7+ Ke7 $1 $15 {Having insufficient development, White cannot show a follow-up in this position.} 12. Qb3 ({A specacular line is} 12. Bd5 Nxd5 $3 13. Nxd5+ ({In the endgame, arising after} 13. Qxd5 Qxd5 14. Nxd5+ Kd7 15. O-O Bd6 $19 {Black has a winning advantage.}) 13... Ke6 $3 {This is the only move to remember! White's problem is that} 14. Nf4+ exf4 15. Qxd8 {will be answered with} Bb4+ 16. Qd2 Bxd2+ 17. Bxd2 f3 $1 {The most precise. Black is spoiling White's kingside structure.} ({Another good option is} 17... Kf5 18. O-O Be6 {with a stable advantage.}) 18. O-O (18. gxf3 Bb7 $15) 18... Bb7 19. Rac1 Rac8 $15 {White is still far away from the draw.}) 12... c5 $3 $19 {[%cal Gc5c4] A spectacular idea. Now, the threat is ...c5-c4.} 13. Bd5 c4 14. Qd1 Nxd5 15. Nxd5+ Ke6 $3 {Once again, we see the same motif.} 16. Qg4+ Kxd5 17. Qd1+ Kc6 18. Qxd8 Bb4+ 19. Qd2 Bxd2+ 20. Bxd2 Bf5 $19 {Black had a winning advantage in the game Sanal, V - Adhiban, B, 2016}) 9... Be6 10. Qc6+ Bd7 11. Qd5 Be6 12. Qc6+ Bd7 $11 {This is the forced draw!}) 6. O-O $3 {This is White's most flexible continuation.} (6. c3 $1 {takes us back to the Smyslov Variation -} g6 7. Bg5 Be7 $1 (7... f6 $5) 8. Be3 Nf6 9. Nbd2 (9. Bc2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 $132) 9... Ng4 $132) (6. d5 Nce7 7. Bxd7+ {Compared to the d4-d5 variation of the Smyslov Spanish, here White has an extra tempo (obviously he wont play c3 and then c4...but c2-c4 in one go) . Nevertheless, the position is closed and an extra tempo doesn't mean much. It will be spent on a move like Re1 or Bd2 and Nlack, following his regular plan with g6-Bg7-h6!-f5!-Nf6 , acquires a very good game!} ({It's instructive to know that} 7. c4 {is very well met by} b5 $132 {which is a typical idea when White delays Bxd7.} 8. Bc2 ({Nothing gives} 8. Bb3 Ng6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Re1 (10. Nc3 b4) 10... Be7 11. Nc3 O-O {Black can already start preparing the thematic advance ...f7-f5.}) 8... g6 9. a4 Bg7 ({Black could have also considered} 9... bxc4) 10. Nc3 b4 11. Ne2 h5 12. a5 c5 13. dxc6 Bxc6 $132 {This structure reminds me the Sicilian Najdorf. Black has fantastic counterplay here and eventually managed to win in the game Riff, J - Kryvoruchko, Y, 2018.}) 7... Qxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg8f6] By taking the control of the g5-square, Black prepares the advance ...f7-f5 followed by . ..Nf6.} ({Another possible setup is} 8... Nf6 9. Nc3 Ng6 10. O-O Be7 {with a playable position. After ...0-0, Black will prepare ...f7-f5 by removing the f6-knight.}) ({Playing in a KID style by means of} 8... g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. O-O h6 $132 {is possible as well. Since the light-squared bishops have been traded off, before playing ...f7-f5, we should always reckon with Ng5-e5. That's why in all these lines Black plays ...h7-h6.} 11. Re1 ({The move} 11. Nd2 {does not prevent us from playing} f5 {For instance, after} 12. exf5 gxf5 $1 13. Qh5+ Kf8 14. a4 Nf6 15. Qe2 Kg8 16. Re1 Kh7 $15 {Black has a perfect version of KID.}) 11... f5 12. a4 Nf6 $132) 9. Nc3 f5 10. O-O Nf6 $132 {This is another playable position. This time, Black can proceed with ...g7-g5 followed by ... Bg7.}) (6. Bb3 $5 {This is a tricky sideline but Black stands perfectly!} exd4 {Now, White will be forced to take on d4 but a knight on d4 does not work well together with a bishop on b3! (an important principle!).} (6... Nxd4 {is possible as well.}) 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 (7... Nf6 $132) 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. O-O Be7 (9... b5 $5 $132) 10. c4 (10. Nc3 b5) 10... b5 $132 {Again, Black starts fighting for the initiative by using White's overextended position. The white queen is also exposed in the centre of the board.}) ({In case of} 6. c4 {you can try} b5 $5 {which is a very interesting novelty!} ({It goes without saying that the usual} 6... exd4 $5 {is simple and good. For instance, after} 7. Nxd4 b5 $5 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bb3 Nf6 10. Nc3 Be7 $132 {Black has enough counterplay.}) 7. cxb5 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. bxa6 ({After} 9. Qxd4 axb5 10. Bc2 Nf6 $15 {Black is better. If provided with the chance, he can even develop his bishop to g7.}) ({In case of} 9. b6 {we need to protect the central pawn with} c5 10. O-O (10. Nd2 Nf6 $132 11. Nc4 Bb5) 10... Nf6 11. Bg5 Be7 $132 {Playing with Black is easier since he has a protected passed pawn in the centre and the b6-pawn will probably be lost. White needs to prove compensation here.}) 9... c5 $36 {Again, I would take Black. Very soon, the a6-pawn will be regained.}) ({Harmless is} 6. dxe5 {when Black has a choice.} dxe5 {As a rule, this move is good when Black hasn't played ...g7-g6.} ({Another typical endgame arises after the moves} 6... Nxe5 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd7+ Kxd7 10. Be3 Ke6 {Even though the endgame is objectively equal, playing with Black is a bit easier. We are at the positive side of equality in view of the more active king. Also, in this endgame, Black can start expanding on both wings.}) 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 Bd6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (51) Antoli Royo,J-Mirzoev,A/La Roda 2008/ CBMs}) 6... Nf6 $1 {This is a very important moment. Don't try to get the Smyslov main line by playing 6...g6 because this move is dropping a pawn.} (6... g6 $4 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. dxe5 $18) 7. Re1 ({After} 7. d5 Ne7 ({or even} 7... Nb8 $5 8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 9. Re1 g6 $132) 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Re1 g6 10. c4 Bg7 $132 {Black is doing fine. This type of position will be covered in a separate lecture.}) 7... b5 {This move is called for since White already wants to take the e5-pawn.} 8. Bb3 (8. dxe5 dxe5 (8... Nxe5 $132) 9. Bb3 Bb4 $5 (9... Bc5) 10. c3 Bd6 $132) 8... Nxd4 $15 9. Nxd4 exd4 $15 {White still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn. Black will just finish the development with ... Be7 and ...0-0.} *

