{[%evp 0,38,16,14,31,14,12,34,31,6,23,7,32,-15,47,41,34,28,24,22,22,30,30,30,34,26,26,20,49,51,46,39,42,20,15,7,-5,-4,36,37,16]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 $5 5. O-O {This is by far the most flexible continuation.} (5. c4 $5 {This is a very interesting attempt for an advantage! Black must be careful. The best idea when I see c2-c4 is to play Bg4! Note that White can even play 5.0-0! Bd7 6.c4! Bg4!! when again I enter the same position, even with a tempo down! But the position is rather closed and Black is doing fine!} Bg4 $1 {This is the thematic reaction to c2-c4.} ({Worse is} 5... Bd7 $6 {White's idea is very well demonstrated in the following line -} 6. O-O Nf6 7. Nc3 g6 $2 {This is a huge positional mistake that I make on purpose for didactic reasons.} ({Better would have been} 7... Be7 8. h3 O-O 9. d3 $14 {when White has a slight but stable advantage.}) 8. Re1 Bg7 9. Bxc6 $3 Bxc6 10. d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 O-O 12. f3 $16 {This is the kind of position that White is hoping for after 5.c4. Black does not have any counterplay in this structure.}) 6. h3 {By playing ...Bg4, Black created the threat of ...Qf6. That's why White wants to immediately get rid of the pin.} ({A typical positional mistake would be} 6. O-O $6 {when after} Qf6 $3 $36 {White cannot keep the integrity of his kingside structure. A possible follow-up would be} 7. Nc3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qxf3 9. gxf3 Nge7 $3 $15 {This is a better square for the knight. After ...0-0-0, Black can always consider ...Ng6.} 10. Nd5 (10. b4 O-O-O $36 {[%cal Gc6d4,Ge7g6] Black has an advantage since White does not have any compensation for his broken pawn structure. Black is ready to start exploiting weaknesses by simple moves such as ...Nd4 and ...Ng6.} ({Another very good idea is} 10... Kd8 $3 $15 {with similar plans.})) 10... O-O-O $17) ({White can also start with} 6. Nc3 {Now, 6...Qf6 will be met by Nd5. Black, however, can resort to his typical play.} Nf6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Be7 9. O-O Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6] Remember this typical move. In this structure, the knight belongs to e6 in order to fight for the d4-square. Therefore, Black usually goes for the maneuver - Nf6-d7-c5-e6. A typical follow-up would be} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d3 Nc5 12. Qg3 Ne6 13. Bd2 a5 {Black is doing fine. Using the b-file to put pressure on b2 is a typical idea in this position. Very often, Black fixes the b2-pawn with ...a5-a4. At the same time, White does not have many constructive ideas in this position. The advance f2-f4 is usually well met by ...exf4 followed by ...Bf6.} ({Another good idea is} 13... c5 14. Nd5 Bh4 15. Qg4 c6 16. Ne3 g6 {when Black has an advantage. He can actually start playing on both wings in this position. At the same time. White has no plan.})) ({Let's now take a look at another typical idea -} 6. d3 Nf6 7. O-O Nd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 {Now, Black has a choice regarding the development of the dark-squared bishop. When you have the chance, the best option is} g6 {the bishop is perfectly placed on g7 in this kind of structure!} 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. Be3 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] Once again, the knight is heading for the perfect e6-square.} 13. Qd1 Ne6 14. Ne2 c5 {With a bishop on g7, this structure is even better for Black. Now, White cannot even think of f2-f4. Additionally, besides his queenside play, Black can also prepare the advance ...f7-f5.}) 6... Bxf3 $1 7. Qxf3 g6 $1 {Once again, I like this plan.} ({Of course, the alternative} 7... Nf6 $1 {is simple and good!} 8. Nc3 Be7 9. O-O Nd7 $3 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d3 Nc5 $1 12. Qg3 Ne6 $132 {We have already discussed this position.}) 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. d3 Nf6 $5 {This is the standard move in such positions.} ({Another very good option is} 9... Nge7 $5 {The idea is the quickly prepare the advance ...f7-f5.} 10. h4 h6 {Remember this thematic idea. Black wants to answer h4-h5 with ... g6-g5.} 11. h5 g5 12. Bd2 O-O {Black is doing fine. The advance ...f7-f5 is already on the agenda.}) 10. Bg5 h6 {Obviously, we cannot tolerate the pin in view of the threat of Nd5.} 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nd7 $36 {[%cal Gc6d4] Once again, this typical move is working well. White should now reckon with ...Nd4.} 13. Bxc6 (13. O-O Nd4) 13... bxc6 {Black has a good game. He can focus on the queenside by means of simple moves such as ...a6-a5 followed by ...Rb8, and ... Nc5.}) 5... Bd7 $1 6. c4 $1 {This is a dangerous sideline because White has won a whole tempo (we will play Bd7-Bg4) compared to the line with 5.c4-Bg4! however the position is rather closed, and Black gets an acceptable game!} (6. d4 $5 Nf6 $1 {transposes into 5.d4-Bd7 6.0-0-Nf6!}) 6... Bg4 $1 {We are already familiar with this thematic reaction to c2-c4.} 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nf6 9. Nc3 {White has nothing better than this natural move.} ({The tricky} 9. Qb3 $5 {is not particularly challenging. Black can just play} Qc8 10. Nc3 Nd7 $132 {Once again, this thematic move provides us with an excellent counterplay.} 11. d3 ({It's important to mention that} 11. Nd5 $2 {is well met by} b5 12. cxb5 Nd4 $15 {when White cannot hold the b5-pawn. For instance, after} 13. Qd1 axb5 14. Bc2 g6 15. d3 c6 16. Nc3 Bg7 $15 {Black's advantage is beyond any doubt.}) 11... Be7 12. f4 {White's only constructive idea.} ({Once again,} 12. Nd5 {is well met by} b5 $1) 12... O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. f5 h6 15. Be3 a5 $132 {Again, Black has enough counterplay. After, ...Rb8, he can try to exchange the dark-squared bishops by means of ...Qd8 followed by ...Bg5. The knight will eventually come to c5.}) ({A dubious idea is} 9. d4 $6 exd4 10. e5 {After} dxe5 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Nd7 13. Re1 f6 $17 {White does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Nd7 $1 {Remember to play this move first!} ({The alternative} 9... Be7 {allows} 10. d4 $14) 10. Bxc6 {White is immediately going for the typical structure.} ({After} 10. Ne2 {Black can play} g6 {planning to put the bishop on the perfect g7-square.} 11. d3 Bg7 $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) 10... bxc6 11. d3 Nc5 (11... Be7 $132) 12. Qg3 Ne6 $132 {Even with a tempo down, this position is more than playable.} 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be7 $132 15. Be3 Bf6 $1 {Putting the bishop on the long diagonal is an important idea in this pawn structure.} 16. Qf2 $1 {[%cal Gd3d4] White is preparing the advance d3-d4. A very good reaction to this idea is} O-O 17. d4 c5 $3 $132 18. dxc5 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Qe7 $11 {when Black has enough compensation for the pawn in view of his superior pawn structure.} *

