1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. d4 Bd7 6. Bb3 $5 {Even though I am almost sure that this move was an over-the-board improvisation, this sideline is a bit tricky. We should immediately take on d4, either with the knight or with the pawn.} g6 $6 {This is not the most precise move and now White is better with a correct play.} ({Better would have been} 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 ({Another good option is} 7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 b5 {Black is just fine. He can follow with ...Re8 and ...Bf8. Under favourable circumstances, the advance ...c7-c5 can be played as well.} ({Another good option is} 11... Be6 12. Bf4 Nd7 {followed by ...Bf6 and ...Nc5.}) ({Also, there is nothing wrong with the simple} 11... Re8)) 8. Nc3 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 b5 $36 {Black has an excellent counterplay. At any moment, White should reckon with the advance ...c7-c5-c4.}) 7. dxe5 dxe5 {Usually, when Black has committed to . ..g7-g6, taking with the knight is a better idea. In this case, however, it does not work concretely.} 8. Bg5 {This is an inaccuracy.} (8. Nc3 $1 $16) 8... f6 9. Be3 {White is only slightly better now but Black is solid enough and little by little he takes over!} Bg4 (9... Qe7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Nd5 Qg7 $36) 10. Nbd2 Bh6 11. Qe2 Qe7 12. h3 Bd7 13. Nc4 Be6 14. O-O-O a5 15. Ba4 Qb4 16. Bb5 Ke7 17. a4 Bxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxe3+ 19. fxe3 Qxa4 20. Kb1 Nh6 21. Rd5 Rhd8 22. Rb5 Rab8 23. g4 Nf7 24. Bxf7 Kxf7 25. Rf1 Kg7 26. g5 Rf8 27. Rd5 Rbd8 28. Rxd8 Nxd8 29. Rd1 Nf7 30. gxf6+ Kxf6 31. h4 Qxe4 32. Rd7 Qc6 33. Qd1 Ke6 34. Nd4+ exd4 35. Qg4+ Kf6 36. Qxd4+ Ne5 37. Rd5 Qe6 38. Rc5 c6 39. Qf4+ Ke7 0-1

