1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. d4 Bd7 6. dxe5 {It's clear that after this move White cannot pretend for an opening advantage. Nevertheless, I will provide some explanations because the arising symmetrical structure is quite typical.} dxe5 {As we have already pointed out, when the dark-squared bishop is going to operate on the diagonal f8-a3, this recapture works very well.} ({Of course,} 6... Nxe5 {is playable as well but it gives White the opportunity to exchange a lot of pieces.} 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd7+ Qxd7 9. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {The arising endgame is objectively equal. White has a slightly better bishop but Black has a more active king. In such positions, the player with a better understanding will win the game.}) 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 ({Let's suppose that White plays} 8. Qe2 {After} Bd6 9. c3 O-O 10. Bg5 {the arising positions are pretty similar to the Italian. Black's biggest priority is to improve the position of the misplaced c6-knight. A possible line would be} h6 11. Bh4 Qe7 12. Nbd2 b5 13. Bc2 Nd8 $132 {[%cal Gd8e6] followed by ...Ne6. Black is doing completely fine.}) 8... Bd6 9. Re1 h6 10. Nd5 O-O 11. Nb6 $6 {This move is already an inaccuracy.} ({For didactic purposes, we shall take a look at the following line -} 11. h3 b5 $1 {The most precise continuation. Now, White will be forced to part with his light-squared bishop.} 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Bb3 Na5 $1 {You should spot such moves automatically.} 14. Bd2 Nxb3 15. axb3 Bc6 {[%cal Gc6b7] Black's first priority is to protect the problematic a6-pawn with ... Bb7 in order to free the rook.} 16. Qe2 Bb7 $15 {Black has a stable advantage.}) 11... cxb6 12. Qxd6 b5 13. Bb3 Bg4 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nd2 Nd4 $15 {It's clear that Black is calling all the shots. White should already fight for equality.} 16. f3 Be6 17. c3 Nxb3 18. Nxb3 Nd7 19. Be3 a5 20. Rad1 Rdc8 21. Rd2 a4 22. Nc1 a3 23. Red1 Nf8 24. Kf2 f6 25. bxa3 Rxa3 26. Rb2 Bc4 27. Rd6 Rxc3 28. Nb3 Bxb3 29. axb3 Ng6 30. g3 Rc2+ 31. Rxc2 Rxc2+ 32. Rd2 Rc3 33. b4 Rb3 34. Bc5 b6 35. Bd6 Nf8 36. f4 Ne6 37. fxe5 fxe5 38. Rd5 Rb2+ 39. Ke3 Rxh2 40. Rxe5 Kf7 41. Rxb5 Rb2 42. Rxb6 Rb3+ 43. Ke2 h5 44. Rb7+ Kf6 45. Kf2 g5 46. b5 h4 47. gxh4 gxh4 48. Be7+ Ke5 49. Bxh4 Kxe4 50. Be7 Kd5 51. Rd7+ 1/2-1/2

