1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. d4 Bd7 $5 {This is the move that avoids all repetitions and takes the game into a KID type of play! Small advantages for White given by the computer are irrelevant here because the position is closed and no concrete lines exist!} 6. d5 Nce7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. c4 g6 {Black is playing in a King's Indian style.} ({I would have preferred} 8... h6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gg8f6] preparing ...f7-f5 followed by ...Nf6. Before playing .. .f7-f5, always watch for Ng5-e6!} 9. Nc3 f5 {Contrary to the KID, here we don't need to retreat the f6-knight in order to play ...f7-f5. The following sequence seems to be quite logical -} 10. exf5 Nxf5 11. O-O Nf6 12. Re1 g5 $5 13. Nd2 Bg7 14. Nde4 O-O $132 {Black has an excellent position. Indeed, the g7-bishop is restricted by all the pawns placed on dark squares. On the other hand, the same pawns also restrict White's bishop. Black has many dynamic opportunities on the kingside. He will first double the rooks on the f-file.}) ({It goes without saying that the immediate} 8... f5 $2 {will be met by} 9. Ng5 $16) 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. O-O h6 11. b4 f5 12. Ne1 Nf6 13. f3 O-O 14. Nd3 g5 15. c5 Qe8 16. exf5 $2 Nxf5 $15 {The d5-pawn is very weak now!} (16... Qf7 $15) 17. Ne4 Qf7 18. cxd6 cxd6 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Nf2 Bd8 21. Ne4 Bb6+ 22. Kh1 Bd4 23. Rb1 Qxd5 24. Qb3 Qxb3 25. Rxb3 d5 26. Nc5 Rf7 27. Ne6 Bb6 28. Re1 Re8 29. Nc5 Bxc5 30. bxc5 e4 31. Kg1 Nd4 32. Rd3 exd3 33. Rxe8+ Rf8 34. Re1 Rc8 35. Rd1 Rxc5 36. Be3 Ne2+ 37. Kf2 Rc2 38. Rxd3 Nc1+ 39. Rd2 Rxa2 40. Rxa2 Nxa2 41. Bd2 d4 42. Ke2 Nc3+ 43. Kd3 Nb5 44. h4 gxh4 45. Bxh6 Nd6 46. Bf4 Nf5 47. Ke4 Ne3 48. Kxd4 Nxg2 49. Bh2 Kf7 50. Kd3 Ke6 51. Ke2 Kf5 52. Kd3 b5 53. Kd4 Ne1 {a very high-level game by Black!} 0-1

