{[%evp 0,88,16,13,25,28,28,16,18,-1,15,9,9,9,16,-4,-6,-4,24,-10,-3,-5,9,7,-12,-26,-24,-47,-23,-16,10,0,-8,-12,49,30,0,0,-35,-35,-19,-85,-6,-12,22,-21,42,-68,-73,-100,40,-37,-33,-48,-33,-2,34,53,53,24,-6,0,0,0,42,-17,-7,1,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-6,0,0,190,151,172,172,214,219,215,224,225,225,207,-277,-344] An amazing game by Black against a very very strong opponent which you should study very carefully several times! Black plays very active chess and he is merciless untll the end!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. d4 exd4 $1 {Perfectly good and suitable for an open fight!} 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Ne2 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gc8b7] In general, in this structure, we want to fianchetto both bishops and develop the knight on e7. Of course, such rules cannot be valid 100%. Often the knight stands well even on f6.} 9. Nbc3 {The most natural move.} ({Let's suppose that White starts with} 9. Bd2 {planning to exchange the dark-squared bishops via c3. In this case, Black can even consider} Bg7 10. Bc3 f6 {preserving the bishop pair.} ({It goes without saying that} 10... Nf6 {planning to answer} 11. e5 {with} Ne4 {is decent and good.})) 9... Bg7 10. O-O Ne7 11. Bg5 {White plays in the most active way. By pinning the knight, he creates the threat of Nd5.} ({In case of} 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Qd2 f5 {Black has excellent counterplay because the bishop pair is working well in this open position.}) 11... h6 12. Bh4 ({Being an experienced player, Black is not afraid of ghosts. For instance, after} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nd5 Qd8 {It becomes clear that White's initiative is only temporary. Black's long-term advantage of the bishop pair, however, remains. The game might continue} 14. c3 O-O 15. Qc2 a5 {Remember this move which is very typical in this pawn structure. Black wants to keep gaining space on the queenside by means of ...a5-a4. Since Black will put pressure on the b-file, fixing the b2-pawn in advance is an important strategic idea.}) 12... g5 13. Bg3 f5 14. f4 Bb7 {We can now see how powerful the black bishops are. They are practically controlling the entire board.} 15. Qd2 {The most natural continuation.} ({Of course, after} 15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Qd3 O-O {Black's bishop pair provides a huge advantage.}) 15... Qd7 16. fxg5 O-O-O {Black has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. Later on, he managed to win the game.} 17. g6 Rdf8 18. exf5 Rxf5 19. Nf4 Rhf8 20. Nce2 Qc6 21. Rf3 Kb8 22. Raf1 Qa4 23. b3 Qe4 24. Bf2 Qb4 25. c3 Qb5 26. Rg3 Qd7 27. b4 cxb4 28. cxb4 h5 29. Bd4 h4 30. Bxg7 hxg3 31. Nxg3 Rxf4 32. Rxf4 Rxf4 33. Qxf4 Nxg6 34. Qf6 Qc6 35. Qd8+ Bc8 36. Qg5 Qc2 37. h4 Bb7 38. Qd8+ Ka7 39. Bd4+ c5 40. Bf2 Qd1+ 41. Nf1 Qg4 42. Ne3 Qxb4 43. Qxd6 Nf4 44. Nc4 Nh3+ 0-1

