{[%evp 0,96,28,28,28,22,22,18,28,-4,16,16,16,16,16,-4,-5,-6,-5,-6,2,-5,-29,-36,-9,-20,-34,-35,-32,-32,-13,-50,-13,-17,-11,-25,-25,-8,4,-11,-14,-28,-12,-19,-9,-3,0,-66,-5,-49,7,1,9,-30,-6,-65,-4,-164,-58,-56,-45,-50,-46,-39,-41,-39,-38,-36,-28,-25,-38,-100,-96,-127,-127,-142,-158,-158,-155,-160,-166,-209,-206,-206,-206,-249,-219,-205,-475,-488,-616,-1066,-789,-636,-705,-978,-992,-992,-1049]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Ne2 Nf6 {Even though I prefer the e7-square for the knight, this move is playable as well.} 9. Nbc3 Bb7 10. Ng3 g6 {Obviously, the dark-squared bishop should occupy the long diagonal.} 11. Bf4 ({You should never be afraid of moves such as} 11. e5 {After} dxe5 {White does not have compensation for the pawn.}) 11... h5 {I like this move a lot. Besides preparing ...h5-h4, Black prevents White from exchanging the dark-squared bishops via h6.} 12. h4 Bg7 13. Qd2 Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5] The knight is heading for the perfect e5-square.} ({Another very good continuation would have been} 13... Qe7 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Rhe1 Qe6 {In this pawn structure, e6 is the perfect square for the queen. Besides being completely safe, from this position, the queen is controlling the entire board.}) 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. O-O f6 16. Bf4 Ne5 17. Nd5 O-O 18. Rad1 Kh7 19. f3 ({After} 19. Bxe5 fxe5 {Black actually improves his pawn structure. The rook is now working very effectively along the f-file. At the same time, both white knights are far away from the g5-square.}) 19... a5 $1 {This is the last important move which is related to the pawn structure. Since Black does not have an active play on the kingside, he avoids being fixed on the other wing. Also, we know that in this structure, the advance ...a6-a5 is generally useful for Black.} ({The following cooperative line shows what White is looking for in this pawn structure -} 19... Rae8 20. a3 Nf7 21. b4 cxb4 22. axb4 Nd8 23. c4 Ne6 24. Be3 {We can now see that White is clearly superior on the queenside. At the same time, Black doesn't have achievements on the other wing.}) 20. Ne3 a4 $132 {In the arising complex middlegame, Black has an excellent counterplay. Later on, he managed to win the game.} 21. Ne2 Bc6 22. Nc3 Rab8 23. Qc1 Qf7 24. Ncd5 Bb5 25. Rf2 Rfe8 26. Kh1 Rb7 27. Rg1 Nc4 28. a3 Nxe3 29. Nxe3 Bd7 30. c3 Rbb8 31. Rd1 Be6 32. Rdd2 Bd7 33. Qd1 f5 34. exf5 Bxf5 35. Nxf5 Qxf5 36. Bg3 Bxc3 37. Rde2 Bd4 38. Rxe8 Rxe8 39. Rf1 Qd7 40. Qc2 Qb5 41. Rb1 Re2 42. Qd1 Rxb2 43. Rxb2 Qxb2 44. Kh2 Qxa3 45. Bf4 Qa1 46. Qe2 Be5 47. g3 Qb2 48. Bd2 a3 0-1

