1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. d4 Nf6 7. Bxc6 $5 {A clever sideline. Black needs to be a bit careful and then he is perfectly fine!} Bxc6 8. Re1 $1 {This is the right continuation. Black not only protects the e4-pawn but also creates an annoying opposition along the e-file.} ({A bad strategic decision would be} 8. d5 {since Black is more than happy to play a position with a closed centre. After} Bd7 9. Re1 {Black can play either} Be7 ({or} 9... g6)) ({An important line that you need to know is} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxe4 11. Re1 Be7 $15 {In this open position, Black's bishop pair provides him with a slight edge. We are even ready to take on c2!}) 8... Be7 $3 {You should remember this precise move.} 9. Nc3 exd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. h3 b5 $5 $132 {Black has an excellent counterplay in this structure. White should always reckon with ...c7-c5 followed by ...b5-b4. Later on, he can proceed with ...Bc6 and ...Re8.} 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Re8 $132 15. Bd2 c6 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Ne2 Bf8 18. Ng3 Re6 19. Qf3 Rae8 20. Bc3 d5 21. exd5 Nxd5 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Bd2 g6 24. b3 Qb6 25. Qd3 Nb4 26. Bxb4 Bxb4 27. Ne4 Be7 28. c3 Qc7 29. Qd4 f5 30. Nd2 Bf6 31. Qd3 Rd6 32. Qc2 Qd7 33. Kf1 Rd3 34. c4 Qd6 35. cxb5 cxb5 36. a4 Qd5 37. axb5 axb5 38. Qa2 Bc3 39. Ke2 Bb4 40. f3 Qd4 0-1

