{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O {This is by far the main line.} ({Another important move order is} 5. c3 Bd7 6. d4 g6 7. Bg5 {With this early bishop sally, White wants to disturb Black's coordination.} (7. O-O Bg7 {transposes to 5.0-0.}) 7... Be7 $1 {In my opinion, this is the most precise move.} ({It goes without saying that} 7... f6 $5 {is possible as well. In this case, however, Black should go for a setup based on ...Nh6-f7. Smyslov liked to handle this line in a similar fashion.}) ({Wrong would be} 7... Nf6 $4 {You should definitely avoid this mistake. It's +4 according to the computer!} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. Bxf6 $18 {White is winning material.}) 8. Bxe7 {Since White has a space advantage, exchanges of minor pieces are more than welcome for us.} ({An important alternative is} 8. Be3 {when after} Nf6 9. Bc2 {Black has a choice.} ({In case of} 9. Nbd2 {Black is more than happy to grab the bishop pair by means of} Ng4 {with an excellent position.}) 9... O-O {This is the simplest.} ({Another decent option would be} 9... Bf8 $5 10. O-O Bg7 11. h3 O-O {tranposing to the main lines of the Smyslov Variation.}) 10. O-O Re8 11. h3 Bf8 {At the end of the day, the bishop will land on g7. We will transpose to a position that is covered under different move order.}) 8... Qxe7 $1 {This is an important moment. In Smyslov, we always develop the knight via f6. Do not play ...Nge7.} 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Rae8 $132 {We will cover similar positions with dark-squared bishops on the board. This version is definitely favorable for Black.} (11... Kh8 $132) ({With dark-squared bishops being exchanges, a very good idea would be} 11... b5 12. Bc2 Nh5 $132 {when Black is ready to increase the pressure with simple moves such as ...Qf6 and Nf4.})) 5... Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 {This is the main tabiya of the Differred Steinitz/Smyslov Spanish. Not much memorization is needed from now on. You just need to study the typical plans and ideas.} 8. Be3 $1 {This is pretty much the only system, where I don't castle so fast (nothing wrong with catling though) My idea, however, is to exploit the e3-bishop by going for ...Nf6-g4.} Nf6 9. Nbd2 {White prefers keeping the tension which is the right strategy.} ({With the bishop being committed to e3, closing the centre with} 9. d5 {is hardly a good idea. A logical continuation would be} Ne7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qc2 h6 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gf7f5] An important move in such positions. Before proceeding with ...Ng4 followed by ...f7-f5, we should prevent the idea Ng5-e6.} 12. c4 Ng4 {It's because of this move that I find the e3-bishop misplaced.} 13. Bd2 f5 14. Nc3 O-O $132 {[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8] ½-½ (22) Videki,S-Zsinka,L/Hungary 2000/ EXT 2009 Black has an excellent version of KID structure. One of his ideas is to double the rooks on the f-file. As we will see in many other lines, an extra possibility is to further undermine the centre by playing ...c7-c6.}) 9... Ng4 $1 {Very risky but aggressive and playable!} ({If you don't want to study any theory} 9... O-O $1 {is simple and good. You will just apply all the typical ideas.} 10. h3 {A typical move designed to secure the e3-bishop. In my opinion, keeping the central tension is White's best strategy in this line.} ({White is not ready for} 10. d5 $2 Ne7 11. Bxd7 Qxd7 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4,Gf7f5] since his bishop as well as the d2-knight are highly misplaced. Black will follow with ...Ng4 on the next move.} 12. Ne1 Ng4 $15 13. Nc2 {A sad necessity. In KID structures, White is never happy to part with the dark-squared bishop.} ({In case of} 13. Bg5 {Black's most precise reaction is} f6 $1 ({Of course,} 13... f5 {is playable as well.}) 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 f5 16. exf5 Nf6 $17 {[%cal Ge7f5] Black has a huge advantage here. He is ready to proceed with ... Nxf5 followed by ...h7-h5. The g3-bishop is much more problematic than the one on g7.}) 13... f5 14. f3 $2 {This move leads to further weakening of the dark squares.} Nxe3 15. Nxe3 Bh6 16. Re1 ({After} 16. Qe2 {[%csl Rb2,Re2,Re3]} Qb5 $19 {White is losing material.}) 16... Qb5 $3 $19 {After this amazing move, White's position is resignable.} 17. Qb3 Bxe3+ 18. Rxe3 Qc5 19. Nf1 f4 $19 {1/2-1/2 Ye,J-Short,N/Beijing 2003/CBM 098/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 10... Re8 {This typical move is designed to put indirect pressure on the e4-pawn. The idea is to provoke White to release the tension with either dxe5 or d4-d5.} ({Since White has committed to Be3, Black can even consider} 10... Nh5 11. Rc1 Qe8 {[%cal Gf7f5] playing for ...f7-f5. For instance, the typical Spanish move} 12. Bc2 $2 {is already a mistake.} f5 $36 ({Further preparing ...f7-f5 with} 12... Kh8 {is another good option. It turns out that after} 13. Re1 {Black can play} f5 {regardless of the opposition along the e-file.} 14. exf5 gxf5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bc5 Rf6 $17 {1/2-1/2 (64) Paravyan,D-Firouzja,A/chess.com INT 2020/[,ÃéÜííçò] Black has an obvious advantage. He can proceed with simple moves such as ... e5-e4 followed by ...Nf4, and ...Rg6.} ({is very good as well.} 16... Rg8 $1 $17)) 13. dxe5 dxe5 $1 ({The alternative} 13... f4 14. Bd4 Nxe5 $132 {deserves attention as well.} (14... dxe5)) 14. Bb3+ Kh8 15. Bc5 Rf6 {Black has an excellent play. It's very difficult to suggest a constructive plan for White in this position.}) 11. Bb3 h6 {By taking control of the g5-square, Black is already threatening to take on e4.} ({The immediate} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 Nxe4 $2 {runs into} 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Bxf7+ {[%cal Gf3g5] with Ng5 to follow if Black takes the bishop.}) 12. Bc2 {White has nothing better than this passive move.} ({After} 12. Re1 exd4 {the vulnerable e4-pawn forces White to play} 13. Nxd4 {Black, however, has decent counterplay in this structure.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd7c6] This is one of the possible idea. Besides some annoying ...Nd3 ideas, Black is planning to proceed with ...c7-c5 followed by ...Bc6.} ({Another very good option is} 13... Na5 14. Bc2 c5 15. N4f3 b5 $132 {Once again, playing with Black is easier. In my opinion, the e4-pawn is more vulnerable than the one on e4.}) (13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. Bxf7+ Kxf7 16. Qf3+) 14. Bc2 c5 15. N4f3 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Bc6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gd8c7,Gc7b7] ГйЬннзтГйЬннзт] Practically speaking, Black is already better. He can increase the pressure by playing ...b7-b5 followed by transferring the queen to b7.}) 12... Nh5 13. Re1 Qf6 $132 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gd7c8,Gd6d5,Gd4d5,Gd4e5] 1-0 (48) Martinez Alcantara,J-Oparin,G/chess.com INT 2020 In positions with a central tension, the move ...Nh5 is often followed by ...Qf6. The next move is going to be ...Nf4. Our idea always remains the same - forcing White to clarify the tension in the centre.}) 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 ({Even worse is} 12. Bxc6 $6 {when Black should play} bxc6 $1 {increasing the central control and getting the possibility to play on the semi-open b-file.} ({A tactical mistake is} 12... Bxc6 $2 {which leaves the g4-knight unprotected. After} 13. Nxg5 fxg5 14. Qxg4 $18 {White is winning.}) 13. Bg3 O-O $36 {Black is already slightly better. The flexible pawn structure gives him many possibilities to open the position for the bishop pair. Of course, a concrete calculation is required.}) 12... h5 {Now, White should reckon with the threat of ...h5-h4.} 13. h3 {This is the safer continuation.} ({In case of} 13. h4 {my suggestion is} Qe7 {[%cal Gg7h6,Ge7g7,Ge8c8] planning to proceed with ... Bh6 followed by ...Qg7, and even ...0-0-0, when needed.} 14. Re1 {Keeping the central tension is the normal strategy in such positions.} ({After} 14. dxe5 {I very much like} Ncxe5 $5 {Trying to exchange the f3-knight which is an important defender of the king.} ({Of course,} 14... dxe5 $5 {is possible as well.}) 15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 16. Nd4 gxh4 {We want to open the g-file for the purposes of the attack. We shouldn't care about the pawn structure!} 17. Bxh4 O-O-O 18. Nf5 Nh6 $36 {immediately challenging the knight and clearing the g-file for the rook. In my opinion, Black's play is easier.}) 14... Bh6 15. b4 {A logical move, anticipating ...0-0-0.} ({After} 15. dxe5 $2 fxe5 $15 {Black also gains access to the f-file.}) ({Another illustrative line is} 15. Nf1 Qg7 16. b4 gxh4 17. Bxh4 Rg8 {when the play on the g-file shouldn't be underestimated. In a practical game, White's position is extremely dangerous.} 18. g3 {The best move.} ({After} 18. Ng3 $4 Nxf2 19. Kxf2 Bf4 $19 {Black is winning on the spot.}) (18. Bb3 $4 Nxf2 {is losing as well.}) 18... Nd8 19. Bb3 Ne6 $36 20. a4 Rf8 $1 $36 {White's position seems dangerous. After ...0-0-0 followed by ...Rde8, Black can consider either ...f6-f5 or ...Nf4.} ({The immediate} 20... Nf4 $15 {is possible as well.})) 15... Qg7 $1 {The most principled choice.} ({The structure arising after} 15... O-O $5 16. dxe5 fxe5 17. hxg5 Bxg5 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Nf3 Qg7 $132 {also offers Black an excellent counterplay.}) 16. Rb1 O-O {In practice, this extremely complicated position is easier for Black. White can easily go wrong here. For instance, a huge mistake would be} 17. hxg5 $2 $17 ({After} 17. dxe5 {I prefer} Ncxe5 {trying to exchange some pieces.}) 17... fxg5 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 $17 {Black's bishop pair as well as attacking chances provide him with an obvious advantage.} ({Another good option is} 18... bxc6 $1 19. dxe5 h4 20. Bh2 dxe5 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black.} ({or} 20... Nxh2 21. Nxh2 g4 $17 {when White is under a dangerous attack.}))) 13... Nh6 14. Re1 {White has nothing better than keeping the tension.} ({A huge mistake would be} 14. dxe5 $2 fxe5 $17 15. h4 {when Black shouldn't close the kingside but play} Bf6 $3 16. hxg5 Bxg5 $17 {with a tremendous advantage. We practically have a free attack going on the kingside.}) 14... Ne7 $1 {This idea of mine is a logical improvement over the game Kasimdzhanov - Mamedyarov. The idea is pretty simple. We want to transfer the knight to g6.} 15. Bxd7+ {Strategically speaking, this exchange is good for White. On the other hand, however, every exchange of minor pieces helps Black to solve his space problems.} ({After} 15. Bb3 Ng6 $132 {White can easily find himself in a difficult position. The following line is quite illustrative -} 16. Nc4 Qe7 17. Ne3 O-O-O 18. Nd5 Qe8 $17 {with an obvious advantage for Black. White does not have a constructive plan. At the same time, Black can play ... h5-h4 followed by ...g5-g4.}) ({It goes without saying that after} 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bb3 Ng6 $36 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ge8c8] Black's play is easier. The next moves are ...Qe7 followed by ...0-0-0.}) 15... Qxd7 16. Nf1 $2 {This normal move is already a mistake.} ({Similar is} 16. Nc4 h4 17. Bh2 g4 $17 18. hxg4 Nxg4 $17 {when Black is attacking for free.}) ({Probably, White should go for the endgame arising after} 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nc4 O-O-O 18. Qxd7+ Rxd7 19. Rad1 Nf7 20. Rxd7 Kxd7 21. Rd1+ Ke6 $15 {Even here, however, Black is slightly better because of his more active king and the g3-bishop which is out of play.} 22. Ne1 Nd6 $3 {A very nice move. The exchange on d6 would allow Black to reinforce the centre.} ({It's also possible to start with} 22... h4 $1 23. Bh2 Nd6 24. Nxd6 cxd6 $17 {[%cal Gf6f5] Black has a huge advantage. The next move is going to be ...f5.}) 23. Nxd6 cxd6 24. f3 f5 $17) 16... h4 17. Bh2 g4 18. hxg4 Nxg4 $19 {The attack is devastating.} *

