{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. dxe5 {This line is generally harmless but Black should know a few precise moves. White will try to build and develop some initiative in a symmetrical pawn structure.} Nxe5 $1 {As usual, this is the best recapture when the bishop is on g7.} 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. f4 {This is the only way to fight for some initiative.} ({The endgame arising after} 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {is completely harmless for Black. We can even fight for a win in view of the more active king. The following lines show how Black should arrange his pieces in this endgame.} 12. Be3 ({Nothing gives} 12. Rd1+ Ke6 $15 {when Black is already slightly better.}) ({In case of} 12. f3 {we can even consider} Bh6 {because the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is favourable for Black. Note that after} 13. Bxh6 Nxh6 14. Nd2 Ke6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh6f7,Gf7d6] the knight is not misplaced on h6. We can easily activate it by means of ... f7-f6 followed by ...Nh6-f7-d6. The attempt to create queenside play by means of} 15. Nb3 b6 16. a4 {does not work in view of} a5 {[%csl Ra4] fixing the queenside structure. Later on, we can transfer the knight all the way to c4.}) 12... Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f7,Gf7d6,Gf7f6] Once again, Black is planning to transfer the knight to d6.} ({It goes without saying that} 12... Bh6 {is possible again. For instance, after} 13. Bxh6 Nxh6 14. Nd2 Ke6 15. Nb3 b6 16. Rfd1 f6 17. f3 Nf7 18. Rd3 Nd6 $132 {Black enjoys a decent position.} ({Another good idea is} 18... Rhd8 19. Rad1 Rxd3 20. Rxd3 Nd6 {By exchanging one pair of rooks we reduce White's counterplay. Now, we are ready to start gaining space on both wings.})) 13. f3 f6 14. Nd2 Nf7 15. Nb3 b6 16. Rfd1+ Ke6 17. Kf2 Nd6 $15 {In my opinion, Black is already slightly better. His main ideas are ...f6-f5, and ...a6-a5-a4. Also, White should reckon with ...Nc4 at any moment.}) ({Nothing gives} 10. Be3 Nf6 {when Black is doing completely fine.} 11. f3 {This looks like the most natural move.} Qe7 {Black is playing for more than equality. He is planning to castle long.} ({Another, quieter, approach would have been} 11... b5 12. Bb3 Qe7 {with a promising position.}) 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. Nd2 O-O-O $132 {Black has excellent chances.}) 10... Bxa4 $1 {This is an important concept. Black deflects the white queen on a4 in order to win an important tempo.} 11. Qxa4+ b5 12. Qb3 {The most natural continuation.} ({Another important line is} 12. Qc2 exf4 13. Bxf4 Nf6 14. Bg5 {This is the only way to fight for something.} ({After} 14. Nd2 O-O $132 {Black has nothing to worry about since} 15. Bg5 {can be met with} Qd6 {when Black has a promising position.}) 14... Qe7 $3 {This is the move to remember.} ({Note that} 14... Qd6 $4 {loses to} 15. Qf2 $18) 15. e5 {Fortunately, this aggressive move does not work tactically.} ({This time,} 15. Qf2 {will be answered with} Ng4 $3 16. Bxe7 (16. Qh4 Qe6 $17) 16... Nxf2 17. Rxf2 Kxe7 18. Nd2 Rad8 $15 {when Black is slightly better in view of his better structure and strong bishop.} ({or even} 18... b4 $15)) 15... Qxe5 {The following couple of moves are quite forced -} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qf2 Be7 18. Qxf7+ Kd7 19. Rd1+ ({Another instructive line is} 19. Qf3 Raf8 20. Qh3+ Kc6 $1 21. Nd2 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Qd5 24. Nf3 Kb7 $19 {when Black has a decisive advantage in view of the domination of his pieces.}) 19... Kc6 20. Qf3+ Kb6 $17 {Black is clearly better.1-0 (75) Marjanovic,S-Khamatgaleev,A/Kavala 2002}) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 ({The alternative} 13. Rxf4 {does not work in view of} Nf6 $1 (13... Nh6 $15) 14. e5 Nd5 $17 {Black is clearly better. Of course, Rd4 will be met by ...c7-c6.}) 13... Nf6 {My analysis shows that White cannot equalize in this position.} 14. Be5 ({The straightforward} 14. e5 {will be answered with} Nd5 15. Rd1 c6 16. Bg3 O-O $17 {Black has a huge advantage in this position.}) ({Nothing gives} 14. a4 O-O {Black is more than happy to sacrifice the b5-pawn in order to open the position.} 15. axb5 {The most principled choice.} ({After} 15. Nd2 c6 16. axb5 cxb5 $17 {Black is better due to his better structure and the vulnerable white king.}) ({A game of Smyslov himself followed with} 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. axb5 Be5 $15 {0-1 (43) Xie,J-Smyslov,V/Marbella 1999/CBM 074/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 15... axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Qxb5 Qa7+ 18. Kh1 Nxe4 19. Qe2 Re8 20. Qf3 Nf6 $17 {Black is better in view of the white vulnerable king.} (20... f5)) 14... O-O $17 {1/2-1/2 Svidler,P-Artemiev,V/chess.com INT 2021} *

