{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. Bg5 $5 {This is another important continuation. By means of this early attack on the queen, White wants to disturb Black's coordination.} ({Too passive is} 8. Bc2 {Black can just play} Nf6 {As we know, the structure arising after} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 {is favourable for Black. The main idea is to seize space on the queenside. Let's take a look at a possible variation -} 11. f3 O-O 12. Be3 Qe7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is already planning to start gaining queenside space with ... c7-c5.} 13. Qe2 c5 14. Nd2 b5 15. Nb3 Rfc8 16. Qf2 Bf8 $15 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gd7e6] Black is better. If allowed, he will follow with ...c5-c4 and ...Be6.}) ({Too slow is} 8. Bb3 $6 Nf6 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3 {White cannot go without this move.} ({In case of} 10. Bg5 $6 h6 11. Bh4 {Black can even put pressure on d4 by means of} Bg4 $1 ({It goes without saying that the standard procedure} 11... exd4 $1 12. cxd4 g5 13. Bg3 g4 14. d5 Na5 15. Nh4 Nh5 $17 {is possible as well. Black has a huge advantage.}) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 $36 {with a strong initiative.}) 10... Re8 11. Nbd2 (11. Ng5 Re7) 11... Na5 $1 {Black immediately makes use of the move Bb3. The idea is to follow with ...c7-c5.} ({Another very good possibility is} 11... Nh5 12. Nf1 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. d5 b5 15. Qe2 Nc4 $1 {When you have time, always use the possibility to improve the knight in this typical way. Black is doing fine.}) 12. Bc2 c5 13. d5 b5 $132 {Black has sufficient counterplay. He can already consider ...c5-c4. A dubious idea for White would be} 14. b4 $6 {since the queenside becomes way too vulnerable now.} ({The move} 14. b3 {is very well met by} Bh6 $1 {I would like to share a very important rule of thumb. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is very good when the centre is closed with d4-d5 or White opted for a symmetrical structure with dxe5. This exchange is not good when White keeps the tension in the centre.} ({Another decent option would be} 14... Qc7 $1 15. Nf1 Nh5 16. Be3 ({or} 16. Bd2 Nb7 17. Rc1 c4 18. b4 a5 $132 {with decent counterplay.}) 16... Nb7 17. Qd2 c4 18. b4 a5 19. a3 Ra6 {Once again, Black gets his typical queenside counterplay.}) 15. Nf1 {White cannot delay this move forever. Otherwise, Black will prepare the advance ...f7-f5.} Bxc1 16. Qxc1 Nh5 17. Qd2 Nb7 18. Ne3 Kg7 19. Ng4 Nf4 $132 {When the dark-squared bishops have been exchanged, installing a knight on f4 is a typical idea. Black is doing more than fine in this position.}) 14... Nb7 15. a3 Qc7 16. Nf1 a5 {That's the problem with b2-b4. White cannot easily keep the queenside intact. The play might continue} 17. Rb1 Rec8 18. Bd3 axb4 19. axb4 c4 20. Bc2 Ra2 $15 {Once again, Black is ready to combine his queenside play with kingside activity. The following lines show how White can easily find himself in trouble.} 21. Ne3 ({Another direction would be} 21. Ng3 Rca8 22. Bd2 Nd8 {As always, the knight is going to f7.} 23. Nh2 Ne8 24. Rc1 f6 25. Rf1 (25. Ng4 Bxg4 26. Qxg4 Nf7 $17) 25... R8a3 26. f4 exf4 27. Rxf4 Nf7 {Black is better. The knight will soon land on e5.}) 21... Rca8 22. Bd2 Bh6 23. Nf1 Bxd2 24. Qxd2 Nh5 $17 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gb7d8,Gd8f7] Once again, Black enjoys a classical advantage. He will now transfer the knight to f7.}) 8... Nf6 $1 {Very safe and very good! In fact, White will have trouble with his g5-bishop since we will play ...h7-h6! soon. The bishop will end up on h4 and then we usually play Nh5!! at a good moment. In such cases, the bishop stands horribly on h4, and Black gains the initiative!} (8... f6 $5 {This is how Smyslov treated this variation but it's very risky and I prefer to avoid it!}) 9. Re1 {An important moment. White protects the e4-pawn and wants to take on e5. That's why we should immediately play ... b7-b5.} ({Obviously, White can play} 9. d5 Ne7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {when Black has a perfect KID type of position. We will discuss similar positions on many occasions.}) (9. Bxc6 $1 {This drawish line is very important and you need to know it by heart!} Bxc6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 $1 {This is the only challenging continuation.} ({The endgame arising after} 11. Qxd8+ $2 Rxd8 12. Nxe5 Bxe4 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nd2 Bf5 $17 {is much better for Black since the bishop pair is very strong in this open position.}) 11... Qxd1 $1 12. Rxd1 Nxe4 $1 {So far, Black is playing only moves.} 13. Bf4 $1 {This time, White needs to be precise. Actually, 13.Bf4 is the only way of avoiding clearly worse position.} ({In case of} 13. Nxc6 $6 Nxg5 14. Na5 Ne6 $15 {Black is better. Of course, the b7-pawn cannot be taken because of ...Rb8.}) 13... g5 $3 {With this precise move, Black is already fighting for an advantage.} 14. Nxc6 $1 {Again, this is the only way to keep the balance.} ({The natural} 14. Bg3 {will be met by} Nxg3 15. Nxc6 Nf5 16. Na5 b6 (16... Nd6 $15) 17. Re1+ Kd7 $15 {with an advantage for Black.}) 14... gxf4 15. Re1 $1 {Again, very precise!} ({After} 15. Na5 Nc5 $1 16. Re1+ Kd7 $1 17. Na3 Rae8 $17 {Black is far away from equality in view of his misplaced knights.}) 15... f5 16. f3 {White should play actively.} ({Black can easily overtake the initiative in this position. Let's take a look at the following line -} 16. Nb4 $2 O-O-O 17. f3 Nc5 18. Na3 Na4 $17 {It turns out that White does not have a comfortable way of defending the b2-pawn. A typical follow-up would be} 19. Rab1 Nxb2 20. Rxb2 Bxc3 21. Rbb1 Bxe1 22. Rxe1 Rd4 23. Nac2 Rc4 $19 {when Black is winning.}) 16... bxc6 17. fxe4 Rb8 $1 {In my opinion, this is the most precise continuation.} ({The alternative} 17... O-O-O $5 {is playable as well.}) 18. exf5+ Kf7 19. Re2 ({After} 19. Nd2 Rxb2 20. Ne4 Rd8 21. Rf1 (21. Ng5+ $2 Kf6 $19) 21... Bh6 $132 {the position is balanced but playing with Black is easier.} (21... Rd3 22. Rxf4 Bxc3 $132)) 19... Rhe8 20. Rxe8 Kxe8 21. b3 Rb5 22. Na3 Rxf5 23. Re1+ Kd7 24. Nb1 c5 $132 {Again, Black has every chance to outplay his opponent.}) (9. Nbd2 {As we know, the typical Ruy Lopez play with the bishop already committed to g5 does not work quite well. First of all, Black should clarify the position of the bishop by playing} h6 10. Bh4 b5 $1 {Again, White protects e4 and starts threatening our e5-pawn! So, we go ...b7-b5! to deal with it!} 11. Bc2 O-O 12. Re1 {The most natural move.} ({An inacurracy would be} 12. Nb3 $6 {since the knight is misplaced on b3. Also, the e4-pawn is getting vulnerable. Black should play} exd4 13. cxd4 Re8 $3 $15 {immediately putting pressure on e4. The threat now is ...g6-g5.} ({The alternative} 13... g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 {is possible as well. Black has excellent counterplay. 1/2-1/2 (39) Firouzja, A-Wang Hao/St Petersburg RUS 2018}) 14. Re1 {White should try to keep the structure intact.} ({After} 14. d5 Nb4 15. Bb1 a5 16. a3 Na6 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. He is ready to proceed with ...a5-a4 followed by ...Nc5. It's clear that the h4-bishop cannot contribute to the queenside battle.}) 14... g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 {I would take Black in this position. Sooner or later he will obtain the bishop pair. Additionally, White's centre is under a lot of pressure in this position.}) 12... Re8 {Once again, we have reached a typical position. Here, an instructive mistake would be} 13. a3 $2 {In this lines White should play fast h2-h3. Otherwise, he should always reckon with ...g6-g5 followed by either ...g5-g4 or ...Nh5.} ({Better would have been} 13. h3 $5 {when I would prefer} Qc8 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc7c5] planning to proceed with ...Na5 followed by ...c7-c5. Let's take a look at a sample line -} 14. Nf1 Na5 ({Another good possibility is} 14... Nh5) 15. b3 c5 16. d5 Nh5 17. Ne3 Nb7 18. Qd2 {Both sides arranged the pieces in the desired way. Now, Black can opt for the familiar procedure -} c4 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Ra6 {[%cal Gc8c7,Ge8a8] Once again, Black is ready to fight for the a-file by means of ...Qc7 followed by .. .Rea8. Even though the following line is by no means forced, it shows how the game might develop.} 21. Nh2 Qc7 22. Nhg4 Kh7 23. f3 Rea8 24. Rab1 axb4 25. axb4 Ra2 26. Qd1 Nd8 27. Bf2 f6 28. Rc1 Nf7 $17 {Black is better. He will start gradually preparing the advance ...f6-f5.}) 13... exd4 $1 14. cxd4 g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 $17 16. d5 Ne7 17. Rb1 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Ng6 $17 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh6h5] Black's advantage is clear. He is ready to proceed with ...g5-g4 followed by .. .h6-h5-h4.}) 9... b5 10. Bc2 h6 11. Bh4 O-O {Once again, White is at crossroads. As always, the h4-bishop turns out to be misplaced.} 12. dxe5 ({Closing the centre with} 12. d5 {is never dangerous for Black. After} Ne7 13. Nbd2 g5 14. Bg3 Ng6 $15 {Black is just better since the g3-bishop is out of play. The next step is to prepare ...f7-f5.}) ({In case of} 12. Nbd2 {the standard reaction is} exd4 ({Another very good move is} 12... Re8 13. dxe5 ({As usual,} 13. h3 {is well met by} exd4 14. cxd4 g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 16. Bh2 g4 17. hxg4 ({After} 17. d5 Ne7 18. hxg4 Bxg4 19. Qc1 Ng6 $36 {the superior piece activity gives Black a huge initiative.}) 17... Bxg4 18. Nb3 Nb4 19. Bb1 c5 $15 {Black has the upperhand.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Nb3 Qe7 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is taking the c5-square under control. He is now ready to proceed with the thematic ...c7-c5-c4.}) 13. cxd4 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 $15 {Black was already better in the game 0-1 Harikrishna, P-Fressinet, L A possible continuation would have been} 15. d5 Nb4 16. a3 Nxc2 17. Qxc2 Rc8 18. Nf1 f5 $17 {with a huge advantage.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Nd2 c5 {We have seen this typical structure on multiple occasions. A possible follow-up would be} 15. Nf3 Qc7 16. Qe2 Nh5 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black.} *

