{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. h3 {We should always consider this useful move that White can play at any time. Usually, White's intention is to keep the central tension as long as possible.} Nf6 (8... b5 $5 {This will more or less transpose to the regular 8.h3-Nf6 lines.}) 9. Re1 ({We should always reckon with} 9. Bxc6 $6 Bxc6 10. dxe5 {We have reached a very important moment. In such situations, you should consider both ...Nxe4 and ...dxe5. Sometimes, both moves are correct but very often only one of them works. Therefore, we always need to calculate. In this concrete position, both moves are playable.} Nxe4 $15 {At the end of the day, Black will end up in a better position due to the bishop pair.} ({or} 10... dxe5 $15)) (9. d5 {This move is not well combined with h2-h3. In a closed KID type of position, the h3-pawn will be a hook for Black's attack.} Ne7 10. Bxd7+ {This move is usually played automatically.} ({Note that Black is already threatening ...b7-b5. Therefore, a move such as} 10. Re1 {will be answered by} b5 {Gaining space on the queenside is important in this structure. Later on, when Black decides to undermine the centre with ...c7-c6, White will not have the possibility of c3-c4.} 11. Bc2 O-O 12. Nbd2 c6 {Since we have played ...b7-b5, White cannot support the centre by means of c3-c4.} ({Another good idea is} 12... Nh5 {preparing the advance ...f7-f5.}) 13. dxc6 Bxc6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Gd6d5] This structure which is also typical for the Najdorf offers Black an excellent counterplay. His main idea is to gradually prepare the advance ...d6-d5.}) 10... Qxd7 11. Re1 O-O 12. c4 Nh5 13. Nc3 h6 {As we already know very well, before playing ...f7-f5, we should take the f5-square under control. Otherwise, White will play Ng5-e6.} 14. Bd2 Qe8 {Another important preparatory move. Black overprotects the h5-knight. Therefore, after ...f7-f5, White will not be able to play exf5 and answer ...gxf5 with Nxe5!.} ({By the way, the structure arising after} 14... f5 15. exf5 Nxf5 {is playable as well.} (15... gxf5 16. Nxe5)) 15. b4 f5 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gf5f4,Gg6g5,Ge8g6,Gh5f6,Gh6h5,Gg5g4] Black has an excellent counterplay on the kingside. The move h2-h3 definitely does not help White.}) 9... b5 $5 {This line is highly transpositional. The same position can also arise in White plays Re1 on move 8. White can overprotect the e4 pawn with} 10. Bc2 {but the bishop is a bit passive here.} O-O {This position can be reached via many move orders. That's why it's very important to understand it.} 11. Be3 {White wants to achieve harmonious development by following with Nbd2. In this case, the centre will be very well protected.} ({Another typical move is} 11. a4 {In this position, however, I find it rather harmless. In many cases, after ...exd4 cxd4, the b4-square will be available for the knight.} Re8 {Almost always we play this typical move. Besides overprotecting the e5-pawn, Black puts indirect pressure on e4.} 12. Nbd2 exd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 {Remember this typical move. The c6-knight is our most problematic piece in Ruy Lopez. Therefore, at the first given opportunity, we try to activate it. Black is ready to attack the centre with ...c7-c5.} 14. Bb3 ({After} 14. Bb1 c5 {Black has an excellent counterplay.} (14... bxa4 {is possible as well.})) 14... bxa4 {Before striking with ...c7-c5, Black wants to exchange the light-squared bishops.} (14... Nd3 $2 {is a tactical mistake in view of} 15. Bxf7+ $18) ({Another decent option is} 14... c5 {when a possible line would be} 15. dxc5 dxc5 16. axb5 Bxb5 (16... axb5 {can be considered as well.}) 17. Ng5 Ra7 {[%cal Gh7h6,Ga7d7,Gb4d3] The activity of the black pieces provides more than enough compensation for the slightly inferior structure.}) 15. Bxa4 Bxa4 ({Obviously, there is nothing wrong with} 15... c5 16. dxc5 dxc5 {with an excellent counterplay.}) 16. Rxa4 Nd3 17. Re2 c5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Rc4 Qb6 $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) ({Very often White starts with} 11. Bg5 {In this case, we should immediately clarify the position of the bishop by playing} h6 {when White's most principled approach is} 12. Bh4 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge5d4,Gc3d4,Gg6g5,Gf6h5,Gg5g4] As we will see from the lines below, the h4-bishop is often misplaced.} Qe8 {[%cal Gf6h5] A typical move which is designed to prepare ...Nh5.} ({Another very typical idea in such positions is} 12... Re8 13. Nbd2 exd4 14. cxd4 g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 {Pay attention to how Black uses the position of the bishop to gain important tempis.} 16. Bh2 g4 $36 {White's vulnerable centre offers Black decent counterplay in this position. The h2-bishops turns out to be out of play.} 17. hxg4 Bxg4) 13. Nbd2 Nh5 {By putting pressure on d4, Black wants to provoke White to clarify the position in the centre. For instance, we are always happy to see a move such as} 14. dxe5 $6 ({Better would have been} 14. Nf1 {when one of the possible options for Black is} Nd8 {[%cal Gd8e6] bringing the knight to e6. Later on, under favourable circumstances, Black can attack the centre with ...c7-c5.}) 14... Nxe5 {As a rule, when Black has a bishop on g7, taking on e5 with the knight is a better idea.} (14... dxe5 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5,Gb2b4,Ga2a4]}) 15. Nxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5]} 16. Nf1 Bf6 $1 {Another important idea. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is obviously favourable for Black. We see one more drawback of having the bishop on h4.} 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Rc2,Gd7]} 18. Ne3 c6 $15 {[%cal Gg8g7,Ge8e7,Gd7e6,Gh6h5,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Gf8d8] Black is ready to follow with simple moves such as ...Qe7, ...Kg7, and ...Be6. He is already slightly better due to his superior bishop and space advantage on the queenside.}) 11... Re8 12. Nbd2 {[%csl Gd2,Ge3][%cal Gf6h5,Gh7h6,Gd8f6,Gh5f4]} Qc8 {[%cal Gc8b7] 1-0 (51) Alekseev, E (2710)-Adhiban, B (2567) Tromsoe 2013 A very interesting idea by Adhiban. Black keeps the pressure on e4 so that White can not transfer the knight to f1. White can also hardly move his dark-squared bishop, so it is not simple to improve the position of his pieces. Black is also a little passive, but he can transfer the queen to the queenside and keep the position flexible until something starts happening. Our next two moves are going to be ...Qb7 and Rad8.} *

