{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. h3 Nf6 9. Re1 b5 $5 10. Bb3 {For the time being, White prefers keeping the bishop on this more active position. Nevertheless, there are two drawbacks behind this retreat. First of all, Black can always win an important tempo with ...Na5. Additionally, in some cases the e4-pawn will be less protected.} O-O 11. Nbd2 {The most natural continuation. As usual in Ruy Lopez, White is planning to bring the knight all the way to g3.} ({As a rule, we answer} 11. Bg5 $6 {with} h6 $1 {clarifying the position of the bishop.} 12. Bh4 Re8 13. Nbd2 ({We know that when our bishop is on g7, the move} 13. dxe5 {should be answered with} Nxe5 {In the position arising after} 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Nd2 c6 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd8c7,Gf6h5,Gh5f4,Gc6c5,Gc5c4,Gd7c6,Gf4e6,Ge6c5,Gh6h5,Gg7h6] Black has every chance to outplay his opponent.}) ({Closing the centre with} 13. d5 {is a strategical mistake here. After} Ne7 14. Nbd2 g5 15. Bg3 Ng6 {Black is definitely better. He will start preparing the advance ...f7-f5.}) 13... Na5 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5] This move should always be considered when the white bishop is on b3. Black is now ready to strike with .. .c7-c5.} ({Another good move is} 13... Qc8 $1 {Besides the usual ...Na5, Black also keeps the option of playing ...Nd8.}) 14. Bc2 c5 15. d5 {Since Black's tempis are more than fine, White closes the position.} ({In case of} 15. Nf1 $2 {[%csl Gc3,Gc5,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4,Ge5] Black is more than happy to play an open position after} cxd4 16. cxd4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Qb6 $17 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5c4] with a huge advantage for Black due to his superior piece activity.}) 15... c4 $1 $15 {Those of you who studied the lecture about typical Ruy Lopez strategies will find this move rather easily.} (15... Kh8 16. Nf1 Kg8 17. Bg5 Kh8 18. Bc1 Kg8 19. Ne3 c4 20. b4 cxb3 21. axb3 Qc7 22. Bd2 Nb7 23. b4 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge8c8,Gf6e8,Gf7f6,Gb7d8,Gd8f7,Gf6f5,Gc2d3,Gc3c4]}) 16. Nf1 ({The entire concept with ...c5-c4 works because} 16. b4 {will be answered with} cxb3 17. axb3 Qc7 {when White does not have a comfortable way of defending the c3-pawn. Once again, the bishop proves to be misplaced on h4.} 18. Re3 Nh5 $132 {[%cal Ga5b7,Gb7c5,Ga6a5] Black is ready to follow with ...Nb7, ...a6-a5, and ...Nc5. At some point, moves like ...Nf4, and ...f7-f5 can be considered as well.} (18... Nb7 19. b4 a5)) 16... Qc7 17. Qd2 Nh5 $15 {[%cal Gh5f4] When the bishop is on h4, the idea of putting a knight on f4 becomes very strong.} ({Obviously, a mistake would be} 17... Nb7 $2 {[%cal Gb7c5,Ga6a5,Ge8b8,Gb5b4] when after} 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Qxh6 {White is just a healthy pawn up.}) 18. Ng3 Nf4 {This move is connected with a deep positional idea.} ({Another possibility is} 18... Nxg3 19. Bxg3 Nb7 $15 {[%cal Gb7c5] planning ...Nc5.}) 19. Ne2 Nd3 $3 $17 {Black sacrifices a pawn in order to eliminate White's light-squared bishop and get the advance ...f7-f5. After} 20. Bxd3 cxd3 21. Qxd3 f5 22. Nd2 Nc4 $17 {Black has a huge advantage.}) 11... Re8 {Never forget about this important move. The idea is to prevent Nf1.} 12. Bc2 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] By overprotecting the e4-pawn, White insists on the maneuver Nf1-g3.} ({The immediate} 12. Nf1 $2 {does not work in view of} exd4 {Now, the tempting} (12... Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. d5 c4 15. b4 cxb3 16. axb3 Qc7 17. Bd2 Nb7 18. b4 (18. Ng3 Nc5 19. b4 Na4 20. Bxa4 bxa4 21. c4 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1,Gd2e3,Gc4c5]}) (18. Ne3 Nc5 19. b4 Na4 20. Bxa4 bxa4 21. c4)) 13. Ng5 {is not enough.} ({Another important line is} 13. cxd4 Nxe4 14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 15. Rxe4 Rxe4 16. Ng5+ Kf8 17. Nxe4 Nxd4 $17 {White does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 13... d5 $3 {This is the thematic move that you should remember. A logical follow-up would be} 14. exd5 Rxe1 15. Qxe1 Na5 16. cxd4 Nxb3 17. axb3 Nxd5 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black.}) ({Fortunately, the move} 12. Ng5 {is very well met by} Re7 {when White will be forced to release the central tension.} 13. Nf1 ({Black is more than happy to see the move} 13. d5 {In this case, we will play the thematic} Na5 14. Bc2 c6 {when White cannot sustain his space advantage -} 15. b4 Nc4 16. Nxc4 bxc4 17. dxc6 Bxc6 $17 18. Qe2 Rc8 19. Rd1 Rd7 20. Nf3 {This position was reached in the game Chirila, I - Halkias, S, 2009. Now, Black should have played} d5 $3 $19 21. Nxe5 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxe5 23. Bxg6 Re7 $19 {with a winning position.}) 13... h6 $15 {Black is already better. White cannot simply retreat because the e4-pawn will be lost.} 14. dxe5 dxe5 ({Another very good option is} 14... Nxe5 15. Nf3 Nc4 $15 {with an advantage for Black.}) 15. Nf3 Na5 16. Bc2 c5 $15 {Black achieved everything he was dreaming for.}) ({Completely harmless is} 12. dxe5 {Since our bishop is already on g7, we should play} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 ({Obviously, after} 13. Nd4 c5 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gc5c4,Gd6d5] followed by ...Bc6, Black has a huge advantage.}) 13... dxe5 {Black is already slightly better in this structure. His main idea to improve the position is based on gaining space on the queenside by means of ... c7-c5-c4. Let's take a look at some examples.} 14. Nf3 ({Nothing changes} 14. Nf1 {when again Black will play} c5 15. Bg5 c4 16. Bc2 Qc7 (16... Be6) 17. Ne3 Bc6 $15 {with an advantage.}) 14... c5 $15 {[%cal Gc5c4] Don't forget this thematic move. Black is planning to follow with ...c5-c4.} 15. Be3 ({Another instructive line would be} 15. Bg5 c4 16. Bc2 h6 17. Bh4 Qc7 $1 {Escaping the pin and preparing ...Nh5-f4.} 18. Qe2 ({In case of} 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Qe2 Kg7 20. Rad1 Be6 $15 {Black's bishop pair, as well as queenside space, provides him with an obvious advantage.}) 18... Nh5 $1 {This is always a good idea when the white bishop is on h4.} 19. Bg3 Nxg3 20. fxg3 Be6 {Once again, Black has a considerable advantage.} ({Another good possibility is} 20... h5 21. Rf1 Bh6 {when Black is again obviously better.})) ({It goes without saying that} 15. Bd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 c4 17. Bg5 f6 $17 {gives Black a huge advantage. The d5-pawn is actually a liability.}) 15... c4 16. Bc2 Qc7 $15 {Again, Black enjoys his typical advantage.}) (12. a3 {With this move White takes the b4-square under control. Hence, after Bc2, Black wouldn't have the option of playing ...exd4 followed by ...Nb4. Also, in some cases, the white bishop will have the a2-square at its disposal.} h6 $1 {As we will see, this subtle move is a prophylaxis against 13.Nf1. Obviously, Black has more than one good move. In order to better understand the arising positions, we shall take a look at some alternatives.} ({The idea of putting pressure on d4 by means of} 12... Nh5 {is very typical as well. We are always happy to see} 13. d5 {when after} Ne7 14. Nf1 Rf8 {Black starts preparing ...f7-f5.} (14... Nc8 {is possible as well.}) 15. Bg5 ({In case of} 15. Bc2 {already to break} c6 {works very well since the white bishop is not on the diagonal a2-g8.} ({preparing ...f7-f5 is possible as well.} 15... h6) 16. dxc6 Bxc6 {We already know that this structure is quite good for Black. The advance ...d6-d5 is our main strategic idea.} 17. Bg5 h6 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Ne3 Nf6 $15 {Black is already slightly better. He will proceed with simple moves such as ...Rad8 followed by ...Qb7, thus increasing the pressure on e4. We are always happy to see a move like} 20. Nd5 {because after} Bxd5 {White is forced to recapture with a pawn.} 21. exd5 Qb7 $1 $17 22. Bb3 Nd7 23. Nd2 f5 $17 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gd7e5] The mobile central majority provides Black with a huge advantage in this position. The is a perfect version of the Najdorf.}) 15... h6 16. Bh4 Nf6 17. Bc2 Kh8 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gf7f5] planning ...Nfg8 followed by ...f7-f5.} ({Another decent possibility is} 17... g5 18. Bg3 Ng6 19. Qd2 (19. Ne3 Kh8) 19... g4 20. hxg4 Nxg4 21. Ne3 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 Qf6 $132 {with an excellent counterplay.}) 18. Qd2 Nfg8 19. Ne3 f5 $15 {Black is already better since his kingside play is pretty straightforward.}) (12... Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gc7c5] You should always consider this thematic move which is usually connected with ...Nd8 followed by ...c7-c5.} 13. Bc2 Nd8 {The most straightforward.} ({Another very interesting idea is} 13... Nh5 {putting pressure on d4. The idea is to meet} 14. Nf1 Na5 {[%cal Gc7c5] besides preparing ...c7-c5, in some cases, Black can also play ... Nc4.} 15. b3 ({In case of} 15. a4 exd4 16. cxd4 Qb7 {Black enjoys a decent counterplay.}) 15... c5 16. d5 c4 $3 17. b4 Nb3 {This is another point behind . ..Na5. Black sacrifices a pawn in order to eliminate White light-squared bishop. Hence, the advance ...f7-f5 will be easier now.} 18. Bxb3 cxb3 19. Qxb3 Ra7 $3 $17 {[%cal Ga7c7] Another great move. Before proceeding with ...f7-f5, we need to rule out any c3-c4 ideas.} 20. Bd2 Rc7 21. Ne3 f5 $15 {Black is already better.}) 14. b4 {A logical move. White wants to prevent Black from gaining a lot of space on the queenside.} ({In case of} 14. Nf1 {a very good reaction is} c5 15. d5 c4 $132 {[%cal Gd8b7,Gb7c5,Gc8c7,Ge8b8,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] As we already know from the lecture about typical Ruy Lopez strategies, the move . ..c5-c4 is a good idea when White has a pawn on a3. Now, White cannot undermine our space advantage by means of b2-b3 (which would have been possible with a pawn on a2). Black is ready to bring his knight to c5.}) 14... Nh5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nb3 Ne6 $132 {Black is doing fine. Under favourable circumstances, Black will carry out the advance ...c7-c5.}) ({Another very typical idea to have in mind is} 12... Qb8 $1 {Usually this move is connected with ...Qb6. At the same time, Black is often ready to carry out ...a6-a5.} 13. Bc2 ({In case of} 13. Ba2 {we can play} Qb6 {putting additional pressure on d4. It's important that White cannot play} 14. Nf1 $2 {because of the following line -} exd4 15. cxd4 Nxe4 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Rxe4 Rxe4 18. Ng5+ Kg8 19. Qb3+ ({Of course, after} 19. Nxe4 Qxd4 $19 {Black is just winning.}) 19... Be6 {This is the point!} 20. Nxe6 Na5 21. Qa2 Nc4 $17 {Black is close to winning.}) 13... a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb8b6] Black wants to gain further space on the queenside with ...a5-a4. Then, he will be ready to proceed with ...Qb6. The move} 14. a4 {allows} exd4 15. cxd4 Nb4 $36 16. axb5 Bxb5 {when Black has the initiative.}) ({Given the fact that White has committed to a2-a3, a perfectly playable option is} 12... Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. d5 c4 15. Nf1 Nb7 16. Ng3 Nc5 $132 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge8b8,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] with sufficient counterplay.}) 13. Ba2 {This is a logical follow-up of the move a2-a3. White keeps the bishop on this active diagonal and sidesteps the idea ...Na5 followed by ...c7-c5. On the downside, the d2-knight is tied to the defence of the e4-pawn.} ({In case of} 13. Nf1 {Black can play} exd4 14. cxd4 Rxe4 $3 {This is the correct way of capturing the pawn.} ({Wrong is} 14... Nxe4 {in view of} 15. Qc2 Nf6 16. Qxg6) ({In such positions, the idea} 14... Na5 15. Bc2 c5 16. d5 Nc4 {Also comes into consideration. Black enjoys a perfect Benoni structure.}) 15. Rxe4 Nxe4 16. Qc2 Qe8 {This move allows Black to keep everything together. White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({A thematic reaction to} 13. Bc2 {is} Nh5 $1 {The idea is that} 14. Nf1 {is usually well met by} Na5 $1 {followed by either ...Nc5 or ...c7-c5-c4.} 15. b3 ({In response to} 15. b4 {Black can play} Nc4 $132 16. Ne3 Nb6 $5 17. Ng4 Nf4 $36 {with a promising position.}) ({We already know that the position arising after} 15. Rb1 c5 16. d5 c4 $15 {is favourable for Black. He is ready to proceed with ...Nb7-c5.}) (15. g4 $6 Nf6 $132) 15... c5 $1 (15... exd4 16. cxd4 c5 $132) 16. d5 c4 $3 17. b4 Nb3 $3 {We are already familiar with this amazing idea. Black is sacrificing a pawn in order to eliminate the light-squared bishop.} 18. Bxb3 cxb3 19. Qxb3 Rc8 $1 20. Ra2 (20. Ne3 f5 $17) 20... f5 $17 {Black is dominating.}) 13... a5 $3 {A very strong positional idea. Black wants to keep gaining space on the queenside by playing ...a5-a4. Later on, he can proceed with ...Na5 followed by ...c7-c5.} 14. d5 {Black is more than ready to play a closed position.} ({After} 14. a4 bxa4 {White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) ({The position arising after} 14. Qe2 a4 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. c4 c6 {is obviously favourable for Black. He can now consider ...Nh5-f4.}) ({In response to} 14. Nf1 {Black should answer with the standard} a4 ({When the bishop is on a2, the sequence} 14... exd4 $6 15. cxd4 Rxe4 16. Rxe4 Nxe4 17. Qc2 Qe8 {does not work quite well in view of} 18. Bxh6 Bxh6 19. Re1 $16 {White has an obvious advantage in this position. Had the bishop been on b3, Black would have had the resource of ...Na5 here.}) 15. Ng3 Na5 $15 {Black is doing fine. His plan is to carry out the advance ...c7-c5.}) ({It goes without saying that with a bishop on g7, the move} 14. dxe5 {is best answered with} Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Qc2 Qe7 $36 {with a comfortable position for Black.} (16... a4 {is good as well.})) 14... Ne7 $132 15. Nf1 c6 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Ng3 Qc7 {As usual, Black is doing fine in this structure. The idea is to carry out the advance ...d6-d5.}) 12... Nh5 $5 {This is one of the three decent moves in this position - the other two are 12...Qc8, and ...Na5. Actually, these are the first three moves to consider in positions in which White tries to keep the central tension.} ({Let's also take a look at} 12... Qc8 $5 {Besides the usual ...Na5, Black also keeps the option of playing ... Nd8. As always, the move} 13. Nf1 {is well met by} Na5 {Whenever the white knight leaves d2, we start fighting for the c4-square!} 14. b3 {With a pawn on a2, this moves makes much more sense. Now, Black does not have the option of .. .c7-c5-c4 followed by ...Nb3.} ({If White neglects Black's queenside play by opting for} 14. Ng3 {a typical response would be} c5 15. d5 Nc4 16. b3 Nb6 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb3b4,Ga6a5,Gc8c7,Ga8a6,Ge8a8] The knight is much better placed here.} 17. Be3 Qc7 18. Qd2 {Both players managed to put their pieces in optimal positions. Now, the best solution is} c4 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Ra6 $15 {[%cal Ge8a8] It's clear that after ...Rfa8, Black is the one who will take control of the a-file.}) 14... c5 15. d5 Nh5 16. Be3 Qc7 $132 17. Qd2 Nb7 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black is planning to follow with ...c5-c4 and answer b3-b4 with .. .a6-a5.} ({The immediate} 17... Nf4 $132 {is possible as well.}) 18. Ng3 {The best continuation. White wants to open the f-file for his rook.} ({A very instructive line would be} 18. N1h2 c4 $15 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Ra6 {[%cal Ge8a8] We already know this typical idea. By using his space advantage on the queenside, Black will get control of the a-file.} 21. Rab1 (21. g4 Nf4) 21... axb4 22. axb4 Rea8 23. Rec1 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1,Rc2,Rd2][%cal Ga6a2]} Nd8 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gd8f7] A key move in Black's concept. After ...f7-f6 followed by ...Nf7, he will be able to combine the queenside play with kingside activity.} 24. Qd1 ({A move like} 24. Qe1 {would allow} f5 $132) 24... f6 25. Ng4 ({Nothing changes} 25. Ra1 Qc8) 25... Nf7 $17 {[%cal Gf6f5] Black is better. Very soon he will carry out the advance ...f6-f5.}) 18... Nf4 $132 {In my opinion, this is the most precise reaction to Ng3.} ({In case of} 18... Nxg3 19. fxg3 c4 20. b4 a5 21. a3 Ra6 {[%cal Gg3g4,Ge1f1,Gf7f6,Gb7d8,Gd8f7] The semi-open f-file would make a difference. After} 22. Kh2 Rea8 {White can deal with Black's queenside initiative by means of the elegant} 23. a4 axb4 24. cxb4 bxa4 25. Qc3 {followed by Nd2. Black will not be able to keep his queenside pawns for too long.})) (12... Na5 $1 {This is another very strong move which is directed against Nf1.} 13. Nf1 ({White can also try} 13. b4 {but then Black obtains counterplay by means of} Nc6 14. a3 a5 15. d5 Ne7 16. Rb1 axb4 17. cxb4 c6 18. dxc6 Bxc6 $132 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd6d5] 0-1 ISPANIKI SMYSLOV-SYDOMEFSI THEORIAS/St Petersburg 0/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 13... c5 14. d5 Nc4 15. b3 Nb6 $132 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black is in a very good shape. He is ready to proceed with ...c5-c4.}) 13. Nf1 ({As always, the move} 13. d5 $6 {is more than welcome -} Ne7 14. Nf1 c6 {''} ({Starting with} 14... h6 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6] is possible as well. In this way, we rule out the idea of Bg5.}) 15. dxc6 Bxc6 $36 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Ne3 Nf6 $17 {We have seen this structure on multiple occasions. Black enjoys a considerable advantage.}) 13... Na5 (13... h6 $132) 14. b3 {The most principled answer. White doesn't like to allow ...Nc4.} ({Another possibility is} 14. Bg5 Qc8 {This is the most flexible continuation.} ({In my opinion,} 14... f6 15. Bc1 c5 16. d5 Nc4 {is possible as well.}) 15. b3 c5 {This typical Ruy Lopez advance is always good.} ({A dynamic possibility is} 15... h6 16. Bh4 exd4 17. cxd4 c5 {With good counterplay.}) 16. d5 Qc7 $1 17. Qd2 Nb7 {This type of closed position is very typical for Smyslov Variation and Ruy Lopez in general. By taking a look at the examples below, you will see how to handle such structures.} ({Another possibility would be} 17... c4) 18. Rac1 {This move allows ...c5-c4.} ({On the other hand,} 18. c4 {is well met by} Na5 19. Bd3 f6 {Black is forcing the bishop to occupy the unfavorable e3-square.} 20. Be3 ({Obviously,} 20. Bh6 $6 {is inferior since it allows the exchange of the dark-squared bishops which is favourable for Black -} Bxh6 21. Qxh6 Nf4 22. Re3 bxc4 23. Bxc4 Nxc4 24. bxc4 Rab8 25. h4 Rb2 $17 {Black has a huge advantage.}) 20... f5 $132 {It's now clear why Black needs the white bishop on e3. Now, exf5 will be answered by ...e5-e4.1-0 Karjakin, S-Sasikiran, K/Tromsoe 2013/CBM 156/}) ({As usual, the move} 18. Ng3 {is a valid option. Let's take a look at a typical example featuring the structure arising after} Nxg3 ({Of course,} 18... Nf4 {is playable as well.}) 19. fxg3 c4 20. b4 ({After} 20. g4 cxb3 21. axb3 Rec8 $15 {The pressure on c3 is rather annoying.}) 20... a5 21. a3 Ra6 {[%cal Ge8a8] We have already seen this thematic way of fighting for the a-file.} 22. Bh6 ({Black's idea is very well illustrated in the following line -} 22. g4 Rea8 23. Rac1 axb4 24. axb4 f6 25. Be3 Nd8 {[%cal Gd8f7] Finally, the knight is heading for the perfect f7-square.} 26. Rf1 Nf7 $17 {[%cal Ga6a2] Black is ready to proceed with ...Ra2. His advantage is out of question.}) 22... Rea8 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Rab1 axb4 25. axb4 Nd8 26. g4 f6 $15 {[%cal Gd8f7] with ...Nf7 to follow. Black is already better.}) ({The advance} 18. a4 $6 {is very well met by} bxa4 19. bxa4 c4 20. Ne3 h6 21. Bh4 Na5 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black is ready to follow with ...Rb8. He has a very good queenside play in this position.}) ({Of course,} 18. g4 $2 {will be answered with} Nf4 {This is even not a sacrifice since the c3-pawn is hanging. White cannot live with the f4-knight and will eliminate it. In this case, however, Black's dark-squared bishop becomes a monster. Let me show one typical idea that you should have in mind.} 19. Bxf4 exf4 20. Rac1 Be5 $3 {Remember this beautiful positional move.} 21. Nxe5 {White has nothing better.} ({After} 21. c4 {Black is going to support the bishop by means of} f6 $17) 21... dxe5 {[%cal Gb7d6] This is the idea. The d6-square is now available for the knight.} 22. c4 ({The attempt to create complications by playing} 22. d6 Nxd6 23. Red1 {is well met by} Re6 $19 {when Black enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 22... Nd6 $19 {Black is strategically winning. Actually, he can consider playing on both wings.}) ({Another typical mistake would be} 18. Bd3 $2 {when a thematic reaction is} c4 $1 19. bxc4 Nc5 {Black is ready sacrifice a pawn in order to free the c5-square for the knight.} 20. cxb5 axb5 $17 {Black's better structure and active pieces provide him with a huge advantage. White should already reckon with the advance ...f7-f5. For instance, after} 21. Ne3 h6 22. Bh4 f5 {White is already on the verge of losing.}) ({The move} 18. Rec1 {does not change Black's strategy -} c4 19. b4 Nf4 {Once again, we see this typical move. Black will obviously follow with ...a6-a5. At some point, however, it's possible to play ...Nd3, thus sacrifice a pawn in order to eliminate the light-squared bishop. In such a scenario, it will be easier to carry out the advance ... f7-f5.} ({The usual} 19... a5 {is possible as well.})) 18... c4 $1 {Always play this move when you get the opportunity.} 19. b4 {This is White's most common reaction.} ({After} 19. bxc4 Qxc4 20. Ne3 Qc8 $1 $15 {Black is better in view of his better structure. Also, White should always reckon with ...Bxh3 ideas.}) {The following couple of moves are quite standard.} 19... a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 Ra2 22. Ra1 Rea8 $15 23. Rxa2 Rxa2 24. Rc1 Nd8 {planning to proceed with ...f7-f6 followed by ...Nf7. As always, Black will combine his play along the a-file with a kingside activity.} 25. Be3 (25. Qd1 Nf4 $17) 25... Qc8 26. Qd1 Qa8 $17 {Black has an obvious advantage.}) 14... c5 15. d5 Qc7 16. Be3 Nb7 {[%cal Gc5c4] Once again, Black follows the procedure we are familiar with. The next move is ...c5-c4 with the idea to answer b3-b4 with ... a6-a5.} 17. Qd2 c4 {[%cal Gc4b3,Ga2b3,Gb7c5,Ga6a5]} 18. b4 (18. Kh1 cxb3 19. axb3 Nc5 20. b4 Na4 21. Bxa4 bxa4) 18... a5 19. a3 Ra6 $132 {As we know, Black can easily takeover in this structure. Here is a sample line -} 20. Rab1 axb4 21. axb4 Rea8 22. N1h2 Ra2 23. Qc1 Qc8 $17 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gb7d8,Gd8f7,Gf5f4,Gg6g5,Gh5f6,Gh7h5,Gg5g4] The queen stands perfectly on this position. White should always reckon with the advance ...f7-f5.} *

