{[%evp 0,38,61,32,56,36,19,7,28,-6,39,22,6,-31,18,40,38,31,6,5,5,31,23,10,19,3,7,-2,21,14,22,27,29,29,31,27,39,32,21,23,20]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Bd7 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. d5 $6 {This is a bad move but everyone thinks it's good!! As you will see, Black is in a very decent shape in all the positions with a closed centre.} Nce7 9. Bxd7+ {This is the most precise continuation since Black was already threatening ...b7-b5.} ({Let's take a look at some lines. For instance,} 9. c4 {is very well met by} b5 $1 {Deflecting the c4-pawn is very important in this structure because later on Black will easily destroy White's centre with ...c7-c6.} 10. Bc2 {The most natural continuation.} ({A typical mistake would be} 10. cxb5 $2 axb5 11. Bc2 h6 $15 {Before proceeding with ...f7-f5, Black takes the g5-square under control.} ({With his light-squared bishop on the board, Black can play the immediate} 11... f5 $15 {since} 12. Ng5 {will be simply met by} Nf6 {with a better position. White's centre can easily fall apart.}) 12. Nc3 ({Another game saw} 12. Bd2 f5 13. exf5 gxf5 14. Bc3 Nf6 15. Bb3 Ng6 $17 {1-0 (33) Haznedaroglu, K-Delithanasis, D/Athens 2007/[,ÃéÜííçò] when Black has a huge advantage in view of his powerful centre and the vulnerable d5-pawn.}) 12... f5 13. exf5 gxf5 {Black is better. He will proceed with ...Nf6 followed by ...0-0.}) ({Another direction is} 10. Bb3 {Therefore, a better idea with be to complete the development by means of} Nf6 {I think that this approach is a bit too slow. Nevertheless, it's quite playable.} ({The immediate} 10... bxc4 11. Bxc4 f5 {would have been even better.}) 11. Re1 O-O 12. a4 bxc4 13. Bxc4 c6 {This way of attacking the centre is quite typical for the Smyslov Variation. Without the c4-pawn, White cannot keep his space advantage. A possible line would be} 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15. Nc3 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 d5 17. Bg5 dxe4 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. Bxe7 Rd7 {with an advantage for Black.}) 10... f5 {The most straightforward continuation.} ({Another very good option is to first eliminate the c4-pawn.} 10... bxc4 11. Nbd2 {White should try to regain the c4-pawn.} ({Nothing changes} 11. Na3 f5 12. Nxc4 Nf6 13. exf5 gxf5 {with an excellent position for Black.}) ({Leaving the c4-pawn alive by means of} 11. Nc3 {does not help either as shown by the following lines.} h6 12. Nd2 f5 13. exf5 {We are more than happy to see this move. White gives up the centre in order to prevent Black from castling.} ({A typical position would arise after} 13. Nxc4 Nf6 14. f3 O-O 15. Be3 f4 16. Bf2 g5 $40 {Black has an excellent version of the King's Indian Defence. The advance ...g5-g4 is very annoying. Remember that the most precise reaction to} 17. Ba4 {is} Bc8 $3 $36 {keeping the light-squared bishop which is an important attacking piece.} ({That being said,} 17... Bxa4 18. Qxa4 h5 $36 ({or} 18... g4 $36 {is also very good.}))) 13... gxf5 14. Qh5+ Kf8 {Black is not afraid of playing ...Kf8. Soon, the queen will be chased back with ...Nf6.} 15. Nxc4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Qe8 $15 {Black is better. He will start gradually developing a kingside attack.} ({Another thematic line would be} 16... Rg8 $15 17. Kh1 Qe8 18. f4 e4 19. Ne3 Qh5 20. Qc4 Ng4 21. Nxg4 Qxg4 $17 {with a strong attack.})) 11... f5 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Nxc4 {This position was reached in the game Deepan Chakkravarthy, J - Naiditsch, A, 2018. Now, the most promising continuation would have been} O-O 14. f3 h6 {With our light-squared bishop on the board, we are not afraid of Ne6.} 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 Qc8 17. exf5 gxf5 18. Bb3 Rb8 $15 {Black is better in view of his strong pawn centre and the vulnerable e6-pawn.}) ({A mistake would be} 10... Nf6 $2 {in view of} 11. c5 O-O 12. c6 Bc8 13. b4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 11. Ng5 (11. c5 Nf6 12. c6 Bc8 $132) 11... Nf6 12. a4 bxc4 13. f3 c6 $1 {Once again, we come across this thematic idea.} 14. dxc6 Qb6+ {Another precise move. Black wants to take on c6 with the queen since the bishop should guard the e6-square.} (14... Bxc6 15. Ne6) 15. Kh1 Qxc6 $17 {White does not have compensation for the pawn. 0-1 (43) Pavlidis,A-McShane,L/ Katowice 2017/CBM 182 Extra'}) ({Pointless is} 9. Nbd2 {when Black gets the opportunity to play} b5 $3 10. Bc2 Nf6 $1 {By putting the knight in front of the pawn, Black indicates his intention to quickly strike with ...c7-c6.} ({It goes without saying that} 10... f5 11. a4 Nf6 {is possible as well. The move ...c7-c6 can be played even later.}) 11. Re1 O-O 12. Nf1 h6 $5 ({or} 12... c6 13. dxc6 Bxc6 $36) 13. Ng3 c6 14. dxc6 Bxc6 $36 {We have seen this structure on multiple occasions. As usual, Blaclk's main idea is to carry out the advance ...d6-d5.}) 9... Qxd7 10. c4 {Sooner or later White should play this move.} ({Let's take a look at another interesting setup -} 10. Be3 h6 11. Nfd2 f5 12. f3 Nf6 13. c4 O-O 14. Nc3 {[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8,Gg6g5,Ge7g6] In this case, besides the typical ...g6-g5 followed by ...Ng6 and doubling the rooks along the f-file, Black can even play} c5 {planning to seize space on the queenside with ...b7-b5-b4.} 15. Rb1 b5 16. b3 b4 $1 17. Ne2 a5 $17 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gf5f4,Gg6g5,Ge7g6] Black will start expanding on both wings.}) 10... h6 ({Of course, not} 10... f5 $2 {when after} 11. Ng5 $16 {[%cal Gg5e6] White gets a huge advantage.}) 11. Nc3 ({We know that} 11. Nfd2 {is not preventing ... f7-f5. After} f5 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Qh5+ Kf8 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1,Rd2,Ge5,Gf5,Rh5][%cal Gg8f6,Gf8g8,Gg8h7,Ge7g6,Gh8g8] Black is doing more than fine. After ... Nf6 and ...Ng6, he will bring the king to h7. The rooks will occupy f8 and g8-squares. Additionally, Black enjoys a powerful and mobile centre.}) 11... f5 12. exf5 {This is almost always a bad idea.} ({More to the point would be} 12. Ne1 Nf6 13. f3 O-O 14. Nd3 g5 $36 {This is one of the most thematic moves in the pawn structure. Usually, Black wants to proceed with ...Ng6 followed by doubling the rooks along the f-file. Indeed, in KID type of positions, the exchange of the light-squared bishops is favourable for White. In this line, however, things are far from simple. Since one pair of minor pieces is exchanged, White's space advantage is less significant. Also, unlike King's Indian Defence, Black played ...f7-f5 without wasting any time. Additionally, due to the better piece coordination in his camp, Black can attack the centre with ...c7-c6. Very often, it's important that the c8-square is available for the rook.} ({The immediate} 14... c6 $5 {is a very good possibility as well.} 15. Bd2 {White should try to keep the central structure.} ({A mistake would be} 15. dxc6 $6 {when after} Qxc6 $15 {Black is already better. White should deal with the pressure on e4 and c4. Also, at any moment, Black can consider playing ...b7-b5.} ({Another very good possibility is} 15... Nxc6 16. b3 Nd4 17. Be3 b5 $15)) 15... cxd5 16. cxd5 Rac8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8c4,Gb5b4,Gg6g5,Ge7g6] Black's better coordination allows him to play on both wings.}) ({Note that without light-squared bishops, the straightforward} 14... f4 15. Bd2 g5 16. b4 h5 17. c5 Ng6 18. Rc1 g4 {does not work so well. We should play in this way only when we have plenty of time to bring all our pieces to the kingside. For instance, after} 19. a4 {a huge mistake would be} g3 $2 {Instead, Black should try to double the rooks on the g-file.} 20. h3 {The kingside is completely blocked. Had our light-squared bishops been on the board, we could have sacrificed on h3.}) ({Another very typical way of playing is} 14... Rf7 {planning to double the rooks along the f-file.} 15. Bd2 ({Remember that in this line, the advance} 15. c5 {is often met by} c6 16. dxc6 Nxc6 17. Be3 d5 $15 {Black was already better in the game ½-½ (56) Kurnosov, I-Ivanchuk,V/ Astana 2012/CBM 149 Extra}) 15... Raf8 16. Qe2 g5 17. Rac1 Ng6 18. exf5 Qxf5 {This structure is almost always acceptable for Black. The weak e4-square is compensated by Black's active play along the f-file. Also, without the e4-pawn, Black can effectively attack the centre with ...c7-c6. Also, the g6-knight can often go to d4. For instance, a very good reaction to} 19. g3 {is} Ne7 20. Nf2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf5d4] planning to follow with ...Nf5-d4.} ({Another possibility would be} 20... Qg6 $1 21. Nfe4 Nf5 $17) ({Even} 20... Qh7 $3 {works fantastically in this structure.} 21. Nfe4 ({After} 21. Nce4 {a very good idea is} Nd7 $3 {Of course, we refrain from an exchange since both white knights are fighting for the e4-square.} 22. Nd3 Nf5 23. Bc3 Qg6 24. b4 h5 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. White should always reckon with ...g5-g5 or ... h5-h4.} (24... b5 $17) (24... c6 $17)) ({Dubious is} 21. g4 {which is very well met by} e4 $3 (21... Ng6 $15) 22. Nfxe4 Nd7 $3 $36 {planning to put the knight on e5. The other knight can occupy the h4-square. All black pieces are working.}) 21... Nf5 $15 {Black is better. The next move is going to be ...Nd4. Also, the pressure along the f-file is very annoying.}) 21. Nfe4 Nf5 22. Be3 Nd4 23. Nxf6+ Rxf6 24. Bxd4 exd4 25. Ne4 R6f7 {[%cal Gc7c6] 1/2-1/2 (62) Markidis,K-Kuljasevic,D/40th International Open \ 2018/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 15. Qb3 {This move does not feel right because the queen is going far away from the kingside.} ({If White starts concentrating his forces on the kingside by playing} 15. Be3 Rf7 16. Qe2 Raf8 17. Rae1 {we have enough time to build our typical kingside activity -} f4 18. Bf2 h5 19. c5 g4 $17 {[%cal Gg7h6,Gg8h7,Gf8g8,Gf7g7,Gg4f3,Ge7g6,Gh6g5,Gg5h4] Later on, Black will start bringing all his pieces to the kingside. At the same time, White's queenside play hasn't even started.}) ({Very often, White starts fighting for the e4-square by means of} 15. exf5 Qxf5 16. Nf2 {In this case, besides everything else, Black can strike with} b5 {when after} 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Nexd5 {White's centre simply gets destroyed.}) {This position was reached in the game Fedossev, V - Ali Marandi, C, 2020. Now, Black could have started active play on the kingside with} 15... fxe4 $5 16. fxe4 Ng6 $15 17. Bd2 $6 Nh5 {when he is ready to proceed with ...Nhf4. In case of} 18. g3 {Black has a devastating attack -} Nxg3 19. hxg3 Qh3 20. Ne2 Nh4 21. gxh4 Qg4+ 22. Kh1 Qxe4+ 23. Kg1 Qg4+ 24. Kh1 Qxe2 $19 {with a winning position.}) ({In my opinion, the best reaction to} 12. Qb3 {is} b6 13. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] planning to open the queenside with a4-a5.} ({In case of} 13. Qc2 Nf6 14. b4 {Black can strike with} b5 $15 {which is a typical way of destroying White's centre. For instace, after} 15. c5 $2 Nxe4 16. c6 Qc8 $19 {Black is already winning.}) 13... a5 {An important move, blocking the queenside.} 14. Qb5 {Anticipating Black's kingside attack, White wants to exchange the queens.} ({As always} 14. exf5 {would just provide Black with a powerful centre.} gxf5 15. Bd2 Nf6 16. Qb5 Qxb5 $1 17. axb5 (17. Nxb5 Kd7 18. Rfe1 Ng6 $17) 17... O-O $17 {Black's advantage is obvious.}) 14... Qxb5 (14... Nf6 15. Nd2 O-O (15... Qxb5 $5 16. axb5 (16. Nxb5 Kd7 17. f3 h5 $17)) 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 17. Nb5 Rac8 18. Na7 Rb8 19. Nb5 Rb7 20. f3 Bf6 21. Nb1 Bg5 $15 {1-0 Kotronias,V-Burtasova,A/Athens 2007/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 15. axb5 Nf6 16. Nd2 Kd7 $36 17. Re1 h5 {A typical move. Black starts expanding on the kingside. Also, the dark-squared bishop can be activated via h6.}) ({Way too passive is} 12. Nd2 {Black will simply follow with} Nf6 13. f3 O-O 14. b3 c6 {Since White is considerably underdeveloped, Black can employ this thematic move.} 15. Bb2 cxd5 16. cxd5 b5 {An important idea. Black not only gains space on the queenside but also prevents Nc4. The d2-knight is really problematic now.} 17. Rc1 h5 $17 {[%cal Gg7h6] with ...Bh6 to follow. Black has a huge advantage.}) ({Of course, after} 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Nd2 O-O 14. f3 c6 {Black has more than sufficient counterplay.}) 12... gxf5 13. Nh4 {The only way to justify the move 12.exf5. White wants to proceed with Qh5 followed by f2-f4.} ({After} 13. Ne1 {Besides the usual 13...Nf6, Black can even play} f4 $15 {restricting the c1-bishop and ruling out any f2-f4 ideas. Due to White's inferior development and poor coordination, the weakness of the e4-square is not significant. The following example shows how the game might develop.} 14. Qh5+ Kf8 15. Ne4 Nf6 16. Nxf6 Bxf6 $17 17. Qe2 Qf5 18. f3 Rg8 19. Nd3 Qh5 20. Nf2 Nf5 21. Ne4 Kf7 $19 {1-0 Zhao,J-Sargissian,G/Riadh 2017/CBM 182 Extra/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 13... Bf6 $3 {This move that I found is even better than the traditional ...Nf6.} 14. Qh5+ {The only principled continuation.} ({Of course, after} 14. Nf3 Ng6 {Black is doing more than fine.}) ({Another very important idea is} 14. f4 e4 15. Be3 {when Black has the following resource:} Bxh4 16. Qh5+ Ng6 17. Qxg6+ Qf7 18. Qxf7+ Kxf7 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gh4f6] 0-1 (46) Al Modiahki, M-Short,N/Gibraltar 2006/CBM 110 Extra/[,ÃéÜííçò] with an advantage in the endgame.}) ({The same idea works also against} 14. Re1 {-} Bxh4 15. Qh5+ Ng6 16. Qxg6+ Qf7 17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. Bd2 Ne7 19. g3 Bf6 {Black is better. He can undermine White's centre either with ...c7-c6 or with ...b7-b5.}) 14... Kf8 15. Ng6+ ({The endgame arising after} 15. Bd2 $2 Qe8 $3 $19 16. Qxe8+ Kxe8 $1 {is lost for White. The point is that} 17. Nf3 {will be met by} b5 $3 $19 {when White's position is collapsing.} 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nxb5 Nxd5 20. Rfd1 Nge7 21. a4 Kd7 $19) 15... Nxg6 16. Qxg6 h5 17. Bd2 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e7,Ge7g7] Planning to transfer the rook to g7.} ({Going for an endgame with} 17... Qh7 18. Qxh7 Rxh7 $15 {is possible as well.}) 18. Rae1 Re7 19. Qg3 Rg7 $36 {Black has a strong initiative.} *

