1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 d6 7. d4 Bd7 8. d5 Nce7 9. Bxd7+ (9. Re1 b5 $1 10. Bc2 f5 11. exf5 gxf5 12. Ng5 Nf6 13. Ne6 Bxe6 14. dxe6 O-O 15. Nd2 Qc8 $17) 9... Qxd7 10. c4 h6 11. Nc3 f5 12. exf5 $6 {This move is dubious unless White has something concrete in mind.} gxf5 13. Nh4 Nf6 {In my opinion, this is not the best move.} (13... Bf6 $3 $15 {This move that I found is even better than the traditional ...Nf6.'} 14. Qh5+ {The only principled continuation.} ({Of course, after} 14. Nf3 Ng6 {Black is doing more than fine.}) ({Another very important idea is} 14. f4 e4 15. Be3 {when Black has the following resource:} Bxh4 16. Qh5+ Ng6 17. Qxg6+ Qf7 18. Qxf7+ Kxf7 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gh4f6] 0-1 (46) Al Modiahki, M-Short,N/Gibraltar 2006/CBM 110 Extra/[,ÃéÜííçò] with an advantage in the endgame.}) ({The same idea works also against} 14. Re1 {-} Bxh4 15. Qh5+ Ng6 16. Qxg6+ Qf7 17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. Bd2 Ne7 19. g3 Bf6 {Black is better. He can undermine White's centre either with ...c7-c6 or with ...b7-b5.}) 14... Kf8 15. Ng6+ ({The endgame arising after} 15. Bd2 $2 Qe8 $3 $19 16. Qxe8+ Kxe8 $1 {is lost for White. The point is that} 17. Nf3 {will be met by} b5 $3 $19 {when White's position is collapsing.} 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nxb5 Nxd5 20. Rfd1 Nge7 21. a4 Kd7 $19) 15... Nxg6 16. Qxg6 h5 17. Bd2 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e7,Ge7g7] Planning to transfer the rook to g7.} ({Going for an endgame with} 17... Qh7 18. Qxh7 Rxh7 $15 {is possible as well.}) 18. Rae1 Re7 19. Qg3 Rg7 $36 {SPANISH SMYSLOV-MAIN LINE   NEW !! MODERN CHESS rapid 2017 Black has a strong initiative.}) 14. f4 e4 15. Be3 O-O 16. Ne2 c5 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Bd4 c5 19. Bc3 d5 20. cxd5 Nexd5 21. Bxf6 Rxf6 22. Ng3 Rf7 23. Qe2 Qe6 24. Kh1 Kh7 25. Rae1 Raf8 26. Nh5 Bd4 27. g4 Ne3 28. g5 Rb7 29. g6+ Kg8 30. g7 Rff7 31. Rg1 Rxb2 32. Rb1 Rfb7 33. Rxb2 Rxb2 34. Rg6 Rxe2 0-1

