{This is a very nice game by Black who had the chance to follow the strategy with double capture. Also, I suggest that you pay a lot of attention to the lines with closed centre that I give in the analysis. You will face them very often in your practice.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Nf6 {Obviously, our move order starts with ...Bd7.} 6. Re1 Bd7 7. c3 g6 8. d4 b5 9. Bb3 Bg7 10. Bg5 $6 {This move is almost never a good idea. We have seen that on many occasions.} O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 {This move is always good in such positions. We will play it sooner or later.} ({Another very nice idea would have been} 11... h6 12. Bh4 exd4 13. cxd4 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 {when the White's centre is vulnerable. In the theoretical files, you will find many examples featuring similar positions.}) 12. h3 $6 {This slow move allows Black to accomplish all the typical ideas.} ({Obviously, in case of} 12. dxe5 {Black is going to play} Nxe5 $1 13. Nxe5 dxe5 {with good chances to outplay the opponent. As we know, the main plan in this structure is based on winning space on the queenside.}) 12... h6 13. Bh4 Na5 {This is probably the most precise move. By using the position of the b3-bishop, Black is winning an important tempo. The next move is going to be ...c7-c5.} 14. Bc2 c5 15. Nb3 $2 {This move is a clear mistake. The knight has nothing to do here.} ({More natural would have been} 15. d5 {when once again we can see all the familiar strategic concepts.} c4 $1 {Never forget this important move. The idea is to reroute the knight to c5. The thematic} 16. b4 {will be answered with} cxb3 17. axb3 Qc7 {Given the fact that the dark-squared bishop is misplaced on h4, White cannot comfortably protect the c3-pawn.} 18. Re3 Nh5 {Black has an excellent counterplay. At any moment, White should reckon with ideas such as .. .f7-f5 and ...Nf4.} ({Another very good idea is} 18... Nb7 19. b4 Nh5 $36 20. Bb3 a5 $1 21. Nf1 Rec8 $17 {Actually, Black has a huge advantage in this position. Since White does not have queenside play, Black can start playing on the other wing. The first job is to transfer the knight to f7. For instance, after} 22. Ra3 Nd8 23. Kh2 f6 $3 24. Bg3 Nf7 $17 {Black's advantage is out of question. The advance ...f6-f5 is coming.})) ({An interesting tactical idea suggested by the computer is} 15. dxe5 $5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 $3 ({Clearly worse is} 16. b4 $6 cxb4 17. cxb4 Nc6 {when White's position is quite overextended. A possible follow-up would be} 18. a3 g5 $1 19. Bg3 Nh5 20. Bh2 Nf4 $15 {With an advantage for Black.} (20... g4 21. hxg4 Bxg4 $15 {is possible as well.}) {A possible way in which Black can increase the advantage is} 21. Nb3 g4 $17 22. hxg4 Bxg4 23. Nc5 Nd4 {with complete domination.}) {The following line is pretty much forced -} 16... Rxe5 17. Nf3 (17. f4 $2 Rh5) 17... Re8 18. e5 Bc6 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. exf6 Bh8 21. Ne5 g5 22. Nxc6 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Nxc6 24. Bg3 Bxf6 25. Be4 Ne7 26. Kf1 b4 $11 {The position is equal.}) ({Another mistake is} 15. Nf1 $2 exd4 $1 16. cxd4 cxd4 {Since our tempis are more than fine, we should go for double capture!} 17. Nxd4 Qb6 $17 {Black has a huge advantage in view of the vulnerable white pieces. The bishop is rather misplaced on h4.}) 15... cxd4 16. Nxa5 Qxa5 17. cxd4 exd4 $1 18. Nxd4 Qb6 19. Nf3 Be6 $3 {A fantastic move that shows Sokolov's tremendous understanding. By freeing the d7-square for the knight, he provokes} 20. Nd4 (20. Bb3 Bxb3 21. Qxb3 Nxe4 $19) (20. a3 Nd7 $17) (20. Qd2 Nd7 $17 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) 20... Bc8 $3 {Another very deep move! As we know, in this structure, the bishop actually belongs on b7.} 21. Qd2 Bb7 22. Bxf6 (22. f3 Nxe4) 22... Bxf6 23. Rad1 d5 $1 24. Bb3 $1 Rxe4 $1 25. Rxe4 dxe4 $19 {Black is winning. After showing very good calculations, Sokolov converted the advantage into a full point.} 26. Nf5 (26. Qxh6 Bxd4 27. Rxd4 (27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Qh7+ Kf6 29. Qh4+ Kg7 30. Qe7+ Kg8 31. Rxd4 Qxd4 32. Qxb7 Rf8 $19) 27... Qxd4 28. Qxg6+ Qg7 29. Bxf7+ Kf8 $19 (29... Kh8 $4 30. Qh5+ Qh7 31. Qe5+ Qg7 32. Qh5+ Qh7 33. Qe5+ $11)) 26... Rd8 $1 27. Nxh6+ Kg7 28. Qc1 Rxd1+ 29. Bxd1 e3 $1 30. Ng4 exf2+ 31. Kf1 Bd4 32. Qh6+ Kg8 33. Qf4 Qc6 34. Bf3 Qc4+ 35. Be2 Bxg2+ 36. Kxg2 Qxe2 37. Nh6+ Kh7 0-1

