{[%evp 0,106,20,18,18,18,18,13,31,4,23,0,6,13,20,5,12,0,2,5,3,-7,-2,12,19,9,26,18,30,23,35,12,34,46,49,24,24,22,24,24,12,19,22,20,33,0,0,1,0,-38,7,-67,-67,-67,-25,-39,-28,-67,-14,-33,0,-9,0,-12,32,4,11,-6,-24,-33,-13,-31,-18,-52,-40,-54,-58,-59,-45,-79,-58,-83,-86,-94,-93,-139,-148,-181,-167,-250,-197,-326,-173,-285,-274,-272,-272,-272,-208,-399,-237,-315,-307,-328,-106,-505,-491,-479,-480] Pay a lot of attention to this instructive game featuring positions with a closed centre.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. c3 Bd7 6. O-O Nf6 ({Our move order would have been} 6... g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. Bg5 Nf6) 7. Re1 g6 8. h3 Bg7 9. d4 b5 10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Bc2 {White goes for the optimal strategy against our variation - keeping the tension in the centre. As you know, in this position, we have three candidate moves - ...Nh5, ...Na5, and ...Qc8. In the game, Black played} Na5 {which is not the optimal solution when the white knight is still on d2.} ({I would have chosen} 12... Qc8 $1 {and only after} 13. Nf1 Na5 {is a decent idea.} ({By the way, Black can also play} 13... Nh5) ({Remember that the move} 13... Nd8 {is identical to ...Na5. At the end of the day, the knight will try to reack the c5-square via different route. Let's take a look at a sample line -} 14. Ng3 c5 15. d5 c4 16. Bd2 Nb7 17. b4 {When you see this move, you should take action. Otherwise, White will play a2-a4.} cxb3 {This move works perfectly fine.} ({We know that the strategy based on} 17... a5 18. a3 Ra6 {works fine as well.}) 18. axb3 Nc5 {[%cal Ga6a5] Black is ready to proceed with ...a6-a5. It's very important that the move b3-b4 can be answered with ...Na4.} 19. Qe2 a5 {Just in time!} ({After Qe2, White is already threatening b3-b4. For instance, after} 19... Qc7 20. b4 Na4 21. Bxa4 bxa4 22. c4 Rec8 23. Rec1 {White is much better since it's extremely difficult to deal with the idea of c4-c5.}) 20. b4 axb4 21. cxb4 Na4 22. Bd3 Qb7 {Black is doing fine.}) 14. Ng3 c5 15. d5 c4 {with excellent counterplay.} (15... Nc4 {is possible as well.})) ({Another very good option is} 12... Nh5 $1) 13. Nf1 {This move justifies Black's idea.} ({Better would have been} 13. b4) 13... h6 {I see no need to play this move. I play it only in response to Bg5.} ({Obviously, better would have been} 13... c5 14. d5 ({We know that the structure arising after} 14. dxc5 dxc5 {is favourable for Black. One of the ideas is to proceed with ...c5-c4 followed by ...Nb7-c5. White can try to fight for the d5-square with} 15. Bg5 {This plan, however, is not dangerous at all. Black can continue} h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne3 Be6 {when a typical positional mistake would be} 18. Nd5 $2 Bxd5 19. exd5 Nc4 20. b3 Nd6 {After putting the knight on d6, Black is strategically winning. He is ready to put his central pawns in motion.}) 14... Nc4 {[%cal Gc4b6] with ... Nb6 to follow}) 14. Ng3 c5 15. b3 {Preventing ...Nc4 but allowing the strategy based on double capture.} ({It goes without saying that} 15. d5 {will be met with} Nc4 $1 16. b3 ({In response to} 16. a4 {Black can even play} Na5 $5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ga5b7,Gb7c5] planning to proceed with ...c5-c4 followed by the maneuver ...Nb7-c5. This plan works very well when the white pawn is not on a2.} ({Another very good idea is} 16... Nb6 17. a5 Nc4 18. b4 Rc8 {with an excellent counterplay.})) 16... Nb6 17. a4 c4 18. a5 cxb3 19. Bxb3 Na4 {is also very good for Black.}) 15... Qc7 {This move is good only when our tempis are not good.} ({The double capture strategy would have been better -} 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Rc8 (17... h5 18. Bg5) 18. Bb2 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] with ...h5-h4 to follow. Black has an excellent counterplay.}) 16. d5 c4 17. b4 Nb7 18. a3 $2 {This is a mistake allowing Black to execute our familiar procedure.} ({White should have played} 18. a4) 18... a5 19. Be3 Ra6 20. Qd2 Kh7 21. Qe2 Rea8 22. Rac1 axb4 23. axb4 Ra2 24. Nh2 Nd8 25. Ng4 Nxg4 $1 $17 {Black has a huge advantage.} (25... Bxg4 $1 $17 26. hxg4 Ng8 27. Nf1 Bf6 $17) 26. hxg4 f6 (26... R8a3 27. Bd2 (27. Qd2 Bxg4) 27... Rb2) 27. f3 Nf7 28. Kf2 Bf8 29. Rh1 Kg7 30. Rb1 Be7 31. Qd2 g5 (31... Ng5) 32. Rhc1 Qb7 33. Ne2 Bd8 34. g3 Nh8 35. Kg2 Ng6 36. Kf2 Bc7 37. Qd1 Bb6 38. Qd2 Qa7 39. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 40. Qe3 Qa6 41. Kg1 Rh8 42. Kg2 h5 43. gxh5 Rxh5 44. Qf2 Qa8 45. Kg1 Qh8 46. Qg2 Bh3 47. Qf2 Bd7 48. Qg2 Qa8 49. Kf2 Rh3 50. Kf1 Rh6 51. g4 Qa7 52. Ng3 Nf4 53. Qf2 Qxf2+ *

