{[%evp 0,32,16,28,39,10,28,8,10,-25,-38,-45,-4,-35,41,8,8,-35,-5,-5,3,-53,-14,-20,-24,-29,3,5,23,-4,22,6,22,7,0]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 {Before you finally reach the Chigorin main line, there are a few alternatives that you must know, and quite possibly, you will get in your games frequently. Not much theory knowledge is needed in these alternatives. All you need is some precise moves at first and then a typical Spanish way of playing. Both players have many ideas, and we get a safe position with nice counterchances!} 4. Ba4 (4. Bxc6 $5 {A very important variation for a better understanding of Spanish and chess. Bxc6 is an interesting move but usually white waits with that move. Taking on c6 mostly occurs when Black has already played Nf6 because the knight on f6 is a bit misplaced. Black's idea is usually to go with the knight on g6, e6, or sometimes even on c6 but with the knight on f6, this takes too much time. Therefore white usually waits and takes on c6 when Nf6 is played.} dxc6 5. O-O (5. Nc3 $6 f6 $3 $13 6. O-O (6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Be3 O-O-O $15) 6... c5 7. d3 Ne7 8. Be3 Ng6 $15) (5. d4 $6 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {The first important thing to understand in this position is that if White manages to exchange a few pieces, he will gain an advantage, and if all the pieces are exchanged, the pawn endgame will be winning for White due to the pawn majority on the king's side. In the long run, Black is not able to create a passed pawn on the queen's side because of the doubled pawns ( c7 and c6), which means that White practically has an extra pawn on the king's side. That is why Black should keep more pieces on the board; by doing so, he is objectively better} 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Be3 Ne7 $1 10. O-O-O {A very important move. The knight would have been misplaced on f6 because after White plays f3, there are no good squares for our knight.} Ng6 $1 11. f3 Bb4 $1 {Black's idea in this position will be to jump with the knight to e5 later on and threaten to jump to c4. White can not afford to allow that because a move like Nc4 at some point will be winning. So White will be forced to play a move like b3 sooner or later, and in all the endgames with a pawn on b3 is much easier for Black to play c5-c4 and undouble his pawns.} 12. Nce2 Rhe8 13. a3 Bf8 $15 {Parking the bishop back to f8 is a very important strategy so the bishop will not interfere with the rest of the pieces. Black is already better because he gets to decide when to play the move c5. If c5 is played very early in the game, that is a strategic mistake that is sometimes made even by many GMs. Playing c5 early weakens the d5 square, and we don't want to play c6 after because that creates even more weaknesses.}) (5. h3 $2 c5 $1 $15 {Controlling the center} (5... Ne7 $3 {A great move played by Black. We mentioned earlier that Black's idea is to put the knight on one of the three squares - g6, e6, or c6 and by playing Ne7, black can go to g6 very fast, and he is also controlling the f4 square.} 6. O-O Ng6 $15 {Black is already better. We have a strong, light-squared bishop, and we can play c5 to control the center. If White himself tries to open up the position fast with d4 we take and exchange the queens exd4 Qxd4 Qxd4 Nxd4, play Bd7, and go for the same plan as in the line with 5.d4})) 5... Bd6 $1 {by far the best line in the Spanish exchange. 5... Qd6!? and Qf6 are also considered good fighting moves} 6. d4 (6. c3 $5 Ne7 7. d4 Ng6 $1 $132 (7... exd4 $1 8. cxd4 Ng6 9. h3 O-O 10. Nc3 Be6 $132 11. Qc2 h6 12. Rd1 f5 $3) (7... f6 $1 8. dxe5 fxe5 9. Nbd2 Ng6 $132 (9... Be6 $5 $132))) (6. Nc3 $2 c5 7. d3 Ne7 8. h3 Ng6 $15) 6... exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 Ne7 {[%cal Ye7g6,Ye8g8]} 8. Be3 O-O 9. Nc3 f5 10. exf5 Nxf5 11. Nxf5 Bxf5 $17) 7... f6 {[%cal Yg8e7,Ye7g6,Yc8e6,Ye8g8,Ye8c8]} 8. Be3 (8. Bd2 $5 c5 (8... Ne7 $5 9. Bb4 b6 $1 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qxd6 cxd6 12. Rd1 Kd7 $1 13. Nc3 (13. Nbd2 Kc7 $15 14. Nc4 d5 $15) 13... Kc7 $36) 9. Qc3 Ne7 10. Be3 b6 $132) (8. e5 fxe5 9. Nxe5 Qf6 10. Re1 Ne7 $15 {Nothing to worry about. Black is better, 0-0 is coming}) 8... Ne7 9. Nbd2 Be6 {A very important principle! When white plays Nc4, we must give up one of our bishops. We always give up the light square bishop for the night because the bishop on d6 is very powerful. Therefore, we prepare to take on c4.} 10. Qc3 (10. Nc4 $2 Bxh2+ 11. Nxh2 Qxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxc4 $17) (10. Rad1 Ng6 {Similar to Rfd1} 11. Nc4 Bxc4 $1 12. Qxc4 Qe7 13. Rfe1 (13. Nd4 Qxe4 $3 $17 14. Rfe1 O-O-O) 13... O-O-O 14. Bd4 Rhe8 $132) (10. Rfd1 Ng6 11. Nc4 (11. Qc3 Qe7 12. Nc4 Bxc4 13. Qxc4 O-O-O 14. c3 Rhe8 15. Nd2 h5 $15) 11... Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Qe7 $15 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Ye8c8,Yh8e8] black is better because the e4 pawn is weak and white has misplaced pieces.}) 10... Qd7 $1 11. Nc4 (11. Nd4 O-O-O $5 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. Rfe1 Ng6 $15) 11... Bxc4 $1 {Important reminder- Giving up the light square bishop!} 12. Qxc4 O-O-O 13. Rad1 Ng6 14. Rfe1 (14. Bc5 Nf4 $15 (14... Rhe8 15. Bxd6 cxd6 $36)) 14... Rhe8 $15) 4... Nf6 5. d3 $5 {this is a decent alternative if White wants to avoid the main lines ! ......he can go d3 on move 5 (which allows a g6-Bg7 setup because the bishop is still on f8) or he can play d3 on move 6 (after we play Be7). This somehow limits Black's choices, but still, Black has a fine game! The system is very interesting, not particularly dangerous if Black knows what he is doing. White is threatening to take on e5. The advantages of 5.d3 are that White could take us out of the book theoretically if we don't know what we are doing, and White may have studied this position well, or even simple moves are good for White without much theory. Another advantage is that the move is good and playable. The disadvantages are that when White plays d3, he is a bit late with c3 -b4. It also allows Black to choose where to develop his dark-squared bishop since the c5, e7, and g7 squares are all options.} (5. Nc3 $1 {This move became fashionable in the latest years. It has some nice ideas, and usually, White wants to get out of theory. Take note that now White is threatening to take on c6 and then on e5.} Be7 $1 {This accurate move is one of the good ways to handle the 5.Nc3 line. We are postponing b5 a bit because the move is premature. White will return to b3, and some Ng5 or Nd5 threats are coming.} 6. O-O (6. Bxc6 $5 dxc6 7. Nxe5 $6 Nxe4 $1 {We are not losing a pawn!} 8. Nxe4 Qd4 9. d3 Qxe5 10. O-O Be6 11. Re1 Qf5 $36 {This position is easier to play with Black because we have the bishop pair and a better pawn structure.}) (6. d3 d6 $1 7. O-O b5 8. Bb3 Na5 $15 9. h3 Nxb3 10. axb3 Bb7 $11 {With a perfect game for Black. c5 is coming soon.} (10... c6 11. d4 {Also a move that can be considered and Black is doing good.} Qc7 $11)) 6... b5 $1 {only now b5!} 7. Bb3 d6 8. a4 $1 (8. d3 $6 Na5) (8. Nd5 Na5 $1 {In the e4 - e5 systems like the Spanish or Italian, we have already mentioned that we don't have a problem giving up the dark-squared bishop for a knight.} 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. d4 (10. d3 O-O 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Nxb3 13. axb3 c5 14. Re1 Qe6 $132 (14... Kh8 15. Qd2 {The idea behind this move is to prepare to play g5.} Bg4 $11 (15... Rg8 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11))) 10... h6 $132) 8... b4 9. Nd5 Na5 $3 10. Nxe7 (10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Ba2 O-O 12. d3 Rb8 $132 13. h3 (13. c3 $4 b3 14. Bb1 c5 15. d4 {We don't allow White to play d4 and Bd3.} c4 16. Be3 Bg4 $17 {Our idea is to take on f3 later. Having the bishop pair doesn't matter here since White's queenside is very passive. The principle here is to exchange White's active pieces.}) 13... Bd7 $11) 10... Qxe7 11. Ba2 c5 12. d3 h6 $132) (5. Qe2 $6 {Playable move, but it doesn't blunder anything, but very soon, our idea will be to put a rook on e8 to harass the queen. This is a bad move for White. Black has a lot of playable options.} b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 $1 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 d6 9. d3 h6 $132 {With a great game for Black. We can feel that White's queen is very misplaced on e2.} 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 Qe7 12. d4 Bg4 (12... Na5 13. Bc2 c5 $11) 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nbd2 Na5 15. Bc2 c5 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Rfd8 $11 {With a great advantage for Black.}) (5. Bxc6 {Interesting move. White can play 5. Bxc6 or 6. Bxc6. Nothing so special here, meaning Black is at least equal. White plays first Ba4 and then takes on c6, and the idea behind it is that White wants to wait for Black to put his knight in f6, where the knight is misplaced. We prefer to have the knight on one of the three magical for us squares - g6, e6, or c6.} dxc6 6. d3 {Interesting way to play as White and get out of book. Both sides have many ideas here. We have to learn how to understand how to play these positions.} Bd6 $1 {Objectively the best move. In some lines, 0-0 is interesting, and in some, 0-0-0.} 7. Nbd2 Be6 $1 {The most accurate. We are preparing 0-0-0 and also stopping Nc4.} 8. O-O (8. Ng5 $6 Bg4 $15) 8... Nd7 9. Re1 f6 10. Nf1 Qe7 $1 (10... O-O $36) 11. Ne3 O-O-O $15 {Black has chances for a very strong attack!} 12. a3 g5) (5. d4 $6 {Not a good move for White, where Black can get a nice play. Sometimes if we don't know what to do in such lines, it can appear quite dangerous. That is why we will check the following game - Djurovic - Stefanou.} exd4 6. e5 (6. O-O Be7) 6... Ne4 7. O-O Nc5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Nxd4 O-O $15) 5... d6 6. c3 (6. O-O $2 b5 {Not a good move by White because he allows us to play b5 - Na5.} 7. Bb3 Na5 $11) (6. c4 {Playable and very decent move. White's idea is to play moves like h3, Be3, and sometimes fast Nc3 - d5.} Bg4 $1 {simple and good!} (6... g6 $1 $132 {Good move, there is a lot of theory but Black can play it.}) 7. h3 (7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Be3 g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 O-O $132) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nd7 9. Be3 g6 $5 $132 (9... Be7 $132) 10. Nc3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. a3 a5 $132) 6... g6 $1 {Against slow play wth c3 we fianchetto our bishop.} 7. O-O (7. h3 $5 {A very strange system, the idea is to put the bishop on e3 and castle followed up by Nbd2. The strength of this system is that all classical approaches played by Black fail!} Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O (9. Nbd2 Nd7 10. Bb3 $132 Nc5) 9... Ne7 $1 {Unusual move, intending c5. I like the idea by GM Korobov very much.} 10. Nbd2 b5 11. Bc2 c5 $132) (7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. Nf1 O-O 9. Bg5 d5 $1 $132 {Carlsen -Caruana 2010 ( see game session)} 10. Qe2 Qd6 (10... h6 $5 $132)) 7... Bg7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Re1 Re8 $1 {That is a good move in every case. Black waits for White to go Nf1 and start the queen-side actions. The idea is to avoid any a4-b4-Nb3 actions made by White after Black plays b5.} (9... b5 {For all the amateur players, this move is good enough.} 10. Bb3 $6 (10. Bc2 $1 Re8 11. Nf1 Bb7 12. Ng3 Nb8 $132 {Na5 makes no sense now, and we still want to push c5, so we use the so-called Brayer maneuver - Nb8 intending Nbd7. There are some small problems in this position. In most cases, White would play 11. Nf1, which is not scary. However, if White knows what he is doing, he will go for 11. a4 followed by b4 - Nb3.}) 10... Na5 11. Bc2 c5 12. Nf1 h6 $3 {Since the knight is on a5 and far from the d5 square, we shouldn't allow White to play Bg5 and capture the knight on f6. That would weaken the d5 square too much.} (12... Re8 $6 13. Bg5 $1 h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Ne3 $14) 13. Ng3 Re8 $15 14. h3 (14. d4 $2 exd4 $3 (14... cxd4 15. cxd4 exd4 16. Nxd4 h5 $15) 15. cxd4 Bg4 $3 $17 {see the game Loutragotis-Papaioannou} 16. d5 Nc4 17. Bd3 Nd7 $3 $17) 14... Bb7 $15 15. d4 $2 exd4 16. cxd4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Rc8 18. b3 d5 19. e5 Ne4 $19) 10. Nf1 (10. h3 h6 $3 11. Nf1 b5 12. Bc2 (12. Bb3 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. Ng3 Qc7 (14... Bb7 $11) 15. Be3 d5 $11 {Comfortable play for Black.}) 12... Bb7 {This is the normal continuation followed by the Brayer maneuver Nb8-Nbd7} 13. Ng3 Nb8 14. d4 Nbd7 $132) 10... b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. Ng3 Nb8 13. h3 (13. d4 Nbd7 $132) 13... c5 $1 $132 14. d4 $2 exd4 15. cxd4 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Nbd7 $17 0-1

