{[%evp 0,74,23,23,25,25,25,28,27,24,24,-32,-21,-20,-13,-9,4,10,16,8,37,19,16,0,14,2,2,5,22,-16,-32,-53,-43,-34,-45,-39,-43,-128,-99,-126,-92,-110,-88,-163,-152,-165,-180,-219,-219,-248,-168,-179,-163,-173,-122,-126,-119,-120,-117,-237,-232,-227,-166,-197,-174,-196,-212,-218,-220,-264,-266,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29998,-29999,-30000] A MODEL GAME BY BLACK !!!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Be3 Ne7 $1 {A very important thing to remember here is that we should develop with Ne7!-Ng6! the knight is never good on f6.} 10. f3 Ng6 11. Kf2 Bb4 {Annoying the knight. Our idea is to take what will lead to a better endgame for black} 12. Nde2 (12. Rad1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 b6 14. Rhe1 c5 $15) 12... Rhe8 13. a3 Bf8 14. Rad1 Ne5 {Threathening Nc4. Look at the theoretical file} 15. g3 Nc4 16. Bc1 Bc5+ 17. Kg2 Be3 18. Na4 c5 19. b3 Bxa4 20. bxc4 Bxc1 21. Rxc1 Rd2 22. Kf2 Bxc2 23. Ke1 Red8 24. Nf4 Rd1+ 25. Ke2 R1d2+ 26. Ke3 c6 27. Nd5 Rd3+ 28. Ke2 cxd5 29. Rxc2 dxe4 30. fxe4 R3d4 31. Kf3 Rd3+ 32. Kf4 Rxa3 33. Re1 Kc7 34. e5 Rd4+ 35. Kf5 Rf3+ 36. Kg5 h6+ 37. Kh5 Rf5# 0-1

