{[%evp 0,74,23,25,25,25,33,27,27,27,27,-13,-9,-4,-12,-1,5,7,10,4,16,12,16,2,14,9,9,3,6,1,13,-25,-21,-39,-55,-57,-54,-67,-54,-54,-40,-55,-41,-39,-14,-42,-32,-32,-1,-34,-4,-74,-76,-95,-88,-88,-78,-153,-152,-236,-174,-174,-192,-197,-144,-144,-185,-174,-202,-128,-126,-305,-389,-386,-315,-570,-572] another model game by black} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Be3 O-O-O 9. f3 Ne7 10. Nc3 Ng6 11. O-O-O Bb4 12. Nde2 (12. Nce2 Rhe8 13. c3 Bf8 14. Rhe1 c5 {As mentioned before, we must be careful when to play the move c5. It is good because White moved his knight far from the d5 square here.} 15. Nb3 b6 16. Nf4 Nxf4 17. Bxf4 a5 $15 {We have a better comfortable position. Enjoying the bishop pair}) 12... Rhe8 13. a3 Bd6 14. Rhe1 h6 15. Bd4 f6 16. g3 c5 17. Bf2 Ne5 18. Ng1 Bc6 19. Nd5 Nc4 20. Ne3 Nxe3 21. Bxe3 h5 22. Nh3 g5 {All these positions are considered to be better for Black. Our idea, later on, will be to push a5-a4 followed by b5-b4, which will help us gain a lot of space and it will force white to undouble our pawns at some point.} 23. Nf2 Rd7 24. Rd2 Rh7 25. Nd1 g4 26. fxg4 hxg4 27. Rf1 Re6 28. Rdf2 Bxe4 29. Rxf6 Rxf6 30. Rxf6 Rxh2 31. Nf2 Bh7 32. Rf7 Bxg3 33. Nxg4 Rxc2+ 34. Kd1 Bd3 35. Bc1 Rg2 36. Ne3 Rh2 37. Bd2 Rh1+ 0-1

