1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 {A very interesting system for White. It is not particularly dangerous if Black knows what he is doing. White is threatening to take on e5. The advantages of 5.d3 are that White could take us out of the book theoretically if we don't know what we are doing, and White may have studied this position well, or even simple moves are good for White without much theory. Another advantage is that the move is good and playable. The disadvantages are that when White plays d3, he is a bit late with c3 -b4. It also allows Black to choose where to develop his dark-squared bishop since the c5, e7 and g7 squares are all options.} d6 {Since White's idea is to play slowly with d3 - c3 the best squere for our bishop will be on g7.} 6. c3 (6. O-O {Not a good move by White because he allows us to play b5 - Na5.} b5 7. Bb3 Na5 8. Nbd2 (8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4 c5 $19) 8... Nxb3 9. axb3 c5 10. c3 {White tries to react fast, so we don't have enough time to play g6 - Bg7. Then we put the bishop on e7.} (10. Re1 {White is slow, so now we have time to continue with the original plan of putting the bishop on g7.} g6 11. h3 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. d4 cxd4 14. cxd4 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bb7 $17) 10... Be7 11. d4 Qc7 $11) 6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 h6 $3 {A very useful waiting move. The idea is to wait for White to play Nf1 and only then to continue with b5 because the idea with a4- b4 -Nb3 is no longer there.} (9... b5 {For all the amateur players, this move is good enough.} 10. Bb3 (10. Bc2 Nb8 {Na5 makes no sense now, and we still want to push c5, so we use the so-called Brayer maneuver - Nb8 intending Nbd7. There are some small problems in this position. In most cases, White would play 11.Nf1, which is not scary. However, if White knows what he is doing, he will go for 11. a4 followed by b4 - Nb3.} 11. Nf1 (11. a4 Bb7 12. b4 Nbd7 13. Nb3 Rb8 $14 {We don't like the fixing of the structure.}) 11... c5 12. Ng3 Nbd7 13. d4 exd4 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bb7 $15) 10... Na5 11. Bc2 c5 12. Nf1 h6 {Since the knight is on a5 and it is far from the d5 square, we shouldn't allow White to play Bg5 and capture the knight on f6. That would weaken the d5 square too much.} 13. Ng3 Re8 14. a4 b4 15. cxb4 cxb4 $15 {We always have some b3 ideas.}) 10. Nf1 Re8 $1 {That is a good move in every case. Black is waiting for White to make another extra move with the knight and put it on g3.} (10... b5 {Playable now.} 11. Bb3 (11. Bc2 Bb7 $11) 11... Na5 12. Bc2 c5 $11) 11. h3 (11. Ng3 b5 $1 12. Bc2 (12. Bb3 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 $36) 12... Bb7 $5 13. h3 Nb8 $132 14. d4 Nbd7 15. Bd2 c6 $11 {Postponing all ideas for later.} (15... c5 16. d5 Qc7 $11 {With a nice game. We are doing fine.})) 11... b5 12. Bc2 (12. Bb3 $6 Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. Ng3 Bb7 (14... Qc7 15. Be3 d5) 15. d4 $2 (15. Be3 c4 $3 (15... Rc8 $1) 16. b4 $2 (16. d4 exd4 17. Bxd4 (17. cxd4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxe4) (17. Nxd4 Nxe4) 17... Nc6 18. Be3 d5) 16... cxd3 17. Bxd3 Nc4 $17) (15. Bd2 c4 $2 (15... Nc6) (15... d5) 16. d4 exd4 17. cxd4) (15. a4 d5 $36) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Rc8 $17 18. Bf4 Nc4 19. b3 Na3 $3 $19) 12... a5 $1 {Very important so pay attention and be careful! In 99% of the cases, a5 is bad in the Ruy Lopez because white plays a2-a4 and he gains control over the light squares on the queenside - b3,c4,b5. But only here12...a5! is good due to concrete reasons.} (12... Bb7 $1 {this is the normal continuation followed by the Brayer maneuver - Nb8-Nbd7} 13. Ng3 Nb8 14. d4 Nbd7 $132 15. d5 Nb6 $1 16. a4 c6 17. axb5 (17. a5 Nc4 $15) 17... axb5 $36 (17... cxd5 $132)) 13. a4 b4 14. Ng3 Rb8 $1 15. d4 (15. Bb3 d5 $1 16. exd5 Nxd5 $15 {Despite the weaknesses, Black is doing very well because the bishop on g7 at some point will also be targeting the pawn on c3.}) 15... bxc3 16. bxc3 exd4 17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Bb3 $2 (18. Bb1 c5 $36 19. dxc5 $2 dxc5 $17) 18... Bb7 $17 19. e5 dxe5 (19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 dxe5 21. dxe5 Nd3 22. Re3 Rxb3 $17 (22... Nxe5 23. Qe2 Nd5 24. Bxd5 Qxd5 $17 25. Ra2 Red8)) 20. Nxe5 Bd5 21. Rb1 c5 22. dxc5 Bxb3 23. Rxb3 (23. Qxb3 Rxe5 24. Rxe5 Nc6 25. Qc2 Rxb1 26. Qxb1 Nxe5 $19) 23... Rxe5 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 25. Rxe5 Rd1+ 26. Nf1 Rxc1 27. g3 Bf8 28. Rf3 Kg7 29. Kg2 Nd7 30. Re8 Nxc5 31. Nd2 Nbd3 32. Nb3 Rd1 33. Nxc5 Bxc5 34. Kh2 Rd2 35. Rd8 Ne5 0-1

