{A very good and famous example about the blockade of a knight!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Re1 {I would say this move is inaccurate because we need this rook on the ''f'' file so White can play f4 later on. Move such as d3 would have been more accurate.} Nd7 8. d4 {White's plan is not d4 usually.} (8. d3 O-O 9. Nc3 (9. Nbd2 c5 10. Nf1 f6 11. Ng3 Re8 12. Bd2 (12. Nf5 Bf8 $11) 12... Nb8 13. h3 Nc6 $15) 9... c5 10. Be3 f6 11. Nd5 (11. h3 Re8 (11... Nb8 $5) 12. Qd2 Nf8 13. Nd5 Bd6 $15) 11... Bd6 $13) 8... exd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Bf4 Nc5 11. Qxd8 Bxd8 12. Nc3 f5 {Black is already slightly better. In this position, White played the worst possible move.} 13. e5 (13. Bg5 fxe4 {Strategically speaking the best move.} 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 Bf5 16. Re2 Bg4 $11) 13... Ne6 {The knight is the best blocker. Now Black's plan and idea is to stop White from coming too close to the knight. Theoretically, the knight on e6 can be challenged from 3 squares - d4, f4, and g5. So for Black to have a big advantage, he has to keep these 3 squares in control.} 14. Bd2 (14. Be3 f4 $19) 14... g5 15. Ne2 c5 {Stoping Nd4 and also threatening g4 to win a piece.} 16. Bc3 b5 17. b3 Bb7 18. Ng3 {The knight is coming to h5 and then to f6. We can't control all the possible squares of the knight, so we need to decide which squares to allow access to the White's knight.} g4 19. Nd2 Be7 20. Nh5 Kf7 21. Nf1 Kg6 {We play around the knight on f6.} 22. Nf6 Rad8 23. Rad1 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rd8 25. Rxd8 Bxd8 26. Ne3 f4 27. Nd1 Bxf6 28. exf6 Be4 29. Bb2 b4 30. f3 Bxc2 31. Nf2 gxf3 32. gxf3 Bb1 33. Ne4 Bxa2 34. Nd2 a5 35. Kf2 Nd4 36. Bxd4 cxd4 37. Ke2 Kxf6 38. Kd3 Ke5 39. Kc2 a4 40. bxa4 c5 41. a5 c4 42. a6 d3+ 0-1

