{In terms of theory, this game does not belong here....however, it is very instructive to see how black is handling the position !} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 $1 {Coming from a different variation, but we use the same ideas.} 8. Ne2 (8. a3 Bd6 $11 {[%cal Yf8e8]}) 8... Re8 9. Ng3 {This move appears good, but it isn't because the knight steps away from the f4 square. A better idea would have been to play h3, Nh2, and f4. Therefore when White plays Ng3 it looks good but the knight doesn't do anything.} (9. Bd2 Bf8 $1 10. Bc3 c5 11. Ng3 f6 $1 12. h3 Nb8 $15 {Remember we said many times before the three magical squares for the knight are g6, e6, and c6!}) 9... Bf8 10. h3 (10. d4 {We mention once again that pushing d4 here is not the idea.} exd4 11. Qxd4 Nc5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Be3 Ne6 14. Rad1 Bd7 15. Ne5 Be8 $11) 10... c5 $1 11. b3 Nb8 $1 12. Bb2 Nc6 13. Nh2 Nd4 $5 14. Ne2 a5 $1 15. a4 Ra6 $1 {The idea behind a5. In chess, we shouldn't only be thinking in files but also ranks.} 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. f4 exf4 18. Rxf4 Rg6 19. Rf3 c5 20. Qf1 Bd6 21. Qf2 (21. Rxf7 Bxh3 $19) 21... Qc7 22. Nf1 Re5 23. Rg3 Rxg3 24. Nxg3 Bxh3 25. Bc1 Re6 26. Nf5 Rg6 27. Nxd6 Rxg2+ 28. Qxg2 Bxg2 29. Bf4 Bh3 30. Kf2 Qe7 31. Rg1 h6 32. e5 Kh7 33. Ne4 Be6 34. Rh1 Bf5 35. Nd6 Bd7 36. Ne4 Bc6 37. Bxh6 gxh6 0-1

