{Coming once again from a different opening but another very clean performance by Black in these typical positions.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Bd6 (7... Nd7 {is also very good of course. The theory is once again irrelevant here !} 8. Ne2 Re8 9. Bd2 Bd6 $132) 8. Ne2 c5 9. Ng3 Re8 10. b3 Nd7 11. Bg5 $2 (11. Nf5 Nf8 12. Nxd6 cxd6 $15 {Followed by Ng6 and f5.}) 11... f6 12. Be3 Nf8 $15 13. Nh4 (13. Nd2 b6 14. Nf5 Bxf5 $2 {Be careful. We don't take the knight on f5 because White can defend the pawn f5 and we free the square e4 for the knight. Avoid that at all costs.} 15. exf5 Qd7 16. Qf3) 13... g6 14. Qd2 Ne6 15. Ne2 Rf8 16. Bh6 Rf7 17. Nf3 Bd7 18. h3 Kh8 19. Nh2 g5 20. h4 Qg8 21. hxg5 fxg5 22. Ng3 Qg6 23. Nf5 Rg8 24. Nf3 Qf6 25. Nh2 Qg6 26. Nf3 Qh5 27. b4 Nd4 28. Nxg5 Rxg5 29. Bxg5 Ne2+ 30. Qxe2 Qxe2 31. Rae1 Qh5 32. f4 Bxf5 33. exf5 Rxf5 34. fxe5 Rxf1+ 35. Rxf1 Qxg5 36. exd6 cxd6 37. bxc5 Qxc5+ 38. Rf2 Qd4 0-1

