{[%evp 0,9,31,29,30,30,8,8,31,5,-3,-34] This is the introduction to 5. 0-0 in
the possible alternatives that White can play. We have already checked the
other sidelines and are ready to move on to this very interesting move.
White's most common idea in this line is to play Re1 right after 0-0 and go
for a setup with c3 and d4. Along the way, we will also check any other moves
and lines that may occur.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O {
The most ambitious move.} Be7 {This is the main starting position of the
lecture. At this point, besides the main move 6.Re1, Papaioannou examines 6.
Bxc6, 6.d3, and 6.d4. The move 6.d3 is particularly challenging and you need
to study it very carefully. Once again, however, it's not a matter of theory.
You should understand the subtleties of the arising positions. This lecture
also covers the so-called Yates Variation which occurs after 6.Re1 b5 7.Bb3 d6
8.c3 0-0 9.d4. If Black knows what he is doing, this line is not particularly
challenging.} *

