[SourceQuality "1"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O {The most ambitious move. Still, you have to pay attention to all the other alternatives.} Be7 6. Re1 {The most ambitious move. White intends to play c3 and d4, and at the moment, White is threatening to take on c6 and win the e5 pawn, so get used to the move order so you don't blunder anything.} (6. Bxc6 $5 {this makes more sense here ..after waiting for a Be7 move first! so ..if white wants to take on c6, he better do it on Move 6 and not on Move 5 !!!} dxc6 7. d3 (7. Nc3 Bg4 $1 (7... Nd7 $1 8. d3 O-O) 8. h3 Bh5 9. d3 Nd7 $15) 7... Nd7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nc4 f6 10. Nh4 Nc5 $1 11. Nf5 Ne6 $132) (6. d3 $1 {d3 on move number 6 is considered a very interesting alternative for White to avoid the main lines and get very interesting strategical positions.} b5 7. Bb3 d6 {Accurate move since we do not intend to play moves like d5.} 8. a3 $1 {Very fashionable position, the idea behind is that White wants to keep the bishop on the a2 - g8 diagonal. Here we have many interesting ideas, but I chose the line with 0-0, followed by h6-Re8 and quite often Na5 and c7-c5.} (8. Nc3 $6 Na5 9. d4 exd4 10. Nxd4 c5 $19) (8. a4 {Interesting move. It seems like White gets some small advantage on the queen's side, but in the long run, White is risking ending up in a position in a close type of Spanish with Na5 and c5 where we know that the a4 move is irrelevant and White is playing on the wrong side of the board.} Bd7 $1 (8... Bb7 $6 {Strategically risky. The bishop makes sense on b7 when White plays with c3 and d4, not with d3. Now the bishop is misplaced. On the other hand, the bishop on b7 can't counter the bishop on b3. So we risk getting into a worse position.}) 9. c3 (9. axb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Qxa8 $11) 9... O-O 10. Nbd2 Na5 11. Bc2 (11. Ba2 bxa4 $11 {Not so easy for White. We get an extra pawn, and in my opinion, it is a nice position.} (11... c5 $11)) 11... c5 12. Re1 Qc7 $11 {Ideas like c4 are always in the air.}) (8. c3 {this move is the most popular choice among amateur players !} O-O 9. Nbd2 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. Re1 Re8 12. Nf1 h6 $3 {Preventing Bg5!} (12... Bf8 $6 {A serious inaccuracy.The correct idea but not the correct move at the moment. Bf8, we could play if the knight was not on a5 but on d7 instead. We mentioned earlier that we don't want to weaken the d5 square too much, and right now, the only piece that controls the d5 square is the knight on f6. Playing Bf8 allows White to exchange this knight.} 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Ne3 $14) 13. Ng3 Bf8 14. h3 $13 Bd7 $3 15. d4 Nc4 {For Nc4 to work, the rooks should be connected and work well with each other. That is good because there are no minor pieces between the rooks.} 16. d5 Nb6 $132) (8. Bd2 $5 {an interesting idea...stopping Na5} O-O $5 (8... Bg4 $5 {we can even start with this move !} 9. c3 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4 11. Qd1 Nxb3 12. axb3 O-O) 9... Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. h3 Bd7 $1 (11... Bh5 $1 12. Be3 O-O $132 13. Nbd2 Rc8 (13... Nc6 14. g4 (14. Re1 d5) 14... Bg6) 14. g4 Bg6 15. Re1 Nc6 $132 (15... h6 $1 $132 16. Nh4 Nh7 $5 (16... Bh7))) 12. d4 Qc7 $132 13. b3 O-O 14. d5 g6 $132) 9. Re1 (9. h3 Rb8 $5 10. a3 Be6 $132 (10... Bd7 $5 11. Nc3 Na5 12. Ba2 c5 13. Nd5 Nc6 $132)) 9... Bg4 $1 {provoking c3} 10. c3 (10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nd4 12. Qd1 Nxb3 13. axb3 c6 $132) 10... Na5 11. Bc2 c5 12. h3 Bh5 $5 {a very rare exception when Bg4 and Bh5 are good ...with the white pawn on d3 !!!} (12... Be6 $5 13. d4 Nc4 14. Bc1 Qc7 $132 {with a very good position... and similar ply with the Chigorin main line!} 15. b3 Nb6 16. d5 Bd7 $132)) 8... O-O 9. Nc3 h6 $5 {Our plans remain the same - Re8, Bf8, and Na5 at a good moment! White has many options now, but we have similar ideas against every single one.} 10. Nd5 (10. Be3 Re8 11. Nd5 {The same idea. We want our ideas to depend on plans, not on memorizing the moves.} Na5 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Ba2 Be6 $132 (13... c6 $5 14. b4 Nb7 15. c4 Be6 16. h3 Qd7 $11)) (10. Re1 Na5 (10... Re8 $5 11. Nd5 Na5 $132 12. Ba2 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Ba2 Bf8 15. b4 Nb7 $132 {The same typical ideas.}) 11. Ba2 c5 12. Nd5 Be6 $132) (10. h3 Re8 11. Bd2 (11. Nd5 Na5 12. Ba2 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Ba2 Bf8 15. Bd2 Nb7 $132 (15... Be6 $132 {At some point, we will push d5, and our knight on b7 is in control of the c5 and a5 squares, and at any moment, it can go to d6.}) 16. b4 Be6 $11) 11... Na5 12. Ba2 c5 13. Nd5 Nc6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Bd5 Bd7 16. c3 Rb8 $132 17. b4 Ne7 18. Bb3 Ng6 $11) 10... Re8 $5 {Also possible. Same ideas.} (10... Na5 11. Nxf6+ (11. Ba2 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 (12. exd5 $2 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Yf7f5]}) 12... c6 {Our knight is bad temporarily but so is his bishop on a2. On the other hand, exd5 allows moves such as f5 at the right moment.} 13. Ba2 Nb7 14. c3 Bf6 15. b4 Re8 16. c4 (16. h3 d5 $15) 16... Be6 $132 17. Bd2) 11... Bxf6 12. Ba2 c5 $1 13. b4 Nc6 14. Bd5 Bd7 15. bxc5 dxc5 16. Be3 Qb6 $132) 11. c3 Na5 $132 12. Ba2 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Ba2 Nb7 15. d4 Bf6 $132) (6. d4 $5 exd4 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxd4 O-O $1 (8... Nc5 $5 9. Nf5 $1 {This move was working in the previous position that we checked - without both sides 0-0 and the bishop still on f8. Here White has this very nice move Nf5.} O-O 10. Qg4 g6 $1 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. Bxc6 dxc6 13. Qg3 Re8 14. Re1 Bf5 15. Nc3 Ne6 $132) 9. Nf5 (9. Re1 Nc5 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Nc3 f5 $1 {The typical blocking idea.} 12. f4 $2 (12. exf6 Bxf6 $132) 12... Ne6 $17) 9... d5 10. Nxe7+ Nxe7 {White has the bishop pair, but typically, our bishop goes to f5, and it is so active that White would soon be forced to exchange the pair of bishops.} 11. c3 Nc5 12. Bc2 Bf5 $132) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 (8. h3 $6 Na5 $15 9. d4 $2 exd4 $1 10. Nxd4 $4 c5 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. exf5 c4 $19) (8. a4 $6 Bd7 9. c3 O-O 10. d4 h6 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Nf1 Bf8 13. Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2 c5 15. d5 c4 $15 {Now this a4 move shows that Black is slightly better because White has weakened some of his squares with his a4 brilliancy, b3-d3-a4} 16. h3 Qc7 17. Be3 Nb7 18. Qd2 Nc5 $11) 8... O-O 9. d4 $5 {This is a harmless but playable alternative.} Bg4 $1 {The only good move is putting pressure in the center.} 10. Be3 $1 (10. h3 $2 Bxf3 $15) (10. d5 $6 Na5 11. Bc2 {Our structure on the queenside is compromised with the a6 - b5, so we need to do something about it fast.} c6 $3 12. h3 (12. dxc6 Qc7 $11 {We want to take with the queen and later put the knight on c4 because the knight on c6 is a bit misplaced.}) 12... Bc8 $3 {A very nice move. We are threatening to take on d5. In the game Andreikin - Ding, you will see another alternative - Bxf3.} 13. dxc6 Qc7 $3 {Taking on c6 with the queen because the knight is not doing much there.} 14. Nbd2 Qxc6 15. a4 Be6 $132 16. Ng5 Bd7 $11) 10... exd4 $1 11. cxd4 Na5 12. Bc2 (12. e5 $2 dxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 $15 14. Bc2 Nc4 15. Qd3 g6 16. Bh6 Re8 $15) 12... Nc4 13. Bc1 c5 14. b3 (14. d5 $2 Nd7 $17 {and this is a terrible Benoni for White!} 15. h3 (15. Nbd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 (16. Bxd2 Ne5 $17) 16... Bf6 $17 (16... Bxf3 $17)) 15... Bxf3 $1 16. Qxf3 Bf6 17. Nc3 Qa5 $17) 14... Nb6 15. Nbd2 (15. Bb2 cxd4 16. Bxd4 (16. Nbd2 Rc8 17. Bxd4 Nbd7 $11 {Improving the position of the knight because there is nothing worse than a bad knight in chess.}) 16... Rc8 $132) 15... cxd4 16. Bb2 Rc8 17. Bxd4 Nbd7 $132 18. h3 Bh5 19. a4 (19. Qb1 $2 Ne5 $1 $15 20. Nh4 Bg6 21. Nxg6 hxg6 $15) 19... Nc5 $132 0-1

