{[%evp 0,138,16,28,38,44,44,-1,8,-27,2,0,-9,-44,-1,1,1,-45,-27,-28,-33,-27,-9,-9,-13,-27,-21,-30,-16,5,31,0,7,-4,3,-6,-3,3,-5,-1,0,2,-2,7,11,0,0,0,2,-5,5,-19,5,-15,-15,-77,-80,-69,-47,-48,-46,-61,-49,-49,-44,-36,-42,-61,-33,-33,-21,-13,-14,-14,-65,-61,-61,-62,-75,-75,-14,-115,-115,-115,-128,-130,-130,-111,-122,-105,-109,-127,-95,-140,-144,-125,-123,-125,-140,-140,-152,-152,-128,-152,-152,-152,-152,-142,-142,-142,-142,-142,-142,-142,-142,-162,-185,-201,-192,-192,-192,-189,-203,-217,-168,-173,-167,-176,-186,-176,-193,-176,-195,-225,-225,-390,-383,-380,-356,-361,-389]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {this is what most amateur players will play!} O-O 9. d3 {we reach the same line shown in the theoretical file by transposition.} Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2 {and now...2 plans for Black: Nc6-h6 ...or Re8-h6!-Bf8-g6 etc.....I learn them both!} (11. d4 {In this particular position, we don't want to double capture on d4 as Black because then White will have a very simple play with the upcoming Nc3. We choose to take on d4 once and then play fast Bg4.} cxd4 (11... exd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. d5 Nc4 $15 {[%cal Yf6d7,Ye7f6] Important to play Nc4 immediately because otherwise, our knight might end up being displaced after b3.}) 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. dxe5 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 dxe5 $11 {[%cal Ya5c6,Yc6d4]}) 11... Nc6 (11... Re8 12. Nf1 h6 13. Ng3 Bf8 14. h3 Bd7 15. d4 Nc4 16. d5 Nb6 $11) 12. Nf1 h6 13. Ng3 Re8 14. h3 Bf8 15. Qe2 $6 {The queen is not well placed against our rook. Now White is never threatening d4, and our d5 idea is gaining strength.} Be6 {Remember this setup. It is also a possible setup instead of the one with g6 and Bg7.} (15... d5 16. exd5 $11) 16. Bb3 Qd7 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. a4 Na5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Be3 Nb3 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Qc2 Na1 23. Qb1 Qa2 24. Qc1 Qa4 25. Re2 Kh7 26. Kh2 g6 27. c4 Nb3 28. Qc2 Nd7 29. cxb5 Qxb5 30. Nd2 Nxd2 31. Rxd2 Rb8 32. Ne2 Qb3 33. Qc1 Nb6 34. Nc3 Qe6 35. f4 d5 36. exd5 Nxd5 37. Nxd5 Qxd5 38. Qc4 Qxc4 39. dxc4 Rb3 