{[%evp 0,24,29,30,30,30,9,4,31,0,0,-12,0,3,20,-31,-6,-26,-23,-13,-12,8,4,7,27,
15,36] In the following file and games, we will get familiar with the Chigorin
main lines.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7.
c3 d6 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 {The main and best
move. Here we have two very interesting options. Bd7 is the safer option. Nd7
is shaky and unstable but worth it.} (12. Nbd2 {is an inaccurate move but you
will see many players playing it. We will see how to react to it properly and
what Black's ideas are in such positions.} Bd7) 12... Bd7 {Probaby the most
important idea that you should remember is that in such closed positions, we
often go for Rubinstein's maneuver, which is putting the pawns on f6 and g6,
and playing Nb7-d8-f7, Nh5-g7. In some cases pushing c4 is also good and we
will see when.} (12... Nd7 {Here, the idea is that the knight first goes to b6
and then Black continues with Bd7 and his ideas. We will see that Black can go
for half of Rubinstein's maneuver, bringing the knight from a5 to f7. Also, we
will see ideas with c4 and a5 play on the queenside.}) *

