{[%evp 0,48,19,21,31,48,22,9,17,-27,-6,-35,10,-51,-3,0,-1,-37,-18,-18,-14,-13,-21,-21,-5,27,15,36,31,42,45,26,40,29,35,20,15,25,32,2,2,1,11,7,1,0,-18,-35,-16,-40,-35]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 $5 {This is by far the best move. However, many players randomly play the inferior 12.Nbd2, which seems natural, but it is not so good.} (12. Nbd2 $6 Bd7 13. Nf1 {At some point, we have to take on d4 but there is this rule - every time a move like Ne3 is possible, we don't take on d4. Whenever this is possible, our position is not good. Therefore, it is too early to take on d4.} (13. a3 $6 {White is playing some waiting move and wants to control the situation better.} cxd4 (13... Rac8 $5 14. d5 c4 $132 {The knight goes Nb7 - c5.}) 14. cxd4 Rac8 15. Bd3 exd4 $1 {We don't have time for moves like Re8 because then d5 is coming and this time Nb7 - c5 is not an option because white plays b4 and White is better.} 16. Nxd4 Rfe8 17. Nf5 $2 (17. N2f3 Nc4 18. b3 Ne5 $132) 17... Bxf5 18. exf5 d5 $3 $15 {a very typical action!} 19. Nf3 Nc4 $3 $15 20. b3 Nd6 21. Bf4 (21. Bb2 Nde4 22. Rc1 Qf4 $36) 21... Qb7 22. Rc1 Nde4 $15) (13. dxe5 $2 dxe5 14. Nf1 Rad8 15. Qe2 Rfe8 (15... c4 16. Bg5 $11) 16. Ne3 Bf8 17. Nh2 Be6 18. Nhg4 Nxg4 19. hxg4 Nc6 $1 20. a4 c4 21. axb5 axb5 22. Nd5 Qc8 $15) (13. d5 $6 c4 $36 14. Nf1 Nb7 15. g4 (15. Ng3 Nc5 16. Nh2 a5 $36) (15. Bd2 Nc5 16. g4 (16. b4 cxb3 17. axb3 a5 $11 {[%csl Yb4]}) 16... g6 $11) 15... g6 $1 (15... h5 $3 {If you want to memorize that is a good move to play here.} 16. gxh5 g6 17. hxg6 fxg6 $15) 16. Ng3 Nc5 17. Bh6 Rfb8 $132 (17... Rfe8 $4 18. g5 $18)) 13... Rfe8 14. Ne3 (14. Ng3 cxd4 $5 {Now we can take because there is no Ne3 anymore.} (14... Nc4 $1 {An alternative, but remember Nc4 is good only when the bishop is already on d7 and the rooks are connected. It also works with the queen on d8, but there should be no other pieces in between the rooks!} 15. Bd3 (15. b3 Nb6 16. Be3 a5 $1 17. Rc1 a4 $1 $132 18. Nd2 axb3 19. axb3 Rec8 20. f4 b4) 15... Nb6 $132) 15. cxd4 Rac8 16. Bd3 Nc6 {Black is doing very well.} 17. d5 (17. Be3 exd4 18. Nxd4 Ne5 $11) 17... Nb4 18. Bb1 Nc2 $15) (14. d5 Nc4 $1 {The idea is to go to b6 later.} 15. Ne3 $5 (15. Ng3 Nb6 16. Nh2 a5 $1 {Not c4 to play Nc4 after f4-exf4, but the idea is to push on the queens' file.} 17. f4 (17. b3 c4 $17) 17... exf4 {We must take otherwise White plays f5 with a dangerous attack.} 18. Bxf4 Nc4 $3 19. b3 Ne5 20. Qd2 $2 c4 $17) (15. b3 Nb6 16. Ng3 c4 17. Bd2 a5 $15) (15. a4 Na5 $1 {We have made it clear that pushing a4 in such a position is good for Black and the idea is to have a pawn on c4 and bring the knight to c5.} 16. Ng3 c4 $132 17. Be3 Nb7 $11) 15... Nb6 $5 16. b3 c4 17. Bd2 Rec8 $36) (14. dxe5 $6 {this is rarely good!} dxe5 15. Ne3 Bc6 (15... Rad8) 16. Nf5 Bf8 17. Nh2 Kh8 18. Ng4 Ng8 $36) 14... g6 $5 (14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Nc6 16. Bb3 Rac8 17. dxe5 Nxe5 $132 (17... dxe5 $132 18. Nd5 (18. Ng5 Rf8 19. Nf5 Bxf5 20. exf5 Bb4 $17) 18... Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Nb4 $15)) 15. b3 (15. d5 $6 c4 16. b4 cxb3 17. axb3 Nb7 18. Bd2 Nc5 19. Qb1 a5 $1 $36) 15... Bf8 (15... cxd4 {An idea that you can try to remember: in this type of position where White has weakened the queenside, we can take on d4 - cxd4 after b3!} 16. cxd4 Nc6 $36) 16. Bb2 Bg7 $1 17. d5 Nb7 18. Qd2 c4 19. b4 (19. bxc4 Nc5 $36) 19... a5 20. a3 Rf8 $15 21. Reb1 Bh6 22. Bc1 Nh5 $11) 12... Nd7 $5 {This is another very interesting and playable idea instead of 12...Bd7. Black's idea is first to play Nd7-Nb6..and then continue with Bd7. It is quite possible afterward to follow a half-Rubinshtein maneuver with only one of the knights Nd8-f6-Nf7 !} (12... Bd7 13. b3 {This is a good move for White. If Ndb2, we transpose to the 12. Nbd2. Don't be worried about this position. The computers tend to give White the advantage and for now White might be standing better objectively, but it is very difficult for White to break our defense and we have great chances for counterplay.} Nb7 $1 {This is very similar to g6.} (13... g6 $1 {Similar to Nb7 where we go for the Rubinstein's plan - Nb7-d8, g6 and bringing a knight to g7 followed by f6-Nf7. We play g6 because we can get this plan with various moves and move orders.} 14. Bh6 Rfc8 15. Nbd2 Nh5 16. Nf1 Nb7 17. Ng3 Ng7 $1 18. c4 $5 (18. Qd2 $6 c4 $1 {Only now do we have this better idea than f6, Nd8-f7 because the queen is on d2. We are already familiar with this idea and we happily go for it. Now that the queen is not on d1 we play c4, b4 a5, and usually, when we go for that idea, there is only one move that annoys us and that is a4 for White. But this move doesn't work with the queen on d2, the queen should be on d1 for it to work. Of course, our main idea in general is to go for Rubinstein's idea but we also keep an eye on this c4 idea.} 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Ra6 21. Rac1 axb4 22. axb4 Rca8 $15 23. Nh2 Ra2 24. Qe3 f6 25. f4 Nd8 26. f5 Qa7 $3 $15 {[%cal Yd8f7,Ye7d8,Yd8b6]}) 18... Nd8 19. Bd3 f6 20. Qc2 Nf7 21. Bd2 {It is not easy for White to break our defense. We still have the idea of pushing f5 in the air at a moment when that is possible.} b4 22. a3 a5 23. Rf1 Rf8 $132 24. axb4 axb4 $11) 14. Nbd2 (14. Bg5 Rfc8 (14... h6 15. Be3) 15. Nbd2 Qd8 (15... Bd8 16. Nf1 Ne8 17. Bxd8 Nxd8 18. Ng3 g6 19. Qd2 f6 (19... Ng7 20. Qh6 f6 21. Qh4) 20. Qh6 (20. h4 Nf7 21. h5 Qd8 22. Nh4) 20... Nf7 21. Qh4 g5) 16. Nf1 Ne8 17. Be3 g6 18. g4 Ng7 19. Ng3 Qc7 20. Qd2 $6 c4 21. b4 a5 22. a3 Ra6) 14... g6 15. Nf1 Nh5 16. g4 Ng7 17. Ng3 Rfc8 (17... c4 {Maybe c4 is also good here since White has pushed g4. Also, if White doesn't push b4 we will happily jump on c5 with the knight. When we can't do that, we go for Rubinstein's idea.} 18. b4 a5 19. Bh6 (19. a4 axb4 20. cxb4 bxa4 21. Bxa4 f5 $40) 19... Ra6 $132) 18. Bh6 f6 19. Qd2 $6 (19. Kh2 $1 Nd8 20. Rg1 Nf7 21. Be3 Kh8 {The computer always gives an advantage for White after Rubinstein's plan, but hundreds of games played in this position by players from all levels show that the engine advantage means nothing. We have a position with mutual chances for both sides! It is not easy for either side to attack. White does have some chances on the kingside. However, Black often strikes there with a well-timed Qc8 and f5!} 22. Qd2 $6 c4 23. b4 a5 24. a4 axb4 25. cxb4 bxa4 26. Ra3 c3 27. Qe2 Qc4 28. Qxc4 Rxc4 29. Rb1 f5 $11) 19... c4 $1 {Don't forget about this plan!} 20. b4 a5 21. a3 Ra6 22. Rab1 axb4 23. axb4 Rca8 24. Be3 Ra2 25. Rbc1 Nd8 26. Qd1 Nf7 27. Kh2 Qb7 28. Rg1 Bd8 $17) 13. b3 {Trying to restrict the knights.} (13. Nbd2 {Here, we focus mainly on the ideas and not that much on the move order.} c4 $1 (13... Nb6 $5 14. b3 (14. Nf1 Nb7 15. Ng3 c4 16. Be3 Bd7 17. Qd2 Rfc8 $132 {[%cal Yb7d8,Yf7f6,Yg7g6,Yd8f7]}) 14... Bd7 15. Nf1 Nb7 16. g4 a5 $132) 14. Nf1 Nb6 15. Ng3 Nb7 $132 16. Nf5 Bxf5 $132 {[%cal Yb7c5]}) (13. b4 $5 Nc4 $1 14. a4 Rb8 $5 15. Nbd2 (15. Bd3 f5 $1 16. exf5 Bb7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Bg5 Nf6 $36) (15. g4 $2 cxb4 16. cxb4 bxa4 17. Rxa4 a5 (17... Ndb6 18. Ra2 h5) 18. bxa5 Nb2 19. Bxb2 Rxb2 20. Bd3 Nc5 21. Ra1 h5 $19) 15... Nxd2 16. Bxd2 $6 (16. Nxd2 h6 $1 (16... Bg5) 17. Ra2 (17. Bd3 Bg5 18. Ra2) 17... Bg5 18. Nf1 Bxc1 19. Qxc1 Nb6) 16... Nb6 $132) (13. a4 $2 c4 14. axb5 (14. Na3 bxa4 15. Bxa4 Nc5 16. Bc2 f5 $15) 14... axb5 15. Na3 Rb8 16. Be3 Nc5 17. Nd2 (17. Bxc5 {Unthinkable move for White.} Qxc5 {[%cal Ye7d8,Yd8b6]}) 17... Bd7 $15) (13. Qe2 $6 {Again we play based on our ideas here as Black.} Nb6 14. Nbd2 c4 15. Nf1 (15. Kh1 f5 $15) 15... Nb7 16. g4 a5 $132 17. Ng3 Nc5 18. Kh1 b4 $36) 13... Nb6 14. Nbd2 (14. Nfd2 Bd7 15. Nf1 Nb7 16. Ng3 a5 $132) (14. Qe2 Bd7 15. Nbd2 c4 16. b4 Nb7 17. Nf1 a5 $132 {[%cal Yf7f6,Yb7d8,Yd8f7]}) 14... Bd7 15. Nf1 (15. Ba3 g6 $1 $132 16. Nf1 Bf6 17. Bc1 Nb7 18. Be3 c4 19. b4 a5 20. a3 Bg7 21. N3h2 axb4 22. axb4 Rxa1 23. Qxa1 Ra8 24. Qd1 Nd8 25. Ng3 f6 26. f4 exf4 27. Bxf4 Nf7 {As we can see, nothing is too different. Black sticks to his ideas and gets a nice position.} 28. Nf3 Ne5 29. Rf1 Na4 30. Qd2 Nb2 31. Be3 Nbd3 32. Nxe5 Nxe5 33. Ne2 Ra2 34. Nd4 Qc8 35. Kh2 Qe8 36. Qe1 Nf7 37. Qc1 Ng5 38. Qb1 Ra3 39. Ne2 Qe7 40. Bc1 {1/2-1/2 Pecka,J-Havumдki,A/ICCF 2016/ Nikos Updates}) 15... Nb7 16. Be3 c4 $5 (16... a5 $132 {Also possible with the idea to play c4 or a4 later on.}) 17. b4 a5 18. a3 Ra6 19. Rb1 axb4 20. axb4 Rfa8 $15 21. Ng3 Nd8 22. Bd2 f6 23. Nh4 Nf7 $15 (23... g6 24. Nf3 Nf7 $19) 24. Nhf5 Bf8 $17 *

