1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 Na5 {This move order is playable, but I suggest you stick to our move order.} 9. Bc2 c5 10. d4 Qc7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. h3 Be6 {Also a good option. The idea is that the bishop stays very well if White doesn't play d5 and Black wants to provoke d5. However, a tempo is a tempo even in a close position.} (12... Bd7 13. Nf1 Rfe8 14. Ng3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Rac8 $11) 13. d5 Bd7 14. Nf1 Rfb8 $5 {This a small example of how we shouldn't play. Black played a very passive game, and later on, he lost.} (14... c4 $1) (14... Nc4 $1 15. b3 Nb6 16. Ng3 c4 17. b4 a5 $11 {[%cal Yb6a4]}) 15. b3 c4 $2 {Black is worse.} 16. b4 Nb7 17. Be3 (17. a4 $1) 17... Ne8 {Wrong!} (17... a5 {That is a must move.} 18. a4 (18. a3 Ra6 19. Ng3 Rba8 20. Rb1 axb4 21. axb4 Ra2 $11 {A very important thing to remember is that we need to improve the position of the knight on b7.}) 18... axb4 19. cxb4 bxa4 $13) 18. a4 g6 19. g4 Nd8 {Preparing for the so-called Rubinstein plan for Black to protect his king.} 20. Qd2 f6 21. Ng3 Nf7 22. Kh2 Ng7 23. Rg1 Kh8 24. Ra2 Qc8 25. Rga1 Qe8 26. Qd1 h5 27. Nh4 Kh7 28. axb5 axb5 29. gxh5 g5 30. Ng6 Rxa2 31. Rxa2 Bd8 32. Ra7 Kg8 33. h4 Nh6 34. hxg5 fxg5 35. f3 Nxh5 36. Nxh5 Qxg6 37. Ng3 Bc8 38. Qa1 g4 39. f4 exf4 40. Bxf4 Bg5 41. Qc1 Nf7 42. Kg1 Bxf4 43. Qxf4 Ne5 44. Bd1 Bd7 45. Be2 Rf8 46. Qe3 Qf6 47. Kg2 Qg6 48. Ra6 Rf7 49. Ra8+ Kg7 50. Ra7 Qh6 51. Qxh6+ Kxh6 52. Ra6 Rf6 53. Rb6 Kg5 54. Nf1 Kf4 55. Ng3 Ke3 56. Rb7 Kd2 57. Nh5 Rh6 58. Nf4 Kxc3 59. Kg3 Kxb4 60. Rc7 Kc3 61. Ne6 Bxe6 62. dxe6 Rxe6 63. Bxc4 Nxc4 64. Rd7 Rxe4 0-1

