{A very instructive masterpiece. Pointing that in the endgame of a Rubinshtein maneuver game, a knight has a route to the a4 square! In particular: Ng7-e8-c7-a8-b6-a4. Always keep that in mind!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 Bd7 13. b3 Ne8 {Not a move that I would play. Remember here we play either Nb7 or g6.} (13... Nb7) (13... g6) 14. Nbd2 g6 15. Nf1 Ng7 16. Bh6 f6 (16... Nb7 17. g4 Rfb8 18. Qd2 c4 $1) 17. g4 Nb7 18. Ng3 Nd8 19. Kh1 Nf7 20. Be3 Kh8 (20... c4 $1 {Interesting and possible to play c4 here. White does have a4, but we exchange everything and push f5, which leads to a very unclear position.} 21. b4 a5 22. a4 axb4 23. cxb4 bxa4 24. Bxa4 f5 $36) 21. Rg1 c4 22. b4 a5 23. a3 axb4 24. axb4 Rxa1 25. Qxa1 Qb7 26. Qa7 $2 (26. Qb2 {White shouldn't play Qa7.} Ra8 27. Ra1 Ra6 $11) 26... Qxa7 27. Bxa7 Ra8 28. Be3 Ra3 $1 {Black starts to take over little by little.} 29. Bc1 Ra2 30. Ne1 Bd8 31. Be3 Ra3 $1 32. Bc1 Ra6 33. Kg2 (33. Be3 Bb6 34. Bxb6 Rxb6 35. Nf3 Ra6 $17) 33... Bb6 34. Rf1 Ra2 35. Bd2 Ne8 $1 36. Bc1 Kg7 $1 37. Bd2 Nc7 38. Bc1 Ba7 39. f3 Na8 40. Nh1 Nb6 41. Nf2 f5 $1 42. Nd1 h5 $1 43. gxh5 gxh5 44. Be3 f4 $1 45. Bf2 Ng5 46. Rh1 Kf7 47. Bh4 Nh7 48. Bf2 Nf6 49. Kf1 Nc8 50. Bh4 Ne7 51. Bg5 (51. Bf2 Bxf2 52. Kxf2 h4 53. Ke2 Nh5 54. Kd2 Ng3 55. Rh2 Ng6 (55... Nc8) 56. Kc1 Nf8 57. Kb1 Ra8 58. Kb2 Nh7 59. Nf2 Ng5) 51... Nh7 52. Bxe7 Kxe7 53. h4 Nf8 54. Ke2 Ng6 55. Kd2 Kf7 56. Ng2 Bb6 57. Kc1 Ra8 58. Kd2 Rg8 59. Ke2 Ne7 60. Ne1 Rg3 61. Nf2 Ng6 62. Bd1 Bd8 63. Kf1 Nxh4 {A very nice example of Black playing on both sides of the board. Little by little, creating more threats and winning the game at the end.} 64. Be2 Kg6 65. Rh2 Kg5 66. Rh1 Bb6 67. Rh2 Be3 68. Ng2 Nxf3 69. Bxf3 Rxf3 70. Ne1 Rg3 71. Ke2 Bxf2 72. Nf3+ Rxf3 73. Kxf3 Be1 74. Ke2 Bxc3 0-1

