{[%evp 0,124,31,30,15,11,25,4,16,13,-3,-61,-3,-62,-28,-8,8,-38,-23,-56,-14,-35,-19,4,-21,-13,35,26,17,32,19,13,42,27,69,58,87,72,75,68,64,58,58,49,49,21,46,-12,35,22,10,8,6,11,66,72,88,69,66,118,81,56,63,51,51,54,61,32,34,32,94,92,161,73,128,59,59,82,173,164,125,121,181,187,176,169,180,179,179,184,184,161,189,162,160,166,162,139,153,142,148,154,154,154,158,158,158,158,224,158,158,158,343,390,430,0,0,0,379,-98,-202,-154,-99,-401,-425,-541,-780]} 1. e4 {IN THIS GAME THAT COMES FROM A DIFFERENT MOVE ORDER, WE WILL SEE A SLIGHTLY DIFFERENT PLAN WHEN HEADING FOR THE RUBINSHTEIN MANEUVER! Black all of a sudden changes the idea and goes for the interesting plan of f6-Nf7-g6-Bh6, which is a rare occurrence.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2 d6 6. c3 Bd7 7. O-O Be7 8. Bb3 O-O 9. Rd1 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 b5 13. b3 Rfb8 $5 {[%mdl 4]} 14. Nbd2 Nb7 15. Nf1 Nd8 $146 {We follow the Rubinstein plan in closed positions of the Spanish where our knight can't use the c5 square.} 16. Ng3 Ne8 17. h3 Bf8 (17... g6 18. Nh2 Ng7 19. Ng4 Bxg4 {In a very closed position like this one giving up the bishop for the knight is good.} 20. Qxg4 Qc8 $132) 18. c4 f6 $5 19. Bd3 Nf7 20. Be3 g6 21. Rac1 (21. Qd2 Ng7 $132) 21... b4 22. Nh2 Bh6 23. Rf1 Ng7 24. f4 Bxf4 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Rxf4 Ne5 27. Rxf6 {Suddenly, something went wrong for Black, but still, Bh6 was a great idea.} Rf8 28. Rcf1 Rxf6 29. Rxf6 Qd8 30. Rf1 Qe7 31. Nf3 Rf8 {Still Black has some compensation for the pawn.} 32. Nxe5 Rxf1+ 33. Nxf1 Qxe5 34. Nh2 Nh5 35. Nf3 Qc3 36. Qc2 Qa1+ 37. Kf2 Nf4 38. Bf1 Qf6 39. Qd2 g5 40. Qe3 Ng6 41. Qxg5 Qxg5 42. Nxg5 a5 43. Nf3 a4 44. Bd3 Kg7 45. h4 h6 46. g3 Kf6 47. Ke3 a3 48. h5 Ne5 49. Nxe5 Kxe5 50. Be2 Be8 51. Bd1 Bf7 52. Be2 Bg8 53. Bd1 Bh7 54. Bf3 Bg8 55. g4 Bf7 56. g5 hxg5 57. h6 Bg6 58. Bg2 Kf6 59. e5+ Kxe5 60. Bh3 Bb1 61. Be6 Kf6 62. Bg8 Bxa2 0-1

