{[%evp 0,57,27,17,14,14,14,29,44,-4,3,11,13,13,13,2,13,-16,4,-14,22,22,23,-4,4,-1,38,16,27,16,31,21,27,4,5,-57,0,10,5,-9,0,-3,2,-19,51,41,130,131,173,176,266,169,266,29,291,297,1111,1982,2068,2493]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Be7 7. Re1 d6 8. c3 Na5 9. Bc2 c5 10. d4 Qc7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. d5 Re8 13. Nf1 Bd7 14. Ng3 c4 15. h3 Nb7 16. Nh2 Nc5 17. f4 a5 $3 {Be very careful !!!! When White often goes for the f2-f4 break, we do not take exf4, because that would give d4 square to his h2- knight. We rather go for a fast queenside attack and , surprisingly, we want to close the queenside with b4-b3 instead of opening it because he will be left with an eternally bad bishop on b1 and rook on a1 !!! Then little by little, we want to take over on the kingside!!!} 18. fxe5 (18. f5 $2 b4 $3 $17 19. Be3 (19. Rf1 Reb8 $1 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. Qxg4 Kh8 22. Qe2 b3 23. Bd1 (23. Bb1 $4 a4 24. f6 Bxf6 25. Rxf6 gxf6 26. Qf3 Qd8 $17)) 19... Reb8 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. Qxg4 Kh8 22. Qe2 b3 23. Bb1 a4 24. a3 (24. Rf1 a3) 24... g6 25. Rf1 Bh4 26. Qg4 Qd8 27. Ne2 h5 28. Qf3 Qf6 $17 29. Kh1 Rg8 $19) 18... dxe5 $15 19. Nf3 h6 $6 (19... b4 $3 $15 20. Qe2 b3 21. Bb1 Reb8 $3 22. Be3 (22. Qxc4 Bb5) 22... a4 23. a3 Nb7 $17) 20. Rf1 Bd6 $2 (20... Ra6 $1) 21. Nh4 $16 Qd8 22. Qf3 Rf8 23. Nhf5 Bxf5 24. Nxf5 Kh7 25. Bxh6 $1 Ne8 (25... gxh6 $1 26. Nxd6 Qxd6 27. Qxf6 Qxf6 28. Rxf6 $16) 26. Bxg7 $1 $18 Nxg7 27. Nxg7 Kxg7 28. Qg4+ Kh7 29. Rf5 1-0

